module.exports={"hotel-riu-palace-macao-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Palace Macao is an adults-only Dominican Republic all-inclusive in Punta Cana with a waterpark for older guests, spa, gym, nightclub, golf course, watersports, and swim-up bar at a premium price point. Hotel Riu Yucatan is a family-oriented Mexican all-inclusive in Playa del Carmen with a kids club, babysitting, waterpark for little kids, diving, and rooms that sleep five or more at a lower price tier. On ratings, Macao outscores Yucatan on food (7.1 vs 6.4), pool (7.1 vs 6.2), atmosphere (7.1 vs 6.5), room (8.5 vs 7.9), cleanliness (9.0 vs 8.7), and sleep quality (8.7 vs 8.3), while Yucatan edges it on overall score (8.6 vs 8.4). Macao is a quieter, more polished adults-only retreat with better rooms and a cleaner property; Yucatan trades some of that refinement for family infrastructure and a lower price. Both share a similar value score (8.5), but they serve fundamentally different travellers.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples or groups who want a premium, quieter Punta Cana all-inclusive with strong room quality, excellent cleanliness scores, a golf course, watersports, and a nightclub without the noise and energy of a family resort.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with young children who want a budget-friendlier Mexican all-inclusive near Playa del Carmen with a kids club, babysitting, diving program, rooms that sleep five or more, and a waterpark designed for little ones.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations are best visited between December and April when rainfall is lowest and humidity most manageable. Punta Cana's hurricane season peaks September to October, making Macao a riskier late-summer booking. Playa del Carmen shares a similar risk window, though both properties offer good value in the shoulder months of May and November before peak-season rates kick in.","activities":"At Macao, guests can windsurf, snorkel, rent watersports equipment, use the golf course, and access a waterpark suited to adults. At Yucatan, certified diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, and watersports rentals are available, with Playa del Carmen's famous Fifth Avenue shopping strip, cenote tours, and Mayan ruins at Tulum and Chichén Itzá all within reach for day excursions."},"bahia-principe-explore-jamaica-vs-bahia-principe-explore-tulum":{"keyDifferences":"Both resorts share the same Bahia Principe Explore branding and identical price tier, but Tulum outperforms Jamaica on nearly every measured dimension. Tulum's overall rating is a full 0.9 points higher (8.5 vs 7.6), with cleanliness (8.7 vs 8.3), service (8.5 vs 7.8), value (8.4 vs 7.7), and atmosphere (6.8 vs 6.3) all notably stronger. Room scores are close (8.2 vs 8.0) and food is essentially tied (6.5 vs 6.4), but the amenity gap is stark: Tulum offers a kids club, teen club, arcade, waterpark for little kids, gym, casino, nightclub, spa, babysitting, swim-up bar, diving, tennis, and a golf course, while Jamaica lists only beach access. Both score modestly on beach quality (5.5 Jamaica, 5.3 Tulum) and pool (6.5 vs 6.4), so neither excels on those fronts. For families at the same price point, Tulum delivers considerably more infrastructure, better service scores, and stronger overall satisfaction. Jamaica's edge is marginal: a slightly better beach rating and the inherent appeal of a Runaway Bay, Jamaica address.","whoShouldChooseA":"Guests who specifically want a Jamaica experience in Runaway Bay and can accept a more stripped-back resort with fewer on-site amenities. Best suited to couples or smaller families who are happy to self-direct their holiday and prioritize location and the Jamaican setting over organized programming.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a full-service Mexican all-inclusive with a wide amenity spread — kids club, teen club, waterpark, babysitting, spa, nightclub, casino, golf, and dive access — backed by strong service (8.5) and cleanliness (8.7) scores at the same price point as its Jamaica sibling.","whenToVisit":"Jamaica's Runaway Bay is best visited November through mid-December or January through April to avoid the Atlantic hurricane peak and summer heat. Tulum's Gran Bahia Principe area on the Riviera Maya shares a similar hurricane window; December through April offers the driest, most comfortable conditions. Both destinations are busiest and priciest over Christmas–New Year and spring break.","activities":"Jamaica's Runaway Bay sits near Green Grotto Caves, Dunn's River Falls, and local market towns, supplementing the resort's limited on-site offering with worthwhile day trips. Tulum's Gran Bahia Principe complex provides diving, tennis, a waterpark, and a golf course on property, while nearby cenotes, Tulum ruins, and Cobá are accessible for excursions. Both coasts offer snorkelling and watersports from the beach."},"hotel-riu-dunamar-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Dunamar and Hotel Riu Yucatan are both mid-to-upper-range Mexican family all-inclusives under the same brand, but they differ in location, room quality, and activity mix. Dunamar sits in the quieter Playa Mujeres area north of Cancun and scores notably higher on rooms (8.7 vs 7.9) and cleanliness (9.0 vs 8.7), while its standout amenity is a dual waterpark serving both big and little kids — something Yucatan lacks. Yucatan is positioned in Playa del Carmen, scoring higher on location (8.5 vs 7.9) and atmosphere (6.5 vs 6.2), with direct access to the town's famous 5th Avenue. Yucatan compensates for its missing waterpark with diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, and watersports rentals, plus rooms that sleep five or more people. Food ratings are nearly identical and equally modest at both properties (6.3 vs 6.4). Dunamar is the better pick for families wanting an on-site waterpark and superior room quality in a calm setting; Yucatan suits active families and larger groups who want watersports and a walkable resort town on their doorstep.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of mixed ages who want an on-site waterpark for both big and little kids, higher-rated rooms, and a cleaner, quieter Playa Mujeres setting away from the bustle of Playa del Carmen.","whoShouldChooseB":"Larger families needing rooms for five or more, and active families who want diving, snorkelling, and windsurfing built into their stay, paired with easy walking access to Playa del Carmen's shops, restaurants, and nightlife on 5th Avenue.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's dry season between December and April, when rainfall is low and temperatures are warm but not oppressive. Playa Mujeres and Playa del Carmen share the same Yucatan Peninsula climate, so hurricane season risk (June through November) applies equally to both. Peak school-holiday periods in July and August and around Christmas bring the highest prices at either property.","activities":"At Dunamar, the on-site dual waterpark, heated pool, swim-up bar, and nightclub keep most guests entertained without leaving the resort. Yucatan guests can add diving, snorkelling, and windsurfing to those same core amenities, and step off the property into Playa del Carmen for cenote excursions, Cozumel day trips by ferry, and the Xcaret and Xel-Ha eco-parks, all within easy reach."},"hotel-riu-palace-tropical-bay-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Palace Tropical Bay is a premium-priced Jamaican family all-inclusive on Negril's famous Seven Mile Beach, earning strong marks for beach (8.8), cleanliness (8.8), and service (8.7), with a notably higher food rating (7.0) than its counterpart. Hotel Riu Yucatan is a more affordable Mexican family all-inclusive near Playa del Carmen with a broader amenity set — nightclub, babysitting, snorkelling, windsurfing, waterpark for little kids — but lags meaningfully on food (6.4), pool (6.2), and atmosphere (6.5). Tropical Bay edges Yucatan on beach quality (8.8 vs 7.3) and food, while Yucatan matches it on value (8.5) at a lower price tier and adds watersports rentals, a waterpark, and babysitting that Tropical Bay lacks. Overall scores are close (8.4 vs 8.6), but the gap in pool and atmosphere ratings at Yucatan is notable. Choose Tropical Bay for a superior beach and dining experience in Jamaica at a premium price; choose Yucatan for a broader activity menu and lower spend in Mexico's Riviera Maya.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who prioritize a world-class beach, stronger dining, and a polished resort atmosphere in Jamaica and are willing to pay a premium price for it. The large-room option and tennis make it suitable for multi-generational groups who want quality over quantity of amenities.","whoShouldChooseB":"Budget-conscious families with young children who want the widest possible amenity spread — babysitting, a kids waterpark, windsurfing, snorkelling, and a nightclub — at a mid-range price point near Playa del Carmen's beaches and cenotes.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April. Negril's dry season runs roughly November to April, avoiding hurricane season. The Riviera Maya shares a similar dry window but benefits from slightly more consistent year-round weather. Avoid both properties during August and September when Atlantic hurricane risk is highest. Yucatan's shoulder months of May and early June offer lower rates before the rainy season intensifies.","activities":"Tropical Bay guests can dive, fish, play tennis, and unwind on Seven Mile Beach, with Negril's cliffside bars and Rick's Cafe a short trip away. Yucatan guests have snorkelling, windsurfing, and watersports rentals on-site, plus proximity to Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue, Tulum ruins, and the Riviera Maya's extensive cenote network — giving it a richer off-resort excursion menu."},"hotel-riu-cancun-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Cancun is an adults-only all-inclusive on Cancun's Hotel Zone strip, priced at the higher $$$$ tier, with a beach, swim-up bar, gym, diving, spa, and evening entertainment. Hotel Riu Yucatan is a family-oriented all-inclusive in Playa del Carmen, priced more accessibly at $$$, with a significantly broader amenity set: kids club, babysitting, waterpark for little kids, nightclub, snorkelling, windsurfing, watersports rentals, and rooms for five or more guests. The two resorts score identically on food (6.4) and beach (7.3), but Riu Cancun edges ahead on pool (6.6 vs 6.2) and atmosphere (6.7 vs 6.5), while Riu Yucatan leads slightly on overall score (8.6 vs 8.5), service (8.7 vs 8.6), and value (8.5 vs 8.4). Location scores are stronger at Cancun (8.8 vs 8.5), reflecting the Hotel Zone's immediate beach access. The core split is straightforward: Cancun is a quieter, pricier adults retreat; Yucatan is a busier, better-value family operation with considerably more programming for children.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults and couples who want a quieter, higher-end Cancun all-inclusive on the Hotel Zone strip with beach access, diving, a swim-up bar, and spa, without children present. The premium $$$$ price point buys a more serene atmosphere and a slightly stronger location score.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of any age who want a well-priced Playa del Carmen all-inclusive with a kids club, babysitting, waterpark, nightclub, snorkelling, and windsurfing. The $$$ price tier and rooms accommodating five or more guests make it especially practical for larger families on a budget.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula, sharing the same climate window. December through April offers dry, breezy conditions with the lowest humidity. May through October brings heat and the Atlantic hurricane season, with September and October carrying the highest risk. Late November and early December offer a quieter shoulder period with still-favourable weather at both properties.","activities":"At Riu Cancun, guests can dive directly from the resort or explore Cancun's Hotel Zone, with day trips to Chichen Itza, Isla Mujeres, and Xcaret easily arranged. At Riu Yucatan, Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue is walkable for shopping and dining, with snorkelling, windsurfing, and watersports on-site, plus close proximity to Tulum ruins, Xcaret eco-parks, and the cenote network of the Riviera Maya."},"hotel-riu-palace-punta-cana-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Palace Punta Cana and Hotel Riu Yucatan are both large family all-inclusives from the same chain, but they differ meaningfully on price, amenities, and ratings. Palace Punta Cana is the pricier option ($$$$) on a Dominican Republic beach, posting stronger scores for beach (7.8 vs 7.3), pool (7.1 vs 6.2), atmosphere (6.8 vs 6.5), rooms (8.5 vs 7.9), and food (7.0 vs 6.4). Yucatan is a notch cheaper ($$$) on Mexico's Riviera Maya near Playa del Carmen and edges ahead on overall rating (8.6 vs 8.4) and value (8.5 vs 8.4). Yucatan also carries a notably broader watersports program — diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, and equipment rentals — plus a nightclub, none of which Palace Punta Cana offers. Both have kids clubs, babysitting, swim-up bars, waterparks for little kids, and large-group rooms. If you want better rooms, a stronger beach, and a more polished pool experience at a higher price in the Dominican Republic, choose Palace Punta Cana. If you want more active watersports, a nightclub, and solid value in Mexico's Riviera Maya, choose Riu Yucatan.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families willing to pay a premium for noticeably better rooms, a stronger beach experience, and higher food and pool ratings in a classic Punta Cana setting. Also suits larger groups needing rooms for five or more who prioritize comfort and cleanliness over a packed watersports menu.","whoShouldChooseB":"Active families and groups who want a more affordable Dominican-style family resort experience on the Riviera Maya, with diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, and a nightclub added to the standard all-inclusive package — and don't mind slightly smaller rooms or a quieter pool area.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April when rainfall is lowest and crowds are highest. Punta Cana's hurricane season runs June through November, with September and October carrying the most risk. The Yucatan is similarly vulnerable to Atlantic storms through October. Shoulder months of May and late November offer better pricing at both properties with generally manageable weather.","activities":"At Punta Cana, guests can explore the resort's waterpark, take spa treatments, and join evening entertainment programs, with excursions to Saona Island and dune buggy tours nearby. At Riu Yucatan, on-site diving, snorkelling, and windsurfing fill active days, and the location near Playa del Carmen opens easy access to the Tulum ruins, Xcaret eco-park, and the cenotes of the Yucatan Peninsula."},"hotel-riu-palace-baja-california-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Palace Baja California is an adults-only resort on Mexico's Pacific coast, priced at $$$$ and earning standout scores for rooms (9.2), cleanliness (9.3), service (9.0), and value (8.8) — a polished, quieter retreat with a limited amenity list beyond no-reservation dining. Hotel Riu Yucatan is a family all-inclusive in Playa del Carmen on the Caribbean side, priced at $$$, loaded with amenities including a kids club, waterpark, nightclub, watersports, diving, and babysitting. Baja California scores higher on rooms, cleanliness, service, sleep quality, and value, while Yucatan beats it on overall rating (8.6 vs 8.3), beach (7.3 vs 6.0), pool (6.2 vs 7.1 — Baja California edges it here), and atmosphere (6.5 vs 7.2 — again Baja California leads). Baja California's beach rating of 6.0 is a notable weak point. If you want a refined, adults-only Pacific Mexico retreat with exceptional rooms and service at a premium price, choose Baja California. If you want a family-friendly Caribbean all-inclusive near Playa del Carmen with broad amenities at a lower price, choose Yucatan.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples or solo travelers seeking a quieter, upscale Pacific Mexico all-inclusive where polished rooms, attentive service, and cleanliness take priority over an extensive amenity list. Best suited to those who value a relaxed, crowd-free atmosphere and don't need a beach rated above average.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of all ages who want a well-priced Caribbean all-inclusive near Playa del Carmen with a kids club, waterpark, babysitting, watersports, nightclub, and large-group room options. A solid choice for those prioritizing amenity breadth and beach quality over room luxury.","whenToVisit":"Baja California's Los Cabos sits in a desert climate — dry and sunny year-round, with peak season November through April and hurricane risk low but present in late summer. Yucatan's Playa del Carmen has a tropical climate; visit December through April to avoid the June–October hurricane season and heavy humidity. Both see higher prices and crowds over Christmas and spring break.","activities":"At Baja California, guests are largely resort-bound, though nearby Cabo San Lucas offers whale watching (December–April), sport fishing, ATV tours, and the famous El Arco rock formation. At Yucatan in Playa del Carmen, snorkelling, diving, and watersports are on-site, and guests can easily access the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, cenotes, Tulum ruins, and the lively Fifth Avenue shopping and dining strip just outside the resort."},"hotel-riu-palace-antillas-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Palace Antillas is an adults-only Aruban all-inclusive on Palm-Eagle Beach, priced at the upper end ($$$$), with standout ratings for beach (8.5), location (8.9), service (8.8), and cleanliness (8.7), but notably weaker scores for pool (6.9) and food (7.0). Hotel Riu Yucatan is a family all-inclusive in Playa del Carmen priced a tier lower ($$$), with a higher overall rating (8.6 vs 8.1) and stronger value score (8.5 vs 8.3), but weaker food (6.4), pool (6.2), and beach (7.3) ratings. Antillas wins decisively on beach quality, room comfort (8.2 vs 7.9), and atmosphere, while Yucatan brings a fuller family amenity set including a kids club, waterpark, babysitting, nightclub, diving, windsurfing, and rooms for five-plus guests. Antillas suits couples wanting a premium Aruban beach experience; Yucatan suits families who need comprehensive programming at a lower price point in Mexico's Riviera Maya, despite its relatively underwhelming pool and food scores.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples or groups who want a premium, quiet Aruban beach holiday with excellent service (8.8), a prime Palm-Eagle Beach location (8.9), and comfortable rooms, and who are willing to pay more for a refined, adults-only atmosphere without the noise and logistics of a family resort.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of all ages who want a well-priced Riviera Maya all-inclusive with a kids club, waterpark, babysitting, nightclub, diving, and large-group rooms. Best for those who prioritize breadth of family amenities and value over beach quality or food ratings.","whenToVisit":"Aruba sits outside the hurricane belt, making Antillas a reliable year-round destination with consistent sunshine and trade winds; peak season runs December through April. Yucatan is best visited November through April to avoid the June-October hurricane season and summer heat and humidity in Playa del Carmen. Both resorts see higher prices and occupancy over Christmas and New Year.","activities":"Antillas guests enjoy calm Aruban waters for swimming and watersports, with Palm Beach's string of bars, restaurants, and shops walkable from the resort, plus island excursions to Arikok National Park and natural pools. Yucatan guests can access diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, and watersports on-site, with Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue shopping and dining strip nearby, and easy day trips to Tulum, Chichen Itza, and Xcaret eco-parks."},"hotel-riu-reggae-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Reggae is an adults-only all-inclusive in Jamaica's Rose Hall area, priced at $$$$ with standout scores for cleanliness (9.0), service (8.8), and rooms (8.6), but notably weak beach (5.3) and food (6.5) ratings. Hotel Riu Yucatan is a family-oriented all-inclusive in Playa del Carmen, Mexico, priced at $$$, with a meaningfully better beach score (7.3 vs 5.3), a kids club, waterpark, babysitting, diving, windsurfing, and rooms that sleep 5+. Yucatan's overall rating edges slightly higher (8.6 vs 8.4) despite costing less. Reggae wins on room quality (8.6 vs 7.9), cleanliness (9.0 vs 8.7), and the adults-only atmosphere that justifies its premium price. Both resorts score identically on atmosphere (6.5) and similarly on food (6.5 vs 6.4), suggesting neither excels at the table. If you want a quieter, cleaner, adults-only Jamaican retreat in Rose Hall with excellent service and no children, go to Riu Reggae. If you want a family-friendly Mexican all-inclusive with a real beach, watersports, and kids programming at a lower price point, go to Riu Yucatan.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples or solo travelers who want a premium, child-free Jamaican all-inclusive in Rose Hall with excellent service, very clean facilities, and comfortable rooms, and who are willing to trade a weaker beach for guaranteed peace and quiet.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of any age who want a well-priced Mexican all-inclusive on a solid Playa del Carmen beach with a kids club, waterpark, babysitting, diving, and large rooms that can accommodate groups of five or more.","whenToVisit":"Jamaica's Rose Hall enjoys warm weather year-round; avoid September and October when hurricane risk peaks. Playa del Carmen's peak season runs December through April, offering dry, comfortable conditions. Both destinations share a similar Atlantic hurricane exposure window, so July through October carries elevated weather risk at either resort regardless of which you choose.","activities":"Riu Reggae guests are close to Rose Hall's historic great house tours, Montego Bay's Hip Strip, and standard resort watersports. Riu Yucatan guests have considerably more on offer: on-site diving, windsurfing, and watersports rentals complement easy access to Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue, nearby cenotes, Tulum ruins, and Cozumel ferry connections, making Yucatan the stronger base for guests who want to explore beyond the resort gates."},"hotel-riu-vallarta-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Vallarta and Hotel Riu Yucatan are both Mexican family all-inclusives in the Riu chain with identical food scores (6.4) and atmosphere scores (6.5), but Yucatan edges ahead on overall rating (8.6 vs 8.2), beach (7.3 vs 6.8), cleanliness (8.7 vs 8.6), and service (8.7 vs 8.6), while coming in at a lower price tier ($$$  vs $$$$). Vallarta is in Nuevo Nayarit on the Pacific coast with a strong location score (8.2) and superior room ratings (8.2 vs 7.9), but its amenity list is thin — only no-reservation dining is noted. Yucatan, near Playa del Carmen on the Riviera Maya, offers a substantially richer amenity set: kids club, babysitting, waterpark for little kids, swim-up bar, nightclub, spa, gym, diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, watersports rentals, evening entertainment, and rooms for five or more guests. For families who need programming and amenities, Yucatan delivers more at a lower price. Vallarta suits those drawn to the Pacific coast who prioritize cleaner, quieter surroundings and don't need a packed activity roster.","whoShouldChooseA":"Guests who prefer Mexico's Pacific coast setting in Nuevo Nayarit and value strong room quality (8.2), cleanliness (8.6), and service (8.6) over a broad amenity list. Best for families or couples who want a quieter Riu experience without needing a kids club or organized activities.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of all ages who want a feature-rich Riviera Maya all-inclusive with a kids club, babysitting, waterpark, swim-up bar, nightclub, diving, and rooms that sleep five or more — all at a lower price point than Vallarta and with a higher overall rating of 8.6.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's dry season running roughly December through April. Vallarta on the Pacific coast sees its rainy season June through October, with hurricane risk lower than the Caribbean. Yucatan near Playa del Carmen sits in the Caribbean hurricane belt, making June through November riskier. For either property, January through March offers the most reliable weather with peak-season pricing to match.","activities":"Yucatan guests can dive, snorkel, windsurf, and rent watersports equipment on-site, plus explore the Riviera Maya's cenotes, Tulum ruins, and Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue nearby. Vallarta sits near the Sierra Madre foothills in Nuevo Nayarit, with access to whale-watching tours seasonally, zip-lining, and the beaches and marina of Nuevo Vallarta and Puerto Vallarta a short drive away."},"hotel-riu-emerald-bay-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Emerald Bay and Hotel Riu Yucatan are both Mexican family all-inclusives under the same brand, but they differ meaningfully in price, location, and guest experience. Emerald Bay is a pricier $$$$-tier property with stronger room (8.4 vs 7.9) and value (8.4 vs 8.5, nearly identical despite the higher price tier) scores, suggesting a more upscale physical product, though its beach rating of 6.3 trails Yucatan's 7.3 noticeably. Yucatan sits in Playa del Carmen at $$$, carries a higher overall rating (8.6 vs 8.0), and edges out on atmosphere (6.5 vs 6.2), service (8.7 vs 8.5), and beach quality. Yucatan also lists a more explicit amenity set including a waterpark for little kids, babysitting, windsurfing, diving, nightclub, and rooms for five or more guests, making its family credentials clearer. Both resorts score similarly on food (6.3–6.4) and cleanliness (8.7). Yucatan delivers better overall guest satisfaction at a lower price point, while Emerald Bay offers nicer rooms in a less-established beach setting.","whoShouldChooseA":"Guests who prioritize well-appointed rooms and are willing to pay a premium for a higher-tier Riu property, and are less concerned about beach quality or a packed family amenity list. Better suited to couples or families who want comfort and value in a quieter Mexican setting.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with young children who want a full amenity lineup — babysitting, a kids waterpark, nightclub, diving, and windsurfing — in Playa del Carmen, one of Mexico's most accessible and lively resort corridors, at a more affordable price point with stronger overall guest ratings.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's dry season, roughly December through April, when rainfall is minimal and temperatures are warm without being oppressive. Playa del Carmen at Riu Yucatan can get busier during North American spring break in March. Emerald Bay's location on the Pacific-facing Sinaloa coast means a different weather pattern; avoid the late-summer hurricane and storm season, particularly August through October, at both properties.","activities":"Riu Yucatan's Playa del Carmen location puts guests close to the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef for world-class diving and snorkelling, Mayan ruins at Tulum and Cobá, cenote swimming, and the shopping and nightlife of Fifth Avenue. On-site, guests can use watersports equipment, the kids waterpark, and the nightclub. Emerald Bay's Mazatlán-area setting offers sport fishing, historic old-town Mazatlán, and resort-based watersports, though the surrounding attraction density is lower than Playa del Carmen."},"hotel-riu-palace-costa-rica-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Palace Costa Rica is a premium-priced ($$$$ vs $$$) family all-inclusive in Sardinal, Costa Rica, with waterpark facilities for both young and older kids, a pool slide, and a water feature, but it underperforms on beach (5.0 vs 7.3) and pool (7.1 vs 6.2 — though here Riu Palace actually edges ahead). Riu Yucatan sits in Playa del Carmen, Mexico, a far more established resort corridor, and its beach rating of 7.3 versus Riu Palace Costa Rica's 5.0 is the single biggest gap between these two properties. Yucatan adds a considerably broader amenity set — spa, nightclub, swim-up bar, diving, windsurfing, snorkelling, evening entertainment, babysitting, and rooms for five or more guests — at a lower price tier, while Riu Palace Costa Rica's edge is its more polished room score (8.4 vs 7.9), cleanliness parity, and a waterpark setup for big kids that Yucatan lacks. Overall ratings are close: 8.4 versus 8.6, with Yucatan narrowly ahead on location (8.5 vs 8.2). For a beachfront experience, Yucatan wins clearly; for waterpark infrastructure and room quality at the expense of beach and amenity breadth, Riu Palace Costa Rica holds its ground.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who prioritize strong room quality (8.4), excellent service (8.8), and a dedicated waterpark for both young and older kids, and who are drawn to Costa Rica's natural setting even if the beach rating (5.0) is a clear trade-off against the higher price tier.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a significantly better beach (7.3), a wider amenity spread — swim-up bar, spa, nightclub, diving, snorkelling, babysitting, and rooms for five-plus — at a lower price point in the well-connected Playa del Carmen corridor of Mexico.","whenToVisit":"Riu Palace Costa Rica's Sardinal location sits in Guanacaste, where the dry season runs December through April — the clearest skies and calmest seas for that region. Riu Yucatan in Playa del Carmen benefits from a longer comfortable window of November through May, avoiding the Atlantic hurricane season peak of August to October. Both properties suit a Christmas or spring-break family trip, but Playa del Carmen carries lower weather risk across a broader travel window.","activities":"Riu Palace Costa Rica guests can explore Guanacaste's national parks, zip-lining, and wildlife tours, while on-site waterpark slides and kids facilities keep younger guests occupied. Riu Yucatan guests can dive and snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef, windsurf, and rent watersports equipment on a strong beach, then access Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue dining and nightlife, plus day trips to Tulum, Chichen Itza, and Xcaret eco-parks within easy reach."},"hotel-riu-lupita-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Both Hotel Riu Lupita and Hotel Riu Yucatan are family all-inclusives in Playa del Carmen at the same price level, but they diverge significantly on amenities and several key ratings. Riu Yucatan scores a 7.3 on beach versus Lupita's striking 2.5, and leads on location (8.5 vs 7.0), atmosphere (6.5 vs 5.8), food (6.4 vs 5.9), and sleep quality (8.3 vs 7.8). Yucatan also carries a far broader amenity set: kids club, waterpark, babysitting, spa, nightclub, swim-up bar, diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, and evening entertainment, compared to Lupita's beach-only listing. Lupita holds a marginal edge on neither rating category in a meaningful way, though both share identical value and cleanliness scores. For families who need a full-service resort with a proper beach and kids programming, Yucatan is the clear step up. Lupita may suit guests prioritizing simplicity at the same price, but its very low beach and pool scores are hard to overlook.","whoShouldChooseA":"Guests who want a straightforward, clean, and well-serviced Playa del Carmen all-inclusive without the crowds of a large resort complex, and who are less reliant on beach quality or structured kids programming as part of their stay.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a full-featured Playa del Carmen all-inclusive with a strong beach score (7.3), kids club, babysitting, waterpark, spa, nightclub, diving, and snorkelling — and are willing to pay the same price for a significantly broader experience.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in Playa del Carmen, where peak season runs December through April with dry, sunny weather and high demand — book well in advance. May through November brings lower rates and quieter crowds, though June to October carries hurricane season risk. The shoulder months of November and late April offer a practical balance of good weather and better availability.","activities":"Both resorts place guests within reach of Playa del Carmen's 5th Avenue for shopping, dining, and nightlife. The nearby Mesoamerican Barrier Reef supports world-class diving and snorkelling, with Cozumel a short ferry ride away. Chichen Itza, Tulum's clifftop ruins, and the cenotes of the Riviera Maya are all accessible as day trips, and Xcaret and Xel-Ha eco-parks sit close by for families seeking structured excursions."},"hotel-riu-palace-aruba-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Palace Aruba and Hotel Riu Yucatan are both family-oriented Riu properties, but they diverge meaningfully on price, amenities, and setting. Riu Palace Aruba sits at a higher price tier ($$$$) with a standout beach score of 8.5 and location rating of 8.9, reflecting Aruba's famous white-sand coastline and reliably calm waters. However, it lags on food (7.0), pool (6.9), and atmosphere (6.9), and its amenity list is notably thin — restaurants not requiring reservations is the only listed feature. Riu Yucatan costs less ($$$), scores higher overall (8.6 vs 8.2), and comes loaded with amenities: kids club, waterpark, babysitting, swim-up bar, nightclub, diving, watersports, spa, and rooms for 5+ guests. Its weaknesses are a lower beach score (7.3 vs 8.5), weaker pool rating (6.2), and the lowest food score of the two at 6.4. Aruba wins on beach quality and location; Yucatan wins on value, activity breadth, and family infrastructure.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples or families who prioritize an exceptional beach and a premium Aruban setting over amenity breadth. Those willing to pay a higher price for Aruba's iconic turquoise water, reliably sunny climate, and a well-located resort where the beach itself is the main event.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with young children who want maximum programming at a lower price point — kids club, babysitting, waterpark, nightclub, diving, and rooms that sleep five or more make this a strong choice for larger families seeking activity-heavy value in the Playa del Carmen area.","whenToVisit":"Aruba sits outside the hurricane belt, making Riu Palace Aruba viable year-round with consistent sun and low rainfall; December through April is peak season. Riu Yucatan in Playa del Carmen is best visited November through April to avoid the June–October hurricane season and summer humidity. Both properties see higher rates and fuller occupancy during North American school holidays.","activities":"Riu Palace Aruba guests can enjoy world-class windsurfing and kitesurfing on Aruba's trade-wind-swept coast, explore Arikok National Park, and visit the island's casino strip. Riu Yucatan guests have onsite diving, snorkelling, watersports rentals, and a waterpark, plus proximity to Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue, Cozumel ferry, Tulum ruins, and cenote swimming — a far richer roster of off-property excursions."},"hotel-riu-palace-bavaro-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Palace Bavaro and Hotel Riu Yucatan are both family all-inclusives from the same chain, but they diverge on price tier, amenity depth, and who they serve best. Riu Palace Bavaro sits at a higher price point ($$$$) in the Dominican Republic's Bavaro area, with stronger beach (7.8 vs 7.3) and pool (7.1 vs 6.2) ratings and a waterpark geared to older kids, but a notably weaker food score (7.0 vs 6.4 is actually closer than it looks — both underwhelm). Riu Yucatan is a more affordable ($$$) Mexico option in Playa del Carmen with a significantly higher overall rating (8.6 vs 8.1), better cleanliness (8.7 vs 8.5), service (8.7 vs 8.4), and value (8.5 vs 8.2), plus a far broader amenity set: kids club, babysitting, swim-up bar, nightclub, spa, diving, windsurfing, snorkelling, and rooms for five or more guests. Riu Palace Bavaro wins on beach and pool experience; Riu Yucatan wins on nearly everything else, at a lower price.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples who prioritize a strong beach and pool setting in the Dominican Republic and are willing to pay a premium for the Palace-tier experience, including a waterpark for older kids, without needing a full slate of organized amenities like a kids club or nightclub.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with younger children who want maximum amenities at a lower price point in Mexico's Playa del Carmen, including a kids club, babysitting, swim-up bar, nightclub, spa, watersports, and large rooms that sleep five or more guests.","whenToVisit":"Bavaro's peak season runs December through April when trade winds keep humidity low; May through November brings heat and hurricane risk. Playa del Carmen is best from November through April, with the driest and coolest conditions; summer months are hot and humid with occasional tropical storms. Both destinations see inflated pricing around Christmas and New Year, so late January through March offers the best balance of good weather and manageable rates.","activities":"At Riu Palace Bavaro, guests can enjoy the beach, pools, and an on-site waterpark for older kids, with Bavaro's busy resort strip offering excursions to Saona Island and zip-lining nearby. At Riu Yucatan, the activity roster is broader on property — diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, and watersports rentals — while Playa del Carmen's location puts guests within easy reach of cenotes, Tulum ruins, and the Riviera Maya's extensive reef system."},"hotel-riu-playa-blanca-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Playa Blanca sits on Panama's Pacific coast at El Farallon del Chiru, a remote setting that rewards guests who want to escape the crowds but comes with trade-offs: beach rates 6.5, pool 6.0, atmosphere 6.1, and food 6.3, all notably low. Its standout numbers are room quality (8.5), cleanliness (8.5), and value (8.4), suggesting a well-maintained property where rooms over-deliver for the price. Hotel Riu Yucatan, positioned in Playa del Carmen on Mexico's Riviera Maya, posts a stronger overall score of 8.6 versus Playa Blanca's 7.9, with better beach (7.3 vs 6.5), atmosphere (6.5 vs 6.1), service (8.7 vs 8.3), sleep quality (8.3 vs 7.9), and cleanliness (8.7 vs 8.5). Yucatan also brings a dramatically wider amenity set: kids club, babysitting, waterpark, swim-up bar, diving, watersports, nightclub, spa, and rooms for five or more guests, compared to Playa Blanca's near-bare amenity list. Playa Blanca's edge is its rooms score (8.5 vs 7.9) and the novelty of a Pacific Panama beach; Yucatan wins on nearly every other measurable dimension.","whoShouldChooseA":"Travelers who want a quiet, off-the-beaten-path Pacific Panama escape where well-appointed rooms and strong cleanliness and service scores outweigh a limited amenity offering. Best for couples or small families comfortable with fewer structured activities and a remote, less-developed beach environment.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of all ages who want a fully loaded Riviera Maya all-inclusive with a kids club, babysitting, waterpark, swim-up bar, nightclub, spa, and diving, backed by strong service (8.7) and cleanliness (8.7) scores, in one of the Caribbean's most accessible resort destinations.","whenToVisit":"Playa Blanca's Pacific Panama location is best from December through April during Panama's dry season, when Pacific swells and rainfall are minimal. Riu Yucatan in Playa del Carmen benefits from the same broad dry-season window, roughly November through April, before the Caribbean hurricane season peaks between August and October. Both resorts share a similar high-season pricing pattern over the Christmas and New Year period.","activities":"At Riu Yucatan guests can dive, snorkel, windsurf, and rent watersports equipment directly on the Riviera Maya, while Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue, Xcaret, Xel-Ha, and the Tulum ruins are all within easy reach. Riu Playa Blanca's remote Pacific setting limits organized on-site activity options, but guests can explore Panama City, transit canal viewpoints, and uncrowded Pacific surf beaches nearby."},"hotel-riu-montego-bay-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Montego Bay is an adults-only Jamaican all-inclusive in Ironshore priced at $$$$ with standout room quality (8.2), cleanliness (8.5), service (8.5), and sleep quality (8.3), but a notably weak beach score (5.3) and modest food rating (6.3). Hotel Riu Yucatan is a family-oriented Mexican all-inclusive near Playa del Carmen priced at $$$ with a stronger overall score (8.6 vs 8.1), better beach (7.3 vs 5.3), superior value (8.5 vs 8.1), and higher cleanliness and service scores (8.7 each), though its pool rating (6.2) edges below Montego Bay's (6.5). Yucatan adds a kids club, babysitting, waterpark for little kids, diving, windsurfing, and rooms for five or more guests — a far broader amenity set. Montego Bay commands a premium price for a quieter adults-only experience with well-appointed rooms, while Yucatan delivers more activity coverage and a better beach at a lower price point. For beach quality, family infrastructure, and value, Yucatan wins clearly; for a refined, child-free retreat with strong room comfort, Montego Bay holds its ground.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults seeking a quieter, child-free Jamaican all-inclusive with well-appointed rooms, strong service, and good sleep quality, and who are willing to pay a premium despite a below-average beach and are not prioritising an extensive activity program.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of any age who want a well-priced Mexican all-inclusive near Playa del Carmen with a solid beach, kids club, babysitting, waterpark, diving, windsurfing, nightclub, and large rooms that sleep five or more.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April. Jamaica's Ironshore area avoids the worst of hurricane season by October, though deals emerge September to November. Mexico's Yucatan coast near Playa del Carmen is best November through May; June through October brings heat, humidity, and hurricane risk. Both resorts offer best value in early December before holiday surcharges kick in.","activities":"Riu Yucatan guests have the fuller on-site menu: diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, watersports rentals, a small waterpark, and a nightclub, with Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue shops, cenotes, and Tulum day trips nearby. Riu Montego Bay guests are close to Montego Bay's Hip Strip, Dunn's River Falls excursions, and river rafting, with snorkelling and watersports available through the resort and local operators."},"hotel-riu-guanacaste-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Guanacaste is a Costa Rican family all-inclusive priced at $$$$ with a notably weak beach score (5.0) and modest pool rating (6.4), but strong room (8.1), cleanliness (8.5), and service (8.3) scores. Its amenity list is sparse — restaurants without reservations is the only listed feature. Hotel Riu Yucatan is a $$$-priced family all-inclusive on the Playa del Carmen strip in Mexico with a considerably higher overall rating (8.6 vs. 7.9), a much better beach score (7.3 vs. 5.0), better value (8.5 vs. 8.0), superior service (8.7 vs. 8.3), and a dense amenity set including a kids club, waterpark, nightclub, spa, swim-up bar, babysitting, watersports, snorkelling, windsurfing, and diving. Yucatan wins on nearly every measurable dimension at a lower price point. Guanacaste's only meaningful edge is its Costa Rica setting for travelers specifically seeking that destination. If the country of travel is flexible, Yucatan is the stronger all-inclusive proposition on almost every metric.","whoShouldChooseA":"Travelers with a firm preference for Costa Rica who prioritize clean, comfortable rooms and attentive service over beach quality or breadth of amenities, and who are willing to pay a premium for the Guanacaste destination itself rather than the resort's standalone offerings.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a well-rounded, amenity-rich Playa del Carmen all-inclusive at a lower price point, with kids club, babysitting, waterpark, spa, nightclub, watersports, and a strong beach — backed by some of the highest service and cleanliness scores in its category.","whenToVisit":"Guanacaste's dry season runs December through April, making those months ideal; the rainy season from May to November brings lush landscapes but afternoon downpours. Playa del Carmen is best visited November through April, when humidity drops and hurricane risk is lowest. Both destinations share a similar peak winter window, so book early if traveling during the December–January holiday period.","activities":"At Riu Yucatan, guests can dive, snorkel, windsurf, and rent watersports equipment directly from the beach, with a waterpark on-site for young children and evening entertainment and a nightclub after dark. Near Playa del Carmen, Tulum ruins, Xcaret eco-park, and numerous cenotes are easy day trips. Riu Guanacaste's listed amenities are limited, but the Guanacaste region offers zip-lining, volcano tours, wildlife watching, and ATV excursions for active families willing to venture off-resort."},"hotel-riu-ventura-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Ventura and Hotel Riu Yucatan are both family all-inclusives in Mexico under the same brand, carrying identical overall ratings of 8.6 and near-identical food scores (6.3 vs 6.4). The clearest split is in beach quality: Yucatan scores a notably higher 7.3 versus Ventura's 5.8, a meaningful gap that reflects Playa del Carmen's stronger beach reputation over Cancun's hotel zone. Yucatan also edges ahead on atmosphere (6.5 vs 6.1) and pool (6.2 vs 5.7). Ventura counters with superior room ratings (8.8 vs 7.9), suggesting newer or better-appointed accommodations, and carries a higher price point ($$$$  vs $$$). Yucatan's amenity list is considerably broader, adding a spa, nightclub, diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, watersports rentals, babysitting, a waterpark for young children, and rooms that sleep five or more. Ventura's distinguishing amenity is an adult pool and access to a golf course. In short, Yucatan delivers more beach, more activities, and more value per dollar; Ventura delivers nicer rooms and a quieter, slightly more upscale feel in Cancun.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples who want nicer rooms in Cancun's hotel zone and appreciate the convenience of a dedicated adult pool and nearby golf. Those willing to pay a premium for better room quality and a quieter atmosphere, and who are less focused on beach ratings or a wide activity roster.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with young children who want a stronger beach, a waterpark, babysitting, and a full activity program including diving, snorkelling, and windsurfing on the Playa del Carmen coast. Those who also want a nightclub and spa, and who prioritize value without sacrificing meaningful amenities.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the same regional climate. December through April offers dry, sunny weather with lower humidity across the Yucatán Peninsula and Cancun corridor — the peak season and most expensive window. May and June are transitional, warm but manageable. Hurricane season runs June through November, with September and October carrying the highest storm risk. Shoulder months of May and early December offer the best balance of good weather and lower rates at both properties.","activities":"At Ventura, guests can use the adult pool, gym, and evening entertainment program, with golf course access nearby in Cancun's hotel zone. At Yucatan, the activity list is substantially longer: diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, watersports rentals, and a waterpark for young children on-site, plus Playa del Carmen's 5th Avenue shopping strip, cenote excursions, Tulum ruins, and the eco-parks of Xcaret and Xel-Há all within easy reach."},"hotel-riu-ocho-rios-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Ocho Rios is a family beach all-inclusive on Jamaica's north coast in Ocho Rios, rated overall 8.0, with strong scores for location (8.2), rooms (8.2), cleanliness (8.5), and service (8.3), but a notably thin amenity list — beach access and little else documented. Hotel Riu Yucatan is a family all-inclusive near Playa del Carmen in Mexico's Riviera Maya, rated overall 8.6, with better value (8.5 vs 8.0), cleanliness (8.7), and service (8.7), and a dramatically broader amenity set: kids club, babysitting, waterpark for little kids, swim-up bar, nightclub, spa, gym, diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, watersports rentals, evening entertainment, and rooms for five or more guests. Both resorts score similarly on food (6.3 vs 6.4) and beach (7.3 vs 7.3), so neither has an edge there. Riu Yucatan also comes in at a lower price tier ($$$ vs $$$$), making the amenity gap even more striking. If you want a quieter Jamaican beach stay with strong service and rooms at a premium price, go to Riu Ocho Rios. If you want a well-priced Mexican family all-inclusive with extensive kids programming, watersports, nightlife, and spa facilities near Playa del Carmen, go to Riu Yucatan.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples or smaller families who prioritize a well-kept Jamaican beach setting with strong room quality, attentive service, and a quieter atmosphere, and who don't need an extensive on-site activity program to feel they're getting value.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families of all sizes, including large groups needing rooms for five or more, who want a well-priced Riviera Maya all-inclusive with a kids club, babysitting, waterpark, watersports, spa, and nightclub all under one roof.","whenToVisit":"Ocho Rios is best November through mid-December or February through April, avoiding Jamaica's peak hurricane season (August–October) and the busy Christmas period. Playa del Carmen is most reliable December through April, when rainfall is lowest and temperatures are warm without the humidity of summer. Both destinations see elevated prices over Christmas and New Year.","activities":"Ocho Rios guests can visit Dunn's River Falls, take ATV tours into the Blue Mountains, go dolphin swimming, or explore local craft markets a short drive from the resort. Playa del Carmen guests can snorkel or dive the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, visit Mayan ruins at Tulum or Chichen Itza, explore the cenotes inland, or walk the shops and restaurants of Quinta Avenida, all easily accessible from the resort's strong location."},"hotel-riu-santa-fe-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Santa Fe and Hotel Riu Yucatan are both mid-to-upper-range Mexican family all-inclusives under the same brand, but they differ significantly across nearly every rated dimension. Riu Yucatan scores a full point higher overall (8.6 vs 7.6) and leads on beach (7.3 vs 4.5, a massive 2.8-point gap), service (8.7 vs 8.1), sleep quality (8.3 vs 7.8), and cleanliness (8.7 vs 8.5). Santa Fe edges ahead only on pool (6.9 vs 6.2) and room ratings (8.1 vs 7.9). Amenity coverage tells a similar story: Yucatan offers a kids club, babysitting, waterpark for little kids, nightclub, spa, diving, windsurfing, snorkelling, swim-up bar, and rooms for five-plus guests, while Santa Fe lists only no-reservation dining. Yucatan sits in Playa del Carmen with a clearly superior beach, while Santa Fe's weaker beach score (4.5) is its most glaring liability. For families who care about beach quality, activities, and service, Yucatan is the stronger choice at the same price tier.","whoShouldChooseA":"Guests who prioritize comfortable rooms and value in a convenient Mexican location and are less concerned about beach quality or extensive on-site amenities. A reasonable pick for travellers who plan to spend more time off-property exploring than on the sand.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with young children who want a well-rounded Playa del Carmen all-inclusive with a strong beach (7.3), kids club, babysitting, waterpark, nightclub, spa, and watersports, all backed by notably high service (8.7) and cleanliness (8.7) scores.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the same broad Mexican Caribbean and Baja window. December through April brings dry, sunny weather with lower humidity. Summer months are warm but carry hurricane-season risk from June through October, with September being the peak of storm activity. Shoulder months of May and November offer better pricing with generally manageable weather at both properties.","activities":"Riu Yucatan guests have access to diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, and watersports rentals on a solid beach in Playa del Carmen, with the Quinta Avenida strip, Cozumel ferry, and Tulum ruins all within easy reach. Riu Santa Fe guests are better positioned for excursions into Los Cabos, whale watching seasonally, and ATV or desert tours, though on-property activity infrastructure is comparatively limited."},"hotel-riu-jalisco-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Jalisco and Hotel Riu Yucatan are both Mexican family all-inclusives from the same chain, but they differ meaningfully in amenity breadth, price, and guest satisfaction. Yucatan sits in Playa del Carmen and carries a significantly stronger overall rating (8.6 vs 7.8), with notable advantages in beach (7.3 vs 6.5), cleanliness (8.7 vs 8.3), service (8.7 vs 8.2), sleep quality (8.3 vs 7.9), and value (8.5 vs 8.0), all at a lower price point ($$$  vs $$$$). Yucatan also offers a far broader amenity set: kids club, babysitting, swim-up bar, nightclub, spa, gym, diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, watersports rentals, and evening entertainment. Jalisco's amenity list is notably thin by comparison, with only no-reservation dining and a small kids waterpark confirmed. Jalisco does edge Yucatan on location rating (8.0 vs 8.5 going to Yucatan), but that gap favors Yucatan. In nearly every measurable category, Riu Yucatan outperforms Riu Jalisco while costing less.","whoShouldChooseA":"Guests already committed to the Jalisco Pacific coast destination who want a Riu family property with easy dining and a small kids waterpark. Best suited to families who prioritize location convenience in that specific region over amenity depth or overall resort quality scores.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want the best overall Riu experience for the money, with a strong beach, kids club, babysitting, spa, nightclub, and watersports all included at a lower price tier. Ideal for those heading to the Riviera Maya who want broad programming and consistently high service ratings.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Mexico's dry season, roughly December through April, when rain is minimal and humidity is lower. Playa del Carmen at Riu Yucatan sits in hurricane-season territory (June through November), so late summer and fall carry more weather risk. Jalisco on the Pacific coast has its own wet season peaking July through September. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates with generally acceptable conditions at both properties.","activities":"Riu Yucatan's Playa del Carmen location puts guests close to the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef for world-class diving and snorkelling, Tulum ruins, cenote swimming, and the lively 5th Avenue restaurant and nightlife strip. The resort itself covers diving, windsurfing, and watersports rentals on-site. Riu Jalisco guests are positioned on the Pacific coast, with access to Puerto Vallarta's old town, whale watching seasonally, sport fishing, and zip-lining in the Sierra Madre foothills nearby."},"hotel-riu-negril-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Negril is a family all-inclusive on Jamaica's famous Seven Mile Beach in Negril, rated 7.9 overall at a higher $$$$ price point, with a standout beach score of 8.3 but a notably thin amenity list compared to its competitor. Hotel Riu Yucatan is a family all-inclusive in Playa del Carmen, Mexico, rated 8.6 overall at a more accessible $$$ price point, with a broader amenity set including a kids club, waterpark for little kids, nightclub, spa, gym, diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, swim-up bar, babysitting, and evening entertainment. Riu Yucatan outscores Riu Negril on overall rating (8.6 vs 7.9), cleanliness (8.7 vs 8.5), service (8.7 vs 8.3), value (8.5 vs 8), and location (8.5 vs 7.9). Riu Negril's clear advantage is its beach score (8.3 vs 7.3), sleep quality (8.1 vs 8.3 is close), and room score (8 vs 7.9). For families wanting amenity depth and better overall value, Yucatan wins decisively; for guests prioritising a superior beach in a Jamaican setting, Negril holds its own.","whoShouldChooseA":"Guests who prioritise a premium Jamaican beach experience above all else and are willing to pay more for Negril's iconic Seven Mile Beach setting, accepting a leaner amenity list in exchange for outstanding sand, good sleep quality, and clean, well-rated rooms.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want maximum amenity coverage at a lower price point, including a kids club, waterpark, babysitting, spa, nightclub, and watersports, alongside high service and cleanliness scores in a well-located Playa del Carmen setting on the Mexican Caribbean.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak in winter. Negril is best from December through April, when Jamaica's dry season keeps conditions ideal and humidity manageable; avoid September and October during hurricane season. Playa del Carmen is similarly best December through April, though its shoulder months of May and November offer good value with fewer crowds. Both carry hurricane risk from August through October.","activities":"At Riu Negril, the beach is the primary draw, with Seven Mile Beach stretching directly in front of the property; local operators offer snorkelling, catamaran trips, and cliff diving nearby. Riu Yucatan guests have on-site diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, and a waterpark, plus proximity to Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue for shopping and dining, and easy access to Tulum, Chichen Itza, and cenote tours from the Riviera Maya."},"hotel-riu-yucatan-vs-riu-republica":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Yucatan is a family all-inclusive in Playa del Carmen, Mexico, with a kids club, waterpark, babysitting, dive program, watersports, nightclub, spa, and swim-up bar on a well-rated location strip scoring 8.5. Riu Republica is an adults-only all-inclusive in Punta Cana, Dominican Republic, with a notably thinner amenity list but a higher pool rating (6.9 vs 6.2) and beach score (7.5 vs 7.3). Yucatan leads meaningfully on overall rating (8.6 vs 7.8), cleanliness (8.7 vs 8.3), service (8.7 vs 8.0), sleep quality (8.3 vs 7.4), and value (8.5 vs 7.9). Republica edges ahead only on pool, beach, atmosphere, and room scores, while offering a quieter adults-only environment. Both share a similar food rating floor (6.4 vs 6.2). If you want a family-oriented Mexican all-inclusive with deep amenities, superior service scores, and proximity to Playa del Carmen, go to Riu Yucatan. If you want an adults-only Punta Cana escape with a slight edge in rooms and pool, go to Riu Republica.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a well-rounded Mexican all-inclusive near Playa del Carmen, with a kids club, waterpark, babysitting, diving, watersports, and a nightclub, backed by high service and cleanliness scores.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups seeking a quieter, adults-only Punta Cana all-inclusive with slightly better room and pool ratings, who don't need an extensive amenity lineup and prefer the Dominican Republic as a destination.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from dry-season travel. Playa del Carmen's peak is December through April, avoiding Atlantic hurricane season. Punta Cana shares a similar window, with the lowest hurricane risk from December to March. Both locations can see elevated heat and humidity in summer, and Punta Cana carries higher storm exposure from August through October.","activities":"Riu Yucatan guests can dive, snorkel, windsurf, and rent watersports equipment directly from the resort, or venture into Playa del Carmen for cenote tours, the Coba ruins, and the 5th Avenue strip. Riu Republica guests are largely dependent on off-resort excursions for variety, with Punta Cana offering dune buggy tours, catamaran trips, and day visits to Saona Island nearby."},"hotel-riu-bambu-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Bambu is a family all-inclusive on Punta Cana's beach strip in the Dominican Republic, with a solid beach rating of 7.8 and strong location and cleanliness scores of 8.3, but a notably thin amenity list: just a beach and no-reservation dining. Hotel Riu Yucatan is a family all-inclusive in Playa del Carmen, Mexico, with a substantially higher overall rating of 8.6 versus Bambu's 7.5, better cleanliness (8.7 vs 8.3), service (8.7 vs 8.0), sleep quality (8.3 vs 7.9), and value (8.5 vs 7.9), plus a far more comprehensive amenity set including a kids club, waterpark, nightclub, spa, gym, swim-up bar, diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, babysitting, and rooms for groups of five or more. Bambu edges Yucatan on beach rating (7.8 vs 7.3) and food is nearly identical (6.2 vs 6.4). In almost every measurable dimension, Yucatan outperforms Bambu at the same price tier, making the beach quality at Bambu the primary reason to choose it.","whoShouldChooseA":"Guests who prioritize a strong Punta Cana beach experience above all else and are comfortable with a stripped-down amenity offering. A good fit for those who want a quieter, less programmed stay in the Dominican Republic and are less concerned about on-site entertainment or structured kids activities.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want maximum coverage of amenities at a mid-range price in Mexico, including a kids club, waterpark, babysitting, spa, and nightclub. Those who value cleanliness and service consistency, travel in groups of five or more, or want structured activities and evening entertainment will find Yucatan the stronger choice.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in peak Caribbean and Mexican Riviera travel windows. Punta Cana's dry season runs December through April, with hurricane exposure peaking August through October. Playa del Carmen shares a similar pattern, with the dry season from November through April offering the most reliable weather. Both carry a $$$  price tier, so peak-season rates will apply in winter months at both properties.","activities":"At Riu Bambu, the focus is the beach itself, with Punta Cana's long Atlantic-facing shoreline the main draw, while off-site excursions to Saona Island and cenote tours are popular add-ons. At Riu Yucatan, guests have diving, snorkelling, windsurfing, and watersports rentals on-site, plus easy access to Playa del Carmen's Fifth Avenue, nearby Tulum ruins, and cenote day trips from the Riviera Maya."},"club-med-fortaleza-vs-club-med-turkoise":{"keyDifferences":"Club Med Fortaleza is a family all-inclusive on Brazil's northeastern coast, rated highly for cleanliness (8.8), service (8.8), and location (8.7), with strong room scores (8.3) suggesting comfortable accommodation for families. Club Med Turkoise is an adults-only all-inclusive on Grace Bay in Turks and Caicos, where its beach rating of 9.8 and location score of 9.4 are among the highest possible — reflecting one of the Caribbean's most celebrated stretches of sand. Turkoise edges Fortaleza on atmosphere (7.4 vs 6.8) and value (8.3 vs 8.0), while Fortaleza leads on room quality (8.3 vs 7.4), cleanliness (8.8 vs 8.3), and service (8.8 vs 8.5). Both properties score similarly on food (7.4 vs 7.3) and pool (6.4 vs 6.2), suggesting neither excels in those areas. Fortaleza suits families wanting a well-run Brazilian beach resort; Turkoise is purpose-built for adults who prioritize an exceptional beach and watersports in a renowned Caribbean destination.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a well-serviced, clean Brazilian all-inclusive on the northeast coast with strong room quality and excellent service scores. A good fit for those seeking a less conventional Caribbean destination with a high location rating and Club Med's family programming.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults-only couples or groups who want the best possible beach experience in the Caribbean. With a 9.8 beach rating and 9.4 location score on Grace Bay, Turkoise is for those who prioritize world-class water clarity, diving, snorkelling, and a lively but adult atmosphere over family amenities.","whenToVisit":"Fortaleza's northeastern Brazil location offers warm, dry conditions from July through January, with peak winds ideal for the area's kite-surfing culture. Turkoise on Grace Bay is best visited December through April when rainfall is lowest and trade winds keep temperatures comfortable; hurricane season runs June through November and carries weather risk.","activities":"Fortaleza guests can access Club Med's activity programming against a backdrop of Brazil's windswept northeastern coast, known for kite-surfing and dune landscapes nearby. Turkoise offers diving, snorkelling, tennis, spa, gym, evening entertainment, and nightclub access directly on Grace Bay, consistently ranked among the world's top beaches, with excellent reef diving and water visibility year-round."},"hotel-riu-palace-paradise-island-vs-hotel-riu-yucatan":{"keyDifferences":"Hotel Riu Palace Paradise Island is an adults-only Bahamas all-inclusive on New Providence Island near Nassau, with a premium price point ($$$$) and standout ratings for beach (8.5), location (8.8), cleanliness (8.8), and service (8.5), but softer scores for food (7.0) and pool (6.7). Hotel Riu Yucatan is a family all-inclusive in Playa del Carmen at a lower price point ($$$), carrying a higher overall rating (8.6 vs 7.6) and stronger service (8.7) and value (8.5 vs 8.1), while its beach (7.3) and room (7.9) scores trail Paradise Island. Yucatan compensates with a full family amenity stack: kids club, babysitting, waterpark for little kids, nightclub, dive center, windsurfing, and rooms sleeping five or more. Paradise Island wins on atmosphere by a slim margin (6.9 vs 6.5), and its Bahamian setting commands a clear premium. If you want an adults-only Bahamian escape with exceptional beach, service, and location scores at a luxury price, go to Riu Palace Paradise Island. If you want a well-priced family all-inclusive in the Riviera Maya with strong service, watersports, and kids programming, go to Riu Yucatan.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults-only couples or groups seeking a premium Bahamian all-inclusive with top-tier beach, service, and location ratings close to Nassau. Best suited to those who prioritize a quieter, upscale atmosphere and are willing to pay more for the Bahamas setting and resort polish.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with young children who want a well-priced Playa del Carmen all-inclusive with a kids club, babysitting, waterpark, watersports, and rooms that sleep five or more. Also suits value-focused travellers who rate service and cleanliness above beach quality.","whenToVisit":"Bahamas peaks December through April when humidity drops and hurricane risk is minimal; avoid late August through October. Playa del Carmen shares a similar winter peak with dry, cooler weather from November through April. Both destinations see higher rates and occupancy over Christmas and spring break. Budget travellers can find lower prices at Riu Yucatan in May or early June before Caribbean hurricane season intensifies.","activities":"At Riu Yucatan guests can dive, windsurf, snorkel, and rent watersports equipment directly on the beach, with Playa del Carmen's famous Fifth Avenue shopping and dining strip walkable from the property and Tulum ruins a short drive south. At Riu Palace Paradise Island, guests are minutes from Nassau's colonial downtown, Atlantis resort, and the Cabbage Beach strip, with snorkelling and water excursions easily arranged through the resort."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall Resort and Spa is a large Jamaican family all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, nightclub, golf course, and evening entertainment on a beach rated 6.0, at a mid-market price point. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a premium boutique St. Lucia property set in the dramatic Marigot Bay, with a beach rated just 2.5 but standout scores in cleanliness (9.2), sleep quality (9.2), service (9.1), food (8.6), and atmosphere (8.6), at a significantly higher price. Dreams Rose Hall wins on activity breadth and family programming, while Zoëtry dominates on food, service, cleanliness, and intimate atmosphere. The gap in food ratings is striking — 8.6 versus 7.4 — as is the service differential of 9.1 versus 8.7. If you want a lively Jamaican family all-inclusive with a lazy river, teen club, nightclub, and golf at a moderate price, choose Dreams Rose Hall. If you want a refined, boutique St. Lucia experience centered on exceptional food, service, and atmosphere in a stunning bay setting, choose Zoëtry Marigot Bay.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a large, activity-rich Jamaican all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, nightclub, golf course, and evening entertainment at a mid-range price point near Montego Bay.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and small families with up to three guests per room who prioritize exceptional food, immaculate cleanliness, and attentive boutique service over beach quality, and are willing to pay a premium for a serene, intimate setting in St. Lucia's picturesque Marigot Bay.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations enjoy Caribbean peak season from mid-December through April, with lower humidity and minimal rain. Jamaica's shoulder months of May and November offer value at Dreams Rose Hall before and after hurricane season. St. Lucia's wet season runs June through November, but Marigot Bay's sheltered setting can make Zoëtry a reasonable year-round choice for those less focused on beach use.","activities":"Dreams Rose Hall guests can play golf on-site, take the lazy river, join the nightclub, and explore Montego Bay's Hip Strip, Dunn's River Falls, and ATV tours nearby. Zoëtry Marigot Bay guests can fish, take boat trips across the bay, hike to the Pitons, visit sulfur springs, or explore Soufrière — a dramatic natural landscape that more than compensates for the limited beach."},"club-med-gramado-vs-club-med-turkoise":{"keyDifferences":"Club Med Gramado is a family all-inclusive nestled in the highlands of southern Brazil, a landlocked mountain resort where beach scores a 4.6 and pool a 6.2, but location (8.8), cleanliness (8.7), and service (8.7) are strong suits. Club Med Turkoise is an adults-only all-inclusive on Grace Bay in Turks and Caicos, one of the Caribbean's most celebrated stretches of sand, reflected in a beach rating of 9.8 and location of 9.4. The gap in beach experience is the defining difference: Turkoise exists almost entirely around its exceptional beachfront, while Gramado trades on its mountain setting, European-influenced architecture, and family programming in a non-beach destination. Room ratings favor Gramado (8.3 vs 7.4), and atmosphere is close (7.1 vs 7.4). Gramado suits families seeking a culturally distinct Brazilian highland escape; Turkoise suits adults chasing world-class Caribbean beach and water sports. Both sit at the same price tier, so the choice comes down entirely to mountains and family versus beach and adults-only.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a culturally rich, non-beach Club Med experience in the Brazilian highlands, where strong service scores (8.7), clean facilities (8.7), and a mountain setting distinguish it from conventional Caribbean all-inclusives. Ideal for those already visiting southern Brazil.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults and couples who prioritize world-class beach access above all else. With a beach rating of 9.8 and Grace Bay consistently ranked among the planet's best, Turkoise suits divers, snorkellers, and sun-seekers who want a no-children environment and strong location scores to match.","whenToVisit":"Gramado sits in Brazil's southern subtropical highlands where winter (June–August) brings cool, misty weather and regional festivals; summer (December–February) is warmer but wetter. Turkoise benefits from Turks and Caicos' dependably dry and sunny Caribbean climate from December through April, with hurricane season running June through November carrying meaningful risk, particularly August through October.","activities":"Gramado guests explore the Caracol State Park waterfalls, Canela's canyon trails, European-influenced town centers, and chocolate and wine routes unique to the region. Turkoise guests dive and snorkel Grace Bay's barrier reef, one of the healthiest in the Caribbean, with on-site gym, tennis, spa, and evening entertainment rounding out the program. Neither property overlaps meaningfully in activity profile."},"breathless-montego-bay-resort-and-spa-vs-dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Breathless Montego Bay and Dreams Rose Hall share the same overall rating of 8.5 and nearly identical service scores (both 8.7), but they serve fundamentally different guests in different price brackets. Breathless is an adults-only property at $$$$ with a tighter amenity set focused on atmosphere, nightlife, and premium rooms, scoring higher on room quality (8.7 vs 8.2) and atmosphere (7.4 vs 7.1). Dreams Rose Hall is a $$ family all-inclusive with considerably broader infrastructure: kids club, teen club, lazy river, babysitting, golf course, and rooms accommodating five or more guests. Dreams edges Breathless on beach (6.0 vs 5.5), sleep quality (8.5 vs 8.3), and location (8.6 vs 8.5), while costing significantly less. The beach scores at both properties are modest by Caribbean standards, so neither should be chosen primarily for sand. Breathless wins on room quality and ambiance for adults; Dreams wins on family programming, value, and space. If you want adults-only atmosphere and superior rooms in Montego Bay at a premium price, choose Breathless. If you want a well-priced family all-inclusive with full kids programming and a lazy river, choose Dreams Rose Hall.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples and groups who want a lively, nightclub-driven Montego Bay all-inclusive with above-average rooms, a swim-up bar, spa, and evening entertainment in an adults-only setting, and who are willing to pay a premium for the separation from families.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families of all sizes, including larger groups needing rooms for five or more, who want a well-priced Montego Bay all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, babysitting, golf, and a full activity program without breaking the budget.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in Montego Bay, where the driest and most reliably sunny period runs from December through April. Summer months bring higher humidity and the possibility of afternoon showers but also lower rates, particularly relevant at Dreams Rose Hall where the $$ price point drops further in shoulder season. Hurricane season peaks August through October; travel insurance is advisable for either property during those months.","activities":"Both resorts offer on-site tennis, spa treatments, swim-up bars, evening entertainment, and nightclub access. Dreams Rose Hall adds a lazy river, golf course, and structured kids and teen programming. Off-property, Montego Bay's Rose Hall area provides easy access to the historic Rose Hall Great House, Chukka Caribbean adventure tours, Rocklands Bird Sanctuary, Montego Bay Marine Park snorkelling, and the dining and shopping of Gloucester Avenue downtown."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-wild-orchid-montego-bay":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall and Secrets Wild Orchid sit in the same Montego Bay market at opposite ends of the guest-profile spectrum. Dreams is a mid-price family resort with a kids club, teen club, babysitting, and rooms for five or more, while Secrets Wild Orchid is an adults-only property priced two tiers higher. Secrets edges Dreams on nearly every rated dimension: food (7.9 vs 7.4), beach (6.8 vs 6.0), pool (7.2 vs 7.1), atmosphere (7.7 vs 7.1), room (8.9 vs 8.2), cleanliness (9.0 vs 8.7), service (8.9 vs 8.7), and sleep quality (8.8 vs 8.5). Location scores are close but favor Secrets (8.9 vs 8.6). The most dramatic gap is atmosphere, a full 0.6 points, reflecting Secrets' quieter, couples-oriented environment versus Dreams' livelier family energy. Secrets also adds a casino, room service, and diving. Dreams counters with family-specific infrastructure — kids club, teen club, babysitting, and a golf course — that Secrets simply doesn't offer. The price premium at Secrets buys meaningfully better rooms and a calmer setting, not just a label.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of any age who want a well-rounded Jamaican all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, babysitting, lazy river, and rooms large enough for five or more, at a mid-range price point where value scores a strong 8.2.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want a quieter, higher-end Jamaican all-inclusive with standout room quality (8.9), excellent cleanliness (9.0), casino access, diving, and room service, and who are willing to pay a significant premium for the adults-only atmosphere.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in Montego Bay, so timing applies equally. Peak season runs mid-December through April when weather is driest and crowds are highest. May and June offer a sweet spot of lower prices and manageable weather before the Atlantic hurricane season intensifies from July through October. November is transitional and often underpriced relative to conditions.","activities":"Both resorts share a Montego Bay location, putting guests within reach of Doctor's Cave Beach, Dunn's River Falls, the Good Hope Estate, ATV tours, and Luminous Lagoon excursions. On-site, both offer tennis, spa treatments, swim-up bars, a lazy river, evening entertainment, and a nightclub. Secrets adds scuba diving and a casino; Dreams adds golf access and dedicated kids and teen programming."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-st-james-montego-bay":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall and Secrets St. James share the same overall rating of 8.5 and both sit on Montego Bay's coast, but they diverge sharply on audience, price, and experience. Dreams is a mid-price family resort with a kids club, teen club, babysitting, lazy river, and rooms for five or more, built around keeping multiple generations entertained. Secrets St. James is an adults-only property priced significantly higher, with a cleaner, quieter atmosphere reflected in its higher atmosphere rating (7.7 vs 7.1), better rooms (8.8 vs 8.2), and superior cleanliness (9.0 vs 8.7). Secrets edges Dreams on food (7.9 vs 7.4), beach (6.8 vs 6.0), and service (8.9 vs 8.7). Dreams counters with a golf course, lazy river, nightclub, and family infrastructure that Secrets simply doesn't offer. Secrets also includes free Wi-Fi and a casino, while Dreams charges for Wi-Fi. Both are solid value plays, but Secrets costs considerably more for a noticeably more refined, adult-oriented environment.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a lively Jamaican all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, babysitting, lazy river, and rooms large enough for five or more. The golf course and nightclub also make it appealing for parents who want adult amenities alongside comprehensive family programming.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want a quieter, more polished Jamaican all-inclusive with superior rooms, cleanliness, and service scores, plus a casino, diving, heated pool, and free Wi-Fi. Guests willing to pay a premium for a noticeably more refined atmosphere without children will find Secrets St. James consistently delivers.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in Montego Bay, so timing advice applies equally. The dry season from mid-December through April offers the most reliable weather and the highest prices. May and November shoulder months can offer better rates with mostly manageable weather. Peak hurricane season runs July through October, with September the riskiest month, though both resorts maintain operations year-round.","activities":"Both resorts offer beach access, swim-up bars, tennis, spas, nightclubs, evening entertainment, and gym facilities. Secrets adds diving and a casino on-site. Dreams adds a lazy river, golf course, and a full kids and teen club program. The broader Montego Bay area offers duty-free shopping at Harmony Hall, river tubing on the Great River, zip-lining at Chukka Caribbean Adventures, and Jamaican cultural excursions to Rose Hall Great House."},"dreams-playa-esmeralda-resort-and-spa-vs-dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Playa Esmeralda is a premium Dominican Republic family all-inclusive in the quieter El Cedro area, earning standout scores for rooms (9.2), cleanliness (9.3), service (9.2), and location (9.0), but its pool rating (7.1) and atmosphere (7.5) suggest a more relaxed, low-key environment. Dreams Rose Hall sits in Montego Bay at a significantly lower price point, offering a broader amenity set including a lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, tennis, golf course, and rooms for five or more guests, but trails Esmeralda in nearly every quality metric: rooms (8.2 vs 9.2), beach (6.0 vs 8.3), atmosphere (7.1 vs 7.5), and overall (8.5 vs 8.9). Esmeralda's beach scores considerably higher (8.3 vs 6.0), a meaningful gap. Rose Hall compensates with more activity infrastructure and a livelier entertainment program at a lower price. If you want a quieter, higher-quality Dominican Republic family resort with an exceptional beach and superior rooms and service, choose Esmeralda. If you want a more activity-packed Jamaican family resort with a nightclub, lazy river, golf, and swim-up bar at a more accessible price, choose Rose Hall.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families and couples who prioritize room quality, a strong beach, and attentive service over a packed activity roster, and who are happy to pay a premium for a quieter, more polished Dominican Republic resort experience away from the busiest tourist corridors.","whoShouldChooseB":"Budget-conscious families, particularly those with teenagers, who want maximum activity variety in Montego Bay — lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, golf, and evening entertainment — and need rooms that accommodate five or more guests without stretching to a premium price tier.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations share a similar Caribbean dry season from December through April, making those months the safest bet for reliable sunshine. The Dominican Republic's El Cedro area can see heavier rainfall from August through October. Jamaica's Montego Bay is similarly wettest from September through November. For either resort, January through March offers the most consistent weather and fewest storm-season concerns.","activities":"At Esmeralda, families can use the kids club, teen club, spa, and gym, with the strong beach front and centre. Rose Hall adds considerably more on-site variety: a lazy river, swim-up bar, tennis courts, a nightclub, evening entertainment, and access to an adjacent golf course. Both resorts sit within reach of excursions — whale watching and Los Haitises National Park near El Cedro, and Montego Bay's doctor's cave beach, river tubing, and Dunn's River Falls day trips from Rose Hall."},"breathless-cancun-soul-resort-and-spa-vs-dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Breathless Cancun Soul is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive in Puerto Morelos rated a touch lower overall (8.4 vs 8.5) but significantly stronger on rooms (9.1 vs 8.2), cleanliness (9.3 vs 8.7), and atmosphere (7.5 vs 7.1), at a premium price point with a more intimate, lifestyle-focused experience. Dreams Rose Hall is a budget-friendlier family all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a notably weaker beach score (6.0 vs 7.8) and pool score (7.1 vs 7.4), but compensates with a much broader amenity set: kids club, teen club, lazy river, babysitting, golf course, tennis, and rooms accommodating five or more guests. Breathless positions itself as a sophisticated adults escape where room quality and cleanliness are genuine strengths; Dreams Rose Hall trades on value and family utility rather than polish. The price gap is substantial — Breathless is $$$$ against Dreams' $$ — making Dreams the clear choice for family budgets and Breathless the pick for adult couples willing to pay for noticeably superior accommodations and a livelier, curated atmosphere without children.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples and groups who want a premium Mexican all-inclusive with standout room quality (9.1), exceptional cleanliness (9.3), a nightclub, and a lively swim-up bar scene in Puerto Morelos — and who are willing to pay a premium to keep the experience entirely adult.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of all ages who want a budget-conscious Jamaican all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a kids club, teen club, babysitting, lazy river, golf, and large rooms — and who can live with a weaker beach (6.0) in exchange for broad amenities at a significantly lower price point.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations are year-round resorts. Cancun and Puerto Morelos peak from December through April when Mexican Caribbean weather is driest and coolest; hurricane season runs June through November with September being highest risk. Montego Bay similarly peaks December through April; Jamaica's hurricane season overlaps the same months, with August through October carrying the most risk. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates at both properties with generally acceptable weather.","activities":"At Breathless Cancun, guests swim, use the spa, work out, and enjoy the nightclub and evening entertainment without leaving the property; nearby Puerto Morelos offers snorkelling on the protected reef just offshore and easy day trips to Tulum and Playa del Carmen. At Dreams Rose Hall, guests play tennis, golf, float the lazy river, snorkel, and join evening entertainment; Montego Bay's Hip Strip, Dunn's River Falls, and ATV excursions into the Jamaican interior are all accessible nearby excursions."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-dreams-sands-cancun-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall and Dreams Sands Cancun share the same overall rating (8.5) and service score (8.7), but diverge sharply on amenities, atmosphere, and price. Rose Hall is a mid-price ($$) Jamaican family resort in Montego Bay loaded with extras: a nightclub, teen club, swim-up bar, spa, gym, tennis, golf access, babysitting, and evening entertainment. Sands Cancun is a premium ($$$$) Mexican property that leans more stripped-back, offering a kids club for under-4s and a lazy river but little else beyond the basics. Atmosphere favors Rose Hall noticeably (7.1 vs 6.7), as does pool quality (7.1 vs 6.0) and room ratings (8.2 vs 7.8). Sands Cancun edges ahead only on beach score (6.5 vs 6.0), though neither excels there. For the price gap, Rose Hall delivers substantially more programming and facilities. Sands Cancun's one meaningful advantage is its toddler-specific kids club, which Rose Hall does not offer. Wi-Fi at Rose Hall comes at an extra charge, while Sands Cancun does not list this restriction.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with older kids or teens who want a well-rounded Jamaican all-inclusive with a nightclub, teen club, spa, golf, swim-up bar, and evening entertainment at a mid-range price point. Also strong for couples seeking lively atmosphere alongside family amenities.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with toddlers or very young children who want a Cancun all-inclusive with a dedicated under-4s kids club and a calmer, quieter atmosphere. Best suited to guests who prioritize the Cancun location and are comfortable paying a premium for a more pared-back resort experience.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak in winter. Jamaica's dry season runs December through April, making those months ideal for Rose Hall. Cancun shares a similar dry-season window but sees its busiest crowds and highest prices from December through March. Cancun's hurricane season (June–October) overlaps with Jamaica's, though Cancun's Hotel Zone location can be more directly exposed. Shoulder months like May and November offer better rates at both properties.","activities":"Rose Hall guests can use the on-site golf course, tennis courts, spa, and lazy river, or venture into Montego Bay for river rafting, Dunn's River Falls day trips, and the Rose Hall Great House tour nearby. Sands Cancun sits in the Hotel Zone with access to Cancun's water parks, Mayan ruins at Chichen Itza and Tulum, snorkeling in the Caribbean, and the Nichupte Lagoon for watersports, though the resort itself offers limited on-site programming beyond beach and pool."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-mirabel-cancun-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall is a mid-price family all-inclusive in Montego Bay, Jamaica, with a lazy river, kids club, teen club, nightclub, babysitting, golf, tennis, and swim-up bar on a beach rated a modest 6.0. Secrets Mirabel is an adults-only luxury resort in Cancún rated considerably higher across nearly every metric: cleanliness (9.3 vs 8.7), service (9.1 vs 8.7), rooms (9.1 vs 8.2), food (8.2 vs 7.4), beach (7.3 vs 6.0), and sleep quality (9.2 vs 8.5), though at a significantly higher price point ($$$$vs $$). Dreams Rose Hall wins on family infrastructure and value, while Secrets Mirabel delivers a quieter, more polished experience with a superior beach and noticeably better rooms. Dreams Rose Hall's overall rating of 8.5 trails Secrets Mirabel's 8.7, and those gaps widen meaningfully in food, beach, and room quality. The amenity set at Dreams is broader for families, while Secrets Mirabel keeps things lean but refined for adult guests seeking calm and comfort.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a lively Jamaican all-inclusive with a lazy river, kids and teen clubs, babysitting, nightclub, and golf at a mid-range price. The strong service and cleanliness scores mean parents can relax while the resort does the heavy lifting.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples and solo travelers who want a high-end, serene Cancún experience with outstanding rooms, impeccable cleanliness, and attentive service, and are willing to pay a premium for it. Those who prioritize sleep quality, a better beach, and refined food over entertainment variety will find Secrets Mirabel the stronger choice.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from dry-season visits. For Dreams Rose Hall, December through April offers the most reliable Jamaica weather before the Atlantic hurricane season builds. Secrets Mirabel in Cancún follows a similar pattern, with November through May delivering the driest, least humid conditions. Both destinations see peak pricing and crowds over the Christmas and spring break windows, so shoulder months like November or early May offer better rates.","activities":"At Dreams Rose Hall guests can play golf, hit the tennis courts, join evening entertainment and nightclub events, snorkel, or simply float the lazy river. Near Montego Bay, the Luminous Lagoon, Dunn's River Falls, and ATV excursions are popular add-ons. At Secrets Mirabel, snorkelling, spa treatments, and pool time anchor the on-site experience. Cancún's Hotel Zone puts guests close to Isla Mujeres day trips, cenote diving, and Chichén Itzá tours."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-dreams-sapphire-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall and Dreams Sapphire are both mid-range family all-inclusives in the Dreams brand, but they differ meaningfully in location, price, and amenity mix. Rose Hall sits in Montego Bay, Jamaica at $$ pricing, with a lazy river, golf course, and nightclub as standout features, though its beach scores a modest 6.0 and pool a 7.1. Sapphire is located in Puerto Morelos, Mexico at $$$$ pricing, and adds diving, snorkelling, fishing, yoga, an adult pool, and a kids club for under-4s — a notable edge for families with toddlers. Sapphire scores higher on service (9.0 vs 8.7), rooms (8.5 vs 8.2), and cleanliness (8.8 vs 8.7), though its beach (5.0) and pool (6.7) ratings are actually lower than Rose Hall's. Rose Hall charges less and includes a golf course and lazy river not found at Sapphire, but Sapphire offers free Wi-Fi, more watersports, and broader age coverage in its kids programming. Overall scores are close: Sapphire at 8.7, Rose Hall at 8.5.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples who want a Jamaica all-inclusive with a lazy river, golf course, and nightclub at a more accessible price point. Those who enjoy a lively Montego Bay setting and don't need diving or toddler-specific kids programming will find Rose Hall delivers strong value.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families — especially those with toddlers or young children — who want a polished Mexican Caribbean all-inclusive with top-tier service (9.0), free Wi-Fi, diving, snorkelling, fishing, yoga, and an adult pool. Those willing to pay a premium for broader programming and a quieter Puerto Morelos atmosphere will feel well-served.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from winter and spring travel. Jamaica's peak season runs December through April when humidity is lower and rainfall minimal; hurricane season (June–November) brings risk but lower rates at Rose Hall. Puerto Morelos and the Riviera Maya are most reliable November through May; summer months bring heat, humidity, and occasional tropical storms. Both properties are worth avoiding during major US school holiday peak weeks when crowds and pricing spike.","activities":"Rose Hall guests can golf on-site, ride the lazy river, and explore Montego Bay's bars and hip strip nearby. Sapphire guests can dive, snorkel, and fish directly from the resort in the calmer waters near Puerto Morelos, with the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef — second largest in the world — just offshore. Both resorts offer tennis, spa treatments, swim-up bars, evening entertainment, and nightclubs. The Mayan ruins at Tulum and Chichen Itza are day-trip options from Sapphire."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-sunscape-dominicus-la-romana":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall Resort and Spa is a mid-price Jamaican family all-inclusive in Montego Bay with an extensive amenity set: lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, teen club, kids club, babysitting, spa, golf, tennis, and evening entertainment. Sunscape Dominicus La Romana is a higher-priced Dominican Republic family resort near La Romana with a notably leaner amenity list anchored by dual waterparks and a kids and teen club. The ratings tell a clear story: Dreams outscores Sunscape on overall rating (8.5 vs 8.1), food (7.4 vs 6.2), pool (7.1 vs 6.2), atmosphere (7.1 vs 6.2), and service (8.7 vs 8.3), while Sunscape holds the edge on beach (8.0 vs 6.0). Sunscape costs significantly more despite delivering fewer amenities and lower scores across most categories. Dreams is the stronger all-around value proposition; Sunscape's main differentiator is its superior beach and waterpark setup for young children.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a well-rounded Jamaican all-inclusive with strong service ratings, a lazy river, nightclub, spa, golf, and babysitting at a mid-market price. Parents with teenagers will appreciate the teen club and evening entertainment program alongside the broader activity lineup.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with young children who prioritize a strong beach and dual waterparks over a wide amenity set, and who are specifically drawn to the La Romana area of the Dominican Republic. Best suited to those for whom beach quality is the non-negotiable priority.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations share a Caribbean climate with peak season running December through April when rainfall is lowest and conditions most reliable. Jamaica's Montego Bay and the Dominican Republic's La Romana both face hurricane season from June through November, with September being the highest-risk month. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates with generally manageable weather at both resorts.","activities":"At Dreams Rose Hall, guests can play tennis, use the gym, golf nearby, and enjoy evening entertainment and the nightclub on-site. La Romana's Sunscape sits near Altos de Chavón, a replica Mediterranean village with galleries and shops, and the Chavón River for excursions. Both resorts offer standard Caribbean beach activities, and Montego Bay's Hip Strip provides off-resort dining and nightlife options close to Dreams."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-tulum-resort-and-beach-club":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall Resort and Spa is a mid-price family all-inclusive in Montego Bay, Jamaica, with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, golf, tennis, babysitting, and evening entertainment on a beach strip setting. Secrets Tulum Resort and Beach Club is a premium adults-only all-inclusive in Mexico's Tulum area, priced two tiers higher, with a dramatically different atmosphere score (8.5 vs 7.1) and stronger room (8.9 vs 8.2), cleanliness (9.1 vs 8.7), and sleep quality (9.1 vs 8.5) ratings. Dreams Rose Hall edges ahead on location (8.6 vs 7.8) and value (8.2 vs 7.9), while Secrets Tulum leads on food (7.9 vs 7.4) and pool (8 vs 7.1). Dreams suits families who want broad amenities and lively entertainment at a reasonable price; Secrets Tulum is for adults who want a quieter, design-conscious retreat with superior rooms and finishes at a significantly higher cost. The beach ratings are weak at both properties, so neither should be chosen primarily for the beach.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a lively Jamaican all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, babysitting, golf, and evening entertainment at a mid-range price point in the Montego Bay area.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or groups who want a premium, tranquil adults-only retreat near Tulum with excellent room quality, high cleanliness standards, and a sophisticated atmosphere, and who are willing to pay top-tier prices for that elevated experience.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak in the December-to-April dry season. Jamaica's Montego Bay can see hurricane-season rain from June through November, with September and October the riskiest months. Tulum's weather follows a similar Caribbean pattern, though its jungle-adjacent setting means humidity year-round. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates at both properties with generally acceptable weather.","activities":"Near Dreams Rose Hall, guests can play golf on-site, explore Montego Bay's Hip Strip, take day trips to Dunn's River Falls, or visit the Rose Hall Great House. Near Secrets Tulum, guests can explore the UNESCO-adjacent Tulum archaeological ruins, snorkel the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, swim in cenotes, and visit the bohemian Tulum town for restaurants and boutiques."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-sunscape-dorado-pacifico-ixtapa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall and Sunscape Dorado Pacifico Ixtapa are both family all-inclusives with similar overall scores (8.5 vs 8.6) and comparable room ratings (both 8.2), but they diverge sharply on amenities and food. Dreams Rose Hall is a fully loaded Jamaican resort with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, spa, babysitting, golf, and tennis, while Sunscape Dorado lists only a beach among its amenities — a significant gap for families expecting programming and facilities. Food scores tell a stark story: Dreams scores 7.4 versus Sunscape's 6.4, a full point lower. Sunscape edges Dreams on beach (6.8 vs 6.0) and location (8.8 vs 8.6), placing it on the Pacific Coast of Ixtapa, a less-visited but scenic Mexican setting. Dreams costs less despite offering far more infrastructure. Sunscape charges more ($$$ vs $$) for a stripped-down experience with a better beach and location score but noticeably weaker food, pool (6.2 vs 7.1), and atmosphere (6.3 vs 7.1) ratings.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a fully programmed Jamaican all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, babysitting, spa, and nightclub at a mid-range price. The strong service (8.7) and cleanliness (8.7) ratings make it a reliable, activity-rich choice for families of all ages near Montego Bay.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families or couples drawn to the quieter Pacific Coast of Mexico who prioritize a solid beach and location over onsite programming. Best suited to guests who are self-sufficient, don't rely heavily on resort amenities or food quality, and want a more off-the-beaten-path Mexican resort experience in Ixtapa.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Rose Hall is best visited November through mid-December or late January through April to avoid peak hurricane season in Jamaica. Sunscape Dorado in Ixtapa sits on Mexico's Pacific Coast, where the dry season runs November through May — the clearest, calmest window for beach and water conditions. Both resorts see higher prices and crowds during North American school holidays regardless of season.","activities":"Dreams Rose Hall guests can play golf and tennis onsite, enjoy the lazy river and swim-up bar, or head into Montego Bay for duty-free shopping, the Hip Strip, and ATV or river-tubing excursions. Sunscape Dorado guests in Ixtapa can explore nearby Zihuatanejo's fishing village, book sportfishing or snorkelling trips, visit Ixtapa Island by ferry, or browse the Ixtapa commercial zone a short drive from the resort."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-montego-bay-jamaica":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall Resort and Spa is a large Montego Bay family all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, nightclub, golf course, babysitting, swim-up bar, and evening entertainment at a mid-market price point. Zoëtry Montego Bay Jamaica is an adults-only boutique all-inclusive in the same area at a significantly higher price point, with markedly better room (8.7 vs 8.2), sleep quality (8.9 vs 8.5), and food ratings (8.1 vs 7.4), but a notably weaker beach score (4 vs 6). Dreams trades on breadth of amenities and family infrastructure; Zoëtry trades on intimacy, room quality, and a quieter atmosphere. The beach underperforms at both properties, but more severely at Zoëtry, making pool and setting more central to that experience. Dreams scores higher on value (8.2 vs 7.9) despite the price gap, suggesting Zoëtry guests are paying a premium for refinement rather than bang-for-buck. If you want a family-oriented Montego Bay all-inclusive with wide-ranging activities and good value, choose Dreams. If you want a high-end adults-only retreat prioritizing room quality and tranquility, choose Zoëtry.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a well-equipped Montego Bay all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, nightclub, and golf at a competitive mid-market price. Also suits couples who prioritize activity variety and strong service ratings over boutique exclusivity.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or solo travelers willing to pay a premium for superior room quality, exceptional sleep ratings, and a quieter, more intimate atmosphere in Montego Bay. Best suited to those who prioritize refined surroundings and attentive service over beach quality or activity breadth.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts sit in Montego Bay, so timing applies equally. Peak season runs mid-December through April when rainfall is lowest and temperatures are most consistent. The shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates with acceptable weather. Hurricane season peaks August through October, when prices drop but weather risk rises. Neither resort's beach ratings are strong enough to make beach conditions a primary booking driver.","activities":"Both resorts are in the Montego Bay corridor, giving guests access to Dunn's River Falls excursions, river rafting on the Great River, and Luminous Lagoon night tours. Dreams guests have tennis, golf, and a lazy river on-site. Zoëtry guests benefit from the quieter property atmosphere but will rely more on off-site excursions for activity variety. Montego Bay's Hip Strip dining and nightlife is accessible from both properties."},"dreams-bahia-mita-surf-and-spa-resort-vs-dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Bahia Mita Surf & Spa Resort is a premium Mexican family all-inclusive on the Pacific coast near Punta de Mita, with standout room quality (9.0), cleanliness (9.2), and service (9.0) ratings that justify its $$$$ price point. Its beach rating is notably low at 4.8, likely reflecting Pacific surf conditions rather than a traditional calm Caribbean beach. Dreams Rose Hall is a budget-friendlier $$ Jamaican family all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a significantly better beach score (6.0 vs 4.8), a lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, teen club, golf, tennis, and rooms accommodating five or more guests. Rose Hall trails Bahia Mita on rooms (8.2 vs 9.0), cleanliness (8.7 vs 9.2), and service (8.7 vs 9.0), but compensates with a broader amenity set at a lower price. Bahia Mita wins on room quality and atmosphere (7.4 vs 7.1); Rose Hall wins on beach, amenity variety, and value for money (8.2 vs 8.5 overall at half the price tier).","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples who prioritize immaculate rooms, attentive service, and a refined Pacific Mexico setting near Punta de Mita and Sayulita, and are comfortable trading a calmer beach for exceptional cleanliness and room quality at a premium price.","whoShouldChooseB":"Larger families, particularly those needing rooms for five or more, who want a well-rounded Jamaican all-inclusive with a usable beach, lazy river, swim-up bar, teen club, nightclub, and golf at a significantly lower price point near Montego Bay.","whenToVisit":"Bahia Mita's Pacific Mexico location means November through April is peak dry season, with lower humidity and minimal rain. Avoid September and October when Pacific hurricane activity peaks. Rose Hall in Jamaica is best from mid-December through April for dry, settled weather. Jamaica's hurricane season runs June through November, with September and October carrying the highest risk for both destinations.","activities":"At Bahia Mita, surfing and ocean exploration along the rugged Pacific coastline are the draw, with Punta de Mita and Sayulita village close by for boutique shopping and surf lessons. At Rose Hall, guests can use the on-site golf course, tennis courts, and lazy river, while Montego Bay's Hip Strip, Dunn's River Falls, and ATV excursions into the Jamaican interior are all accessible nearby."},"dreams-natura-resort-and-spa-vs-dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Natura Resort & Spa is a higher-priced ($$$$ vs $$) eco-influenced Mexican family resort in Puerto Morelos with standout room scores (8.8) and cleanliness (9.0), but a notably weak beach rating (4.5) and a limited amenity set — no lazy river, spa, gym, tennis, nightclub, babysitting, or teen club on the listing. Dreams Rose Hall is a more affordable Jamaican family all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a stronger beach score (6.0 vs 4.5), stronger atmosphere (7.1 vs 6.9), a higher location score (8.6 vs 8.0), and a far broader amenity lineup including a lazy river, swim-up bar, teen club, kids club, babysitting, nightclub, golf course, spa, gym, and tennis. Food scores are nearly identical (7.3 vs 7.4). Natura edges ahead on room quality, cleanliness, and value perception despite its higher price, suggesting a quieter, more refined experience, while Rose Hall delivers more programming and activity variety at a significantly lower price point for families who want structured entertainment and watersport facilities.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples who prioritize beautifully appointed, exceptionally clean rooms in a quieter eco-influenced Mexican setting near Puerto Morelos and are less concerned about an extensive activity program or a strong beach.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with kids of all ages who want a well-priced Jamaican all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, teen and kids clubs, babysitting, golf, and a full entertainment schedule on a beach that actually delivers.","whenToVisit":"Puerto Morelos enjoys its driest, calmest weather from December through April, making that the prime window for Dreams Natura. Montego Bay is a year-round destination with its best weather also running November through April. Both resorts sit in the Caribbean hurricane belt, so late August through October carries the most weather risk at either property.","activities":"At Dreams Natura, the surrounding Puerto Morelos area offers world-class snorkelling and diving on the Mesoamerican Reef, cenote exploration, and the Puerto Morelos village craft market a short drive away. Dreams Rose Hall's Montego Bay location puts guests near Dunn's River Falls, ATV tours, catamaran cruises, and the lively Hip Strip, while the resort itself covers golf, tennis, and a lazy river on-site."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-st-lucia-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall Resort and Spa is a mid-price family all-inclusive in Montego Bay, Jamaica, loaded with amenities: kids club, teen club, lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, golf course, tennis, spa, babysitting, and evening entertainment. Secrets St. Lucia Resort and Spa is a premium adults-only all-inclusive in Saint Lucia at twice the price tier, with a much leaner amenities list but standout service and cleanliness ratings. Secrets beats Dreams on nearly every quality metric: service (9.2 vs 8.7), cleanliness (9.1 vs 8.7), sleep quality (9.2 vs 8.5), room (8.6 vs 8.2), food (8.0 vs 7.4), beach (6.8 vs 6.0), pool (7.6 vs 7.1), and atmosphere (7.8 vs 7.1). Dreams counters with a far broader activity and family infrastructure at a significantly lower price point. If you want a lively, amenity-rich Jamaican family all-inclusive with kids programming and entertainment at a mid-market price, choose Dreams Rose Hall. If you want a refined, adults-only Saint Lucia escape with exceptional service, quieter rooms, and premium finishes at a higher spend, choose Secrets St. Lucia.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a fully loaded Jamaican all-inclusive with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, nightclub, golf, and babysitting at a mid-market price point in convenient Montego Bay.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travelers willing to pay a premium for exceptional service, superior cleanliness, and a peaceful Saint Lucia setting without the noise and activity infrastructure of a family resort.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations share a similar Caribbean dry season from December through April, making those months the safest bet for settled weather. Jamaica's Montego Bay sees occasional shoulder-season deals from May to November, though hurricane risk rises. Saint Lucia sits slightly further south and can be more sheltered, but both resorts are best booked for winter or early spring travel to maximize beach and pool time.","activities":"Dreams Rose Hall guests have tennis, golf, a lazy river, swim-up bar, spa, and evening entertainment on site, with Montego Bay's shopping, dining, and excursions nearby. Secrets St. Lucia guests have the resort's spa and pools, with Saint Lucia's exceptional natural attractions close at hand: the Piton mountains, sulfur springs, rainforest hikes, zip-lining, snorkeling, and Castries duty-free shopping all accessible by short excursion."},"dreams-los-cabos-suites-golf-resort-and-spa-vs-dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Los Cabos Suites Golf Resort & Spa is a premium Mexican all-inclusive on the Pacific side of Los Cabos, rated exceptionally high for rooms (8.7), cleanliness (8.9), and service (8.7), but with a notably weak beach score (3.3) — a known consequence of the rough Pacific surf at San Jose del Cabo. Dreams Rose Hall is a more budget-friendly Jamaican all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a genuine beach (6.0 vs. 3.3), a lazy river, teen club, nightclub, swim-up bar, babysitting, tennis, and rooms that fit five or more guests. Los Cabos comes in at a significantly higher price tier ($$$$  vs. $$) and delivers on room quality and polish, but guests who want a true beach holiday will be disappointed. Rose Hall trades some of that luxury finish — rooms score 8.2 vs. 8.7 — for a far more complete amenity set and actual swimmable water. If you want premium suite-level accommodations and don't mind sacrificing the beach, go to Dreams Los Cabos. If you want a value-driven Jamaican family all-inclusive with a real beach, lazy river, and nightclub, go to Dreams Rose Hall.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples or families who prioritize exceptional room quality, cleanliness, and service over beach access, and are willing to pay a premium for a polished, upscale Los Cabos experience — perhaps anchored by golf, a spa, and Pacific scenery rather than swimming in the sea.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of all ages who want a well-priced Jamaican all-inclusive with a real beach, lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, teen club, babysitting, and large-group rooms — getting strong value without sacrificing the core Caribbean beach holiday experience.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Los Cabos is best visited October through June, avoiding the late-summer hurricane-adjacent heat and humidity; winter months bring dry, sunny conditions. Dreams Rose Hall benefits from Jamaica's peak dry season, December through April, when rain is minimal and trade winds keep temperatures comfortable. Both resorts see higher prices over Christmas and spring break, so shoulder months like November or early May offer better value.","activities":"At Dreams Los Cabos, guests can explore the art galleries and restaurants of San Jose del Cabo town, go sportfishing, whale watching (December–April), or take ATV tours through the desert landscape. At Dreams Rose Hall, guests have tennis, golf, a lazy river, and nightclub on-site, plus access to Montego Bay's Hip Strip, Dunn's River Falls excursions, and catamaran snorkelling trips along Jamaica's north coast."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-dreams-tulum-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall Resort and Spa is a mid-market Jamaican family all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a lazy river, teen club, kids club, nightclub, swim-up bar, babysitting, gym, tennis, spa, and golf course access — a wide amenity spread at a $$ price point. Dreams Tulum Resort & Spa is a significantly pricier $$$$ Mexican all-inclusive in Tulum with a much leaner amenity set: only a beach, a kids club for under-4s, and no-reservation dining. Rose Hall outscores Tulum across nearly every rating category — overall (8.5 vs 8.2), food (7.4 vs 7.0), pool (7.1 vs 6.7), atmosphere (7.1 vs 6.8), value (8.2 vs 7.9), and service (8.7 vs 8.5) — while costing a fraction of the price. Tulum's beach edges it slightly (6.3 vs 6.0), but neither beach rating is strong. Rose Hall is the clear value play for families wanting structured programming and nightlife; Tulum suits those paying a premium for the Mayan Riviera setting alone.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want maximum amenity coverage at a mid-market price — lazy river, teen club, kids club, nightclub, babysitting, and swim-up bar — in a well-rated Jamaican resort near Montego Bay. Especially strong for families with teenagers or mixed-age groups needing varied programming.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families drawn specifically to the Tulum destination and the Mayan Riviera experience who are willing to pay a substantial premium for location and atmosphere over amenities. Best suited to younger children (under 4 have dedicated programming) and parents who prioritize the cultural surroundings over resort facilities.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from the Caribbean's dry season, roughly mid-December through April, when rain and humidity are lowest. Jamaica's Montego Bay and Mexico's Tulum share similar hurricane-season vulnerability from June through November. Tulum's shoulder months of May and November can offer lower rates with acceptable weather. Rose Hall's strong year-round service ratings make it a reliable choice outside peak season.","activities":"At Rose Hall, guests can use the lazy river, swim-up bar, tennis courts, spa, and on-site nightclub, with golf nearby and Montego Bay's excursion scene — Dunn's River Falls, river tubing, and catamaran cruises — easily accessible. At Dreams Tulum, the ancient Tulum ruins, cenote swimming, and Sian Ka'an Biosphere Reserve are the primary draws beyond the beach, making the destination itself the activity anchor."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-sunscape-coco-punta-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall Resort and Spa is a mid-price Jamaican family all-inclusive in Montego Bay with an impressive amenity spread — lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, teen club, kids club, spa, golf, tennis, babysitting, and evening entertainment — posting strong scores across service (8.7), cleanliness (8.7), and overall (8.5). Sunscape Coco Punta Cana is a pricier Dominican Republic family all-inclusive in Punta Cana with a noticeably thinner amenity list — essentially beach, kids club, and teen club — and trails Dreams on nearly every rating: food (6.2 vs 7.4), pool (6.2 vs 7.1), atmosphere (6.2 vs 7.1), and overall (8.2 vs 8.5). Sunscape edges ahead only on beach score (6.8 vs 6.0). The value gap is striking given Sunscape's higher price tier and lower ratings. Dreams delivers more programming, better-rated facilities, and stronger scores at a lower price point. If you want a feature-rich Jamaican family all-inclusive with superior service and entertainment at a better price, Dreams Rose Hall wins clearly.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a fully loaded Jamaican all-inclusive with a lazy river, kids and teen clubs, babysitting, nightclub, spa, and golf — all at a mid-range price. Strong service and cleanliness scores make it a reliable choice for families who want maximum programming without premium pricing.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families prioritizing a slightly better beach in Punta Cana over resort amenities and atmosphere. Best suited to low-maintenance travelers content with minimal organized programming who simply want a clean, well-located Dominican base — though the higher price tag is hard to justify against the ratings.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations share a similar Caribbean high season from December through April, when rainfall is lowest and crowds peak. Jamaica's Montego Bay and the Dominican Republic's Punta Cana are both susceptible to hurricane season between June and November, with September the riskiest month. Shoulder months of May and November offer a balance of lower rates and reasonable weather at both properties.","activities":"Dreams Rose Hall guests can use the on-site golf course, tennis courts, spa, and lazy river, while nearby Montego Bay offers duty-free shopping, the Hip Strip, and excursions to Dunn's River Falls or river rafting. Sunscape Coco Punta Cana's thin on-site offering pushes guests off-property to Punta Cana's excursion circuit — dune buggies, catamaran trips, Saona Island day tours, and zip-lining are all accessible nearby."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-curacao-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall is a large Jamaican family all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, nightclub, babysitting, swim-up bar, golf, and tennis at a mid-range price point, sitting on a beach that rates a modest 6.0. Zoëtry Curaçao is a premium adults-only boutique resort near Willemstad with an 8.8 room rating and 8.8 sleep quality, but a strikingly low beach score of 3.3 and a considerably higher price tier. Dreams edges Zoëtry on overall score 8.5 vs 7.6 and value 8.2 vs 7.4, while Zoëtry leads on food 8.1 vs 7.4, rooms 8.8 vs 8.2, atmosphere 8.0 vs 7.1, and sleep quality 8.8 vs 8.5. Dreams is the better choice for families wanting activity-rich programming in Jamaica; Zoëtry suits couples seeking a quiet, design-conscious retreat in Curaçao despite neither resort offering a strong beach experience. The price gap is significant: Zoëtry costs considerably more for ratings that only partially justify the premium.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a lively Jamaican all-inclusive near Montego Bay with structured kids and teen programming, a lazy river, nightclub, golf, and evening entertainment at a competitive mid-range price point.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adult couples or solo travelers who prioritize exceptional room quality, deep sleep, and a refined boutique atmosphere near historic Willemstad, and who can accept a weak beach and a high price tag in exchange for a quieter, more intimate experience.","whenToVisit":"Jamaica's peak season runs mid-December through April when rainfall is lowest; hurricane season runs June through November with September the riskiest month. Curaçao sits outside the main hurricane belt and enjoys a dry, sunny climate year-round with consistent trade winds, making it a reliable destination in any month, though prices dip in the Caribbean off-season of May through November.","activities":"Dreams Rose Hall guests can play golf on-site, take to the lazy river and swim-up bar, explore Montego Bay's Hip Strip, snorkel, or join evening entertainment and nightclub programming. Zoëtry Curaçao guests can tour the UNESCO-listed colonial architecture of Willemstad, dive renowned Curaçao reef walls, visit Shete Boka National Park, explore the island's rugged coastline, and enjoy on-site spa treatments in a boutique setting."},"dreams-puerto-morelos-resort-and-spa-vs-dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Puerto Morelos is a premium-priced Mexican family all-inclusive in Puerto Morelos with a waterpark for both little and big kids, a beach, and a kids club, scoring well on rooms (8.5), cleanliness (8.6), and service (8.5), but posting weaker numbers on beach (5.0) and pool (6.7). Dreams Rose Hall is a more affordable Jamaican family all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, tennis, golf, spa, babysitting, teen club, and rooms for 5+ guests, earning a higher overall rating (8.5 vs 7.8), stronger location score (8.6 vs 7.5), better food rating (7.4 vs 7.0), and meaningfully better value (8.2 vs 7.8) at a fraction of the price. Puerto Morelos wins on room quality and has a dedicated waterpark setup for kids, but Rose Hall delivers a broader amenity spread, a livelier atmosphere with evening entertainment and a nightclub, and a significantly better overall guest experience at a lower price point. The beach scores are modest at both, though Rose Hall edges ahead there too (6.0 vs 5.0).","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children who prioritize high-quality rooms, cleanliness, and a dedicated waterpark experience in Mexico, and are willing to pay a premium price despite weaker beach and pool ratings relative to the cost.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families seeking strong all-round value in Jamaica near Montego Bay, with a wide amenity lineup including lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, golf, spa, babysitting, teen club, and large rooms sleeping 5 or more, all at a significantly lower price point.","whenToVisit":"Puerto Morelos is best visited November through April to avoid peak hurricane season and summer humidity on Mexico's Caribbean coast. Rose Hall in Montego Bay similarly benefits from a December to April visit during Jamaica's dry season. Both destinations see elevated prices and fuller resorts over Christmas and New Year, so early January or March offer a good balance of weather and availability.","activities":"At Puerto Morelos, guests can explore the Puerto Morelos coral reef, one of the best-preserved sections of the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, with snorkelling and diving close to shore, plus easy access to Cancun and Tulum. At Rose Hall, guests can play golf on the resort's own course, use the tennis courts, visit the historic Rose Hall Great House nearby, or take excursions into Montego Bay for water sports, shopping, and nightlife."},"dreams-playa-bonita-panama-vs-dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Playa Bonita Panama is a premium-priced family all-inclusive on the Pacific coast near Panama City, with a kids club for under-4s and reservation-free dining, but it posts some of the weakest ratings in this comparison: beach at 4.0, pool at 6.6, food at 6.7, and atmosphere at 6.5. Dreams Rose Hall Resort and Spa is a more affordable Montego Bay family all-inclusive with a dramatically stronger across-the-board scorecard — overall 8.5 versus 7.4, food 7.4 versus 6.7, beach 6.0 versus 4.0, pool 7.1 versus 6.6, value 8.2 versus 7.2, cleanliness 8.7 versus 8.0, and service 8.7 versus 8.1. Rose Hall also offers a far broader amenity set: lazy river, swim-up bar, teen club, nightclub, spa, golf, tennis, babysitting, and evening entertainment. Panama's appeal is its unusual location for travelers already visiting Central America, but by nearly every measurable metric, Rose Hall delivers more for less money.","whoShouldChooseA":"Travelers combining a Caribbean-style resort stay with a Panama City itinerary who prioritize cleanliness, sleep quality, and a quieter atmosphere, and who have very young children benefiting from the under-4 kids club. Best suited to those for whom Panama's geography is itself a draw.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families seeking strong value in Montego Bay who want a full amenity suite — lazy river, swim-up bar, teen and kids clubs, spa, golf, nightclub, and babysitting — backed by consistently high service and cleanliness ratings at a significantly lower price point than Dreams Panama.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Rose Hall is best visited between December and April, Jamaica's dry season, when beach and pool conditions are at their peak. Dreams Playa Bonita Panama sits on the Pacific side, where the dry season similarly runs December through April. Both resorts see higher rates and demand over the Christmas and Presidents' Day holiday windows, so booking early is advisable for either.","activities":"Dreams Rose Hall guests can play golf on the adjacent course, use the tennis courts, relax on the lazy river, and access Montego Bay's dining and excursion scene, including river rafting and Dunn's River Falls day trips. Dreams Playa Bonita Panama guests can explore Panama City's historic Casco Viejo district, transit the Panama Canal, and take rainforest excursions into Soberanía National Park — making it the stronger choice for travelers who want resort comfort alongside genuine sightseeing."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-sunscape-puerto-vallarta-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall is a mid-price Jamaican family all-inclusive in Montego Bay with strong across-the-board ratings: an 8.5 overall, 8.7 for both service and cleanliness, and 8.2 for rooms and value. Sunscape Puerto Vallarta is a pricier Mexican family all-inclusive on the Pacific coast that underperforms on nearly every comparable metric, scoring 8.0 overall, 6.2 for food and atmosphere, 6.0 for pool, and 5.3 for beach — a full 0.7 below Dreams Rose Hall's already modest beach score of 6.0. Dreams Rose Hall also has a richer amenity set: lazy river, nightclub, golf course, teen club, babysitting, and rooms for five or more, all at a lower price point. Sunscape Puerto Vallarta's best arguments are its location score of 8.3 and proximity to Puerto Vallarta town, but it costs more while delivering less on food, atmosphere, pool, and beach. If the ratings gap and amenity difference matter, Dreams Rose Hall is the stronger pick by a clear margin.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a well-rounded Jamaican all-inclusive with strong service, a lazy river, teen club, babysitting, golf, and nightclub access at a mid-market price. The high cleanliness and service scores make it a reliable choice for families with children of all ages.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families prioritizing access to Puerto Vallarta town and the broader Mexican Pacific coast experience over resort-specific amenities or ratings. Best suited to guests who plan to spend significant time off-property and treat the resort primarily as a comfortable base.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Rose Hall is best visited November through mid-December or January through April to avoid Jamaica's hurricane season peak and summer heat. Sunscape Puerto Vallarta suits travel from November through April, when Puerto Vallarta's dry season delivers reliable sunshine and low humidity. Both resorts see higher prices and crowds during U.S. school holidays, so early December or late January offer the best balance of weather and value.","activities":"Dreams Rose Hall guests can play golf on-site, take tennis lessons, use the lazy river, and access Montego Bay's shopping and dining via a short transfer. Sunscape Puerto Vallarta sits near the Malecon boardwalk, Zona Romántica, and world-class sport fishing, zip-lining, and whale-watching excursions in season. Both resorts offer beach and pool time, spa services, and evening entertainment programs suited to families traveling with children."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-sunscape-sabor-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall Resort and Spa is a large Jamaican family all-inclusive in Montego Bay with a lazy river, kids club, teen club, nightclub, spa, tennis, golf course, swim-up bar, and babysitting, scoring a strong overall 8.5 with particularly high marks for cleanliness (8.7), service (8.7), and location (8.6). Sunscape Sabor Cozumel is a stripped-back Mexican family all-inclusive on Cozumel island with beach access as its primary amenity, scoring a notably lower overall 7.6, with weaker food (6.1 vs 7.4), pool (5.8 vs 7.1), and atmosphere (6.2 vs 7.1) ratings. Dreams Rose Hall wins on almost every measurable dimension and offers a dramatically broader amenity set at the same price level. Sunscape Sabor Cozumel's main draw is its Cozumel location, which puts guests near world-class reef diving and snorkelling, but the resort itself delivers a far more modest experience. If you want a fully featured Jamaican family all-inclusive with strong service and a wide activity program, go to Dreams Rose Hall. If you want a simple, affordable base for exploring Cozumel's exceptional marine environment, go to Sunscape Sabor Cozumel.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a full-service Jamaican all-inclusive with a lazy river, kids and teen clubs, nightclub, spa, babysitting, and golf, and who value strong service and cleanliness ratings over a budget-first approach. A good fit for multigenerational groups needing rooms for five or more.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families or couples who prioritize Cozumel's world-renowned diving and snorkelling over resort amenities, and are happy with a simple, no-frills base at a modest price point. Best suited to guests who plan to spend most of their time off-property exploring the reef.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April when Caribbean weather is driest and most reliable. Cozumel sits slightly outside the main hurricane belt, making it marginally more weather-stable in shoulder months. Jamaica's Montego Bay sees the heaviest rainfall September through October. Either destination offers better value and thinner crowds in May or early December.","activities":"Dreams Rose Hall guests can play tennis, use the gym, take spa treatments, hit a nearby golf course, and enjoy evening entertainment and a nightclub on-site. Sunscape Sabor Cozumel's sparse on-site amenities push guests outward to Cozumel's exceptional off-property offerings, including world-class scuba diving and snorkelling along the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, glass-bottom boat tours, and day trips to Mayan ruins on the mainland."},"dreams-cozumel-cape-resort-and-spa-vs-dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Cozumel Cape Resort & Spa is a higher-priced ($$$$ vs $$) family all-inclusive on the island of Cozumel, Mexico, with a kids club for under-4s and a strong showing in room quality (8.2), cleanliness (8.5), service (8.3), and location (8.3). However, its overall rating of 7.3 trails Dreams Rose Hall's 8.5 by a significant 1.2 points, and its food (6.8), pool (6.7), and beach (5.3) ratings are all notably weaker. Dreams Rose Hall Resort and Spa near Montego Bay, Jamaica, delivers a broader amenity set including a lazy river, teen club, swim-up bar, nightclub, golf course, babysitting, tennis, spa, and gym, at a much lower price tier while outperforming Cozumel on value (8.2 vs 7.5), atmosphere (7.1 vs 6.9), cleanliness (8.7), and service (8.7). Cozumel's edge is its island location and room quality; Rose Hall wins on breadth of amenities, overall guest satisfaction, and price-to-value ratio.","whoShouldChooseA":"Guests who prioritize a distinctive island setting on Cozumel with strong room quality, cleanliness, and service, and who have toddlers to enroll in the under-4 kids club. Best suited to travelers willing to pay a premium for an intimate Mexican Caribbean island experience over sheer amenity volume.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want maximum amenities at a lower price point near Montego Bay, Jamaica, including a lazy river, nightclub, teen club, babysitting, golf, and swim-up bar. Ideal for multigenerational groups needing rooms for five or more, or families with kids and teens who all need dedicated programming.","whenToVisit":"Cozumel is best visited November through April when the Caribbean side of Mexico is dry and calm, with peak diving conditions on the reef. Rose Hall near Montego Bay also peaks December through April, avoiding Jamaica's wetter summer months. Both destinations sit in the Atlantic hurricane belt, so July through October carries elevated weather risk at either resort.","activities":"Cozumel guests have world-class scuba diving and snorkeling on the Mesoamerican Reef, island ATV tours, and ferry access to mainland Playa del Carmen just steps away. Rose Hall guests can play golf on-site, enjoy tennis, watersports on the Montego Bay strip, and take excursions to Dunn's River Falls, the Blue Mountains, or Montego Bay's Hip Strip restaurants and bars."},"dreams-acapulco-resort-and-spa-vs-dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Acapulco Resort & Spa is a family all-inclusive on Mexico's Pacific coast with a kids club for under-4s and no-reservation dining, but it trails Dreams Rose Hall on nearly every measured metric. Its overall rating sits at 7.4 versus Rose Hall's 8.5, with particularly notable gaps in food (6.5 vs 7.4), pool (6.2 vs 7.1), atmosphere (6.3 vs 7.1), cleanliness (7.9 vs 8.7), and service (7.7 vs 8.7). Dreams Rose Hall in Montego Bay, Jamaica carries a significantly broader amenity set: lazy river, teen club, nightclub, swim-up bar, tennis, golf course, babysitting, spa, gym, and rooms accommodating five or more guests. Acapulco's location rating of 7.7 is respectable but below Rose Hall's 8.6, and Acapulco's limited amenity list makes it a noticeably thinner product. Rose Hall is simply the stronger all-around resort at a mid-range price point, while Acapulco's main case rests on its Pacific Mexico setting for travelers specifically targeting that destination.","whoShouldChooseA":"Travelers committed to an Acapulco, Mexico itinerary who want a family-friendly all-inclusive with reliable cleanliness and service scores and flexible no-reservation dining, and who are comfortable with a smaller amenity footprint and lower ratings across food, pool, and atmosphere.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families who want a well-rounded Jamaican all-inclusive near Montego Bay with strong ratings across the board, a lazy river, teen and kids clubs, babysitting, golf, nightclub, swim-up bar, and rooms large enough for groups of five or more, all at a mid-range price point.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Acapulco benefits from Mexico's dry season, roughly November through April, when Pacific coast rainfall is minimal. Dreams Rose Hall sits in Jamaica's Montego Bay, where the peak dry season runs December through April. Both properties are in hurricane-adjacent zones during the June to November Atlantic season, though Acapulco faces Pacific storm risk separately. Shoulder months like May and November offer lower rates at Rose Hall with generally manageable weather.","activities":"At Dreams Acapulco, guests are well-positioned to explore Acapulco's iconic cliff divers at La Quebrada and the historic Fuerte de San Diego. At Dreams Rose Hall, Montego Bay's Hip Strip, Dunn's River Falls excursions, and Rose Hall Great House are nearby. Both resorts offer beach access, though neither scores above 6.0 on beach ratings. Rose Hall adds on-site tennis, golf, and a lazy river for guests who prefer to stay on property."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-aura-cozumel":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall Resort and Spa is a family-friendly Jamaican all-inclusive in Montego Bay with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, tennis, golf, babysitting, spa, and evening entertainment on a beach that rates a modest 6.0. Secrets Aura Cozumel is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on Cozumel island, priced two tiers higher at $$$$ versus Dreams' $$, yet scores notably lower overall at 7.4 compared to Dreams' 8.5. Dreams outperforms Secrets Aura across nearly every rating category including food (7.4 vs 7.3), pool (7.1 vs 6.9), atmosphere (7.1 vs 7.3), room (8.2 vs 7.6), value (8.2 vs 7.2), and cleanliness (8.7 vs 8.1). Secrets Aura's draw is Cozumel's world-class diving and snorkelling proximity rather than the resort itself, which offers strikingly sparse documented amenities for its premium price point. Dreams delivers far more resort infrastructure and better ratings at a significantly lower cost, while Secrets Aura trades on its island location rather than the property's own strengths.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a well-rounded Jamaican all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, babysitting, golf, tennis, and evening entertainment at a competitive mid-range price, backed by strong cleanliness and service ratings.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults-only couples, particularly divers and snorkellers, drawn specifically to Cozumel's renowned reef systems and willing to pay a premium for an island setting, accepting that the resort itself delivers modest ratings relative to its $$$$ price tier.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations share a Caribbean dry season from December through April, making that the peak window for settled weather and calm seas. Jamaica's hurricane season peaks August through October, as does Cozumel's, so both carry similar weather risk in summer. Cozumel's dive visibility is best November through May, which adds extra incentive for underwater-focused travellers to visit in the dry season.","activities":"At Dreams Rose Hall guests can play tennis, golf, use the lazy river, swim-up bar, and spa on site, with Montego Bay's Luminous Lagoon, Dunn's River Falls day trips, and Hip Strip nightlife nearby. At Secrets Aura Cozumel the main draw is off-property: the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef offers world-class scuba diving and snorkelling, while the island's San Gervasio Mayan ruins and Punta Sur Eco Beach Park round out excursion options."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-sunscape-curacao-resort-spa-and-casino":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall and Sunscape Curacao are both mid-market family all-inclusives, but Dreams Rose Hall outperforms Sunscape Curacao across nearly every rating category despite costing significantly less. Dreams Rose Hall scores 8.5 overall versus Sunscape Curacao's 7.3, with particularly stark gaps in food (7.4 vs 6.2), pool (7.1 vs 6.0), and atmosphere (7.1 vs 6.2). Dreams Rose Hall's value rating of 8.2 is also notably higher than Sunscape's 7.2, despite Sunscape sitting at a much higher price tier. Dreams Rose Hall brings a lazy river, teen club, kids club, nightclub, babysitting, golf, and tennis to Montego Bay's well-developed resort strip. Sunscape Curacao adds a casino to its offering and sits near Willemstad, a UNESCO-listed colonial capital, giving it a distinct cultural advantage. If you want strong family amenities, better food ratings, and greater value in a proven Jamaican resort destination, Dreams Rose Hall is the clear choice. If the novelty of Curacao, proximity to Willemstad, and a casino matter more than ratings or price efficiency, Sunscape Curacao makes sense.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a well-rounded Jamaican all-inclusive with a lazy river, kids and teen clubs, babysitting, nightclub, and golf at a competitive price point. The high service (8.7) and cleanliness (8.7) scores make it particularly reliable for families prioritizing consistency and value.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families or couples drawn specifically to Curacao as a destination, who want a casino on-site and easy access to the UNESCO-listed streets and diving of Willemstad. Best suited to guests for whom exploring a unique Dutch-Caribbean island matters more than ratings or price efficiency.","whenToVisit":"Jamaica's peak season runs December through April when rainfall is lowest, though hurricane season (June to November) brings lower prices to Dreams Rose Hall. Curacao sits outside the main hurricane belt, making Sunscape Curacao a more weather-reliable option year-round. Both destinations are warmest and driest January through April, making that window the safest choice for either resort.","activities":"Dreams Rose Hall guests can play golf on-site, use the tennis courts, take watersports from the beach, and access Montego Bay's lively restaurant and excursion scene nearby. Sunscape Curacao guests are well-placed to explore Willemstad's colorful colonial waterfront, world-class reef diving and snorkeling, and jeep tours of the island's rugged interior, making Curacao the stronger choice for guests who want activities beyond the resort fence."},"dreams-curacao-resort-spa-and-casino-vs-dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Curaçao and Dreams Rose Hall are both family all-inclusives in the Dreams brand, but they diverge sharply on ratings and amenity depth. Rose Hall scores a 8.5 overall versus Curaçao's 6.4, with Rose Hall outperforming on nearly every metric: service (8.7 vs 7.3), cleanliness (8.7 vs 7.8), value (8.2 vs 6.4), and rooms (8.2 vs 7.3). Curaçao edges ahead only on sleep quality (8.2 vs 8.5, negligibly) and location perception (7.9 vs 8.6, though Rose Hall wins that too). Rose Hall is the more comprehensively equipped resort, with a lazy river, teen club, babysitting, swim-up bar, nightclub, tennis, golf, gym, evening entertainment, and rooms sleeping 5 or more, all at a significantly lower price point ($$  vs $$$$). Curaçao counters with a casino and a convenient no-reservation dining policy, but its beach rating of 5.3 and overall value score are hard to overlook given the premium price. Rose Hall sits near Montego Bay with beach access, while Curaçao's appeal leans on Willemstad's Dutch colonial character rather than beach quality.","whoShouldChooseA":"Guests who want to base themselves near Willemstad's distinctive Dutch-Caribbean culture, value a casino on-site, and prioritize sleep quality and room comfort over broad amenity coverage — and who aren't primarily beach-driven or budget-conscious.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families of all sizes, including groups needing rooms for five or more, who want strong service, excellent cleanliness, a lazy river, teen club, babysitting, nightclub, and golf near Montego Bay at a price point that consistently delivers high perceived value.","whenToVisit":"Curaçao sits outside the Atlantic hurricane belt, making it a reliable year-round destination with dry, sunny conditions and low humidity peaking December through April. Rose Hall follows Jamaica's seasonal pattern — peak season runs mid-December through April for best weather, while May through November brings lower rates but some hurricane risk, with September and October the most active months.","activities":"At Dreams Rose Hall, guests can play golf, use the tennis courts, join evening entertainment and the nightclub, or explore Montego Bay's Hip Strip and Luminous Lagoon nearby. At Dreams Curaçao, the main draw beyond the resort is Willemstad itself — a UNESCO-listed Dutch colonial city with colourful architecture, diving on unspoiled reefs, and the iconic Queen Emma floating bridge, all within easy reach."},"dreams-grand-island-cancun-vs-dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Grand Island Cancun is a premium-priced ($$$$ vs $$) family all-inclusive in Costa Mujeres, Mexico, with standout cleanliness (9.0), service (9.1), and sleep quality (9.0) ratings that place it among the top performers on those metrics. Dreams Rose Hall is a more affordable Jamaican family all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a broader amenity set including a lazy river, teen club, nightclub, swim-up bar, golf course, tennis, and babysitting — areas where Cancun's offering is comparatively thin. On food, Rose Hall edges ahead marginally (7.4 vs 7.2), and both properties score nearly identically on beach (6.0 vs 6.1), pool (7.1 vs 7.1), and location (8.6 vs 8.5). The meaningful gaps are in value (8.2 vs 7.9) and atmosphere (7.1 vs 6.9), both favouring Rose Hall. Grand Island Cancun wins decisively on service, cleanliness, and room quality (8.3 vs 8.2), and suits guests who prioritise a polished, quieter experience. Rose Hall wins on amenity breadth and price efficiency for active families needing a teen club, nightclub, and golf.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children, including toddlers, who want an exceptionally clean, well-serviced Mexican all-inclusive with reservation-free dining, strong sleep quality, and a quieter Costa Mujeres setting, and who are willing to pay a premium for a more refined, less hectic atmosphere.","whoShouldChooseB":"Value-conscious families with children and teenagers who want a broad amenity lineup — lazy river, teen club, nightclub, swim-up bar, golf, tennis, and babysitting — in a Montego Bay setting, and who prioritise getting the most activity coverage per dollar spent.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak in winter. Cancun's Costa Mujeres is driest and calmest December through April, with hurricane risk highest in September and October. Montego Bay follows a similar Caribbean pattern, with peak season running mid-December through April and the wettest, most active hurricane months falling August through October. Both resorts offer better rates in the May–June shoulder window.","activities":"At Dreams Grand Island Cancun, guests have access to snorkelling, watersports, and easy day trips to Isla Mujeres and Cancun's Hotel Zone nearby. At Dreams Rose Hall, the golf course is on-site, with tennis, watersports, and the historic Rose Hall Great House — a well-known Jamaican heritage site — a short drive away. Montego Bay also offers convenient access to Dunn's River Falls excursions and river tubing."},"breathless-puerto-vallarta-resort-and-spa-vs-dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa":{"keyDifferences":"Breathless Puerto Vallarta is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on Banderas Bay at a premium price tier, with standout room (9.1), cleanliness (9.3), and service (9.2) ratings that reflect a polished, intimate experience. Dreams Rose Hall is a family-oriented Jamaican all-inclusive near Montego Bay at a budget-friendly price, with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, babysitting, golf course, and rooms that sleep five or more. Breathless edges Dreams on atmosphere (7.5 vs 7.1), rooms (9.1 vs 8.2), and cleanliness (9.3 vs 8.7), while Dreams holds its own on value (8.2) at a significantly lower price point. Both share modest beach ratings (6.5 vs 6.0), so neither is primarily a beach destination. Breathless is for adults who want a refined, high-service Pacific Mexico experience; Dreams is for families who need structured kids programming, a lazy river, and budget-accessible rates in Jamaica. If you want a polished adults-only retreat in Puerto Vallarta with excellent service and rooms, choose Breathless. If you want a family-friendly Jamaican all-inclusive with kids and teen clubs at an accessible price, choose Dreams Rose Hall.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples or groups who want a premium, adults-only Puerto Vallarta experience with exceptional cleanliness (9.3), service (9.2), and room quality (9.1) in a lively but refined atmosphere, and who are willing to pay a higher price for a noticeably more polished product.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with children of all ages who want a well-priced Jamaican all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a kids club, teen club, lazy river, babysitting, golf, and large rooms that sleep five or more, without sacrificing solid service (8.7) and cleanliness (8.7).","whenToVisit":"Puerto Vallarta's dry season runs November through April, making those months ideal for Breathless with minimal rain and comfortable temperatures. Dreams Rose Hall benefits from Jamaica's similar dry season of December through April. Both destinations see higher prices and fuller resorts over the Christmas and spring break windows. Budget-conscious travelers can find better rates at Dreams in the May–June shoulder season before peak hurricane risk arrives in August and September.","activities":"Breathless guests can explore Puerto Vallarta's vibrant Malecón boardwalk, zip-lining in the Sierra Madre, whale-watching excursions from November to March, and water-taxi trips to Yelapa. Dreams Rose Hall sits near Montego Bay's Rose Hall Great House, Chukka Caribbean Adventures, and Dunn's River Falls day trips, while on-site guests have tennis, golf, a lazy river, nightclub, and evening entertainment to keep the whole family occupied without leaving the property."},"dreams-rose-hall-resort-and-spa-vs-secrets-macao-beach-punta-cana":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Rose Hall and Secrets Macao Beach share an identical overall rating of 8.5, but diverge sharply across almost every subcategory. Secrets Macao dominates on room quality (9.1 vs 8.2), cleanliness (9.3 vs 8.7), service (9.2 vs 8.7), sleep quality (9.1 vs 8.5), beach (8.2 vs 6.0), food (8.1 vs 7.4), and atmosphere (8.1 vs 7.1). Dreams Rose Hall counters with a strong location score (8.6) near Montego Bay and a comprehensive family amenity package: kids club, teen club, babysitting, lazy river, golf course, and a nightclub. Secrets Macao is an adults-only Dominican Republic property at a significantly higher price point ($$$$  vs $$), built around polished rooms, a superior beach, and refined service with no children in sight. Dreams Rose Hall is a value-oriented Jamaican family resort where the programming breadth compensates for more modest physical ratings. If you want a well-priced Jamaican family all-inclusive with strong service and extensive kids programming near Montego Bay, choose Dreams Rose Hall. If you want a premium adults-only Dominican Republic retreat with outstanding rooms, beach, and cleanliness, choose Secrets Macao Beach.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who want a well-rounded Jamaican all-inclusive near Montego Bay with a lazy river, kids and teen clubs, babysitting, golf, and evening entertainment at a mid-range price point. The strong service and cleanliness scores mean kids and parents alike are well looked after.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and adult travelers who want a premium, adults-only Dominican Republic experience with standout room quality, an excellent beach, and exceptional cleanliness and service, and who are willing to pay a significantly higher price for a quieter, more refined atmosphere.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations enjoy reliable Caribbean weather from mid-December through April, when rainfall and hurricane risk are lowest. Jamaica's Montego Bay and the Dominican Republic's Punta Cana share similar seasonal patterns, so either resort is best booked in peak winter months. For better value and thinner crowds, consider late April through early June before the summer peak and well clear of hurricane season, which runs June through November.","activities":"At Dreams Rose Hall guests can play golf on the on-site course, take to the tennis courts, float the lazy river, dive into watersports off the beach, or catch evening entertainment and nightclub programming. Near Montego Bay, Dunn's River Falls, Luminous Lagoon, and the Hip Strip add easy off-property excursions. Secrets Macao sits on a naturally beautiful Punta Cana beach ideal for snorkelling and watersports, with Bavaro's wider resort strip and Indigenous Eyes Ecological Park close by."},"sandals-grande-antigua-resort-and-spa-vs-sandals-royal-caribbean":{"keyDifferences":"Sandals Grande Antigua and Sandals Royal Caribbean are both couples-only, premium-tier Caribbean all-inclusives with broadly similar amenity sets, but they diverge meaningfully on beach quality, service, and setting. Grande Antigua holds a commanding beach rating of 8.5 versus Royal Caribbean's 6.3, a 2.2-point gap that reflects Antigua's world-class Dickenson Bay shoreline and makes it the clear choice for beach-focused couples. Royal Caribbean counters with superior service (9.1 vs 8.6), cleanliness (9.1 vs 8.9), and value (8.3 vs 8.0), and adds snorkelling, room service, and a lazy river that Grande Antigua lacks. Location scores favour Grande Antigua (9.1 vs 8.8), while rooms are virtually tied (8.5 vs 8.6). Royal Caribbean's Montego Bay setting is busier and more urban than Antigua's quieter resort corridor. If pristine beach is the priority, Grande Antigua wins decisively. If polished service, better perceived value, and a lazy river matter more than sand quality, Royal Caribbean is the stronger performer.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples for whom beach quality is non-negotiable. Grande Antigua's 8.5 beach rating reflects one of the finest stretches of sand in the Caribbean, making it ideal for those who want to spend most of their holiday on an exceptional shoreline in a quieter, less trafficked Antiguan setting.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples who prioritise impeccable service, cleanliness, and value over beach quality. Royal Caribbean's 9.1 service and cleanliness scores, lazy river, snorkelling, and room service suit those who want a highly polished, amenity-rich Jamaican experience in Montego Bay at a slightly better return on spend.","whenToVisit":"Antigua peaks December through April with dry, breezy conditions and minimal hurricane risk; the wet season runs July through October. Montego Bay is similarly best December through April, with the hurricane season peaking August through October. Both resorts sit in the same broad Caribbean weather pattern, so timing preferences alone should not drive the choice between them.","activities":"Both resorts offer diving, fishing, tennis, spa treatments, evening entertainment, and nightclub access. Royal Caribbean adds snorkelling, a lazy river, and room service. Grande Antigua is well-positioned for exploring Antigua's 365 beaches, sailing excursions, and English Harbour's historic Nelson's Dockyard. Royal Caribbean guests can access Montego Bay's Hip Strip, Dunn's River Falls, and Jamaica's broader tour and excursion network."},"beaches-turks-and-caicos-vs-sandals-royal-caribbean":{"keyDifferences":"Beaches Turks & Caicos and Sandals Royal Caribbean both sit at the same overall rating of 8.6 and the same price tier, but they serve fundamentally different guests and deliver very different physical experiences. Beaches is a large family resort on Providenciales with a waterpark, Flowrider, heated pools, kids club for under-4s, babysitting, and rooms sleeping five or more — it earns a standout beach score of 9.6 and pool score of 9.8, reflecting Grace Bay's world-class sand and an exceptional aquatic setup. Sandals Royal Caribbean is a couples-only adults resort in Montego Bay where the beach scores a notably weaker 6.3 and pool 7.1, but it edges ahead on value (8.3 vs 7.9), service (9.1 vs 8.9), and cleanliness (9.1 vs 9.0), and adds a nightclub and room service absent at Beaches. Atmosphere at Beaches (8.1) matches Sandals (7.7 is lower), while Sandals' location score of 8.8 trails Beaches' 9.4. The core trade-off is an unmatched family beach and water experience in Turks and Caicos versus a quieter, couples-focused Jamaican retreat with better value scores.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of any age who want one of the Caribbean's best beaches paired with a full waterpark, Flowrider, kids clubs from infancy upward, babysitting, and large-group rooms — and are willing to pay a premium for that breadth of family infrastructure on Grace Bay.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples who want a quieter, adults-only Jamaican all-inclusive in Montego Bay with strong service, a nightclub, room service, and better perceived value, and who are not prioritising an exceptional beach or pool experience.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak in the dry season from December through April. Turks and Caicos stays calmer longer into spring, while Jamaica's shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates with manageable weather. Both sit in the Atlantic hurricane belt, making July through October higher risk; Turks and Caicos is statistically more exposed to direct storm tracks than Montego Bay.","activities":"At Beaches, guests can dive, snorkel, surf the Flowrider, ride the lazy river, play tennis, or join evening entertainment on one of the world's top-rated stretches of sand. At Sandals Royal Caribbean, guests can dive, snorkel, fish, kayak, play tennis, visit the nightclub, or take the resort's private island tender. Providenciales offers world-class reef diving; Montego Bay adds cultural day trips to Dunn's River Falls and the Blue Mountains."},"sandals-ochi-beach-resort-vs-sandals-royal-caribbean":{"keyDifferences":"Both are couples-only Sandals properties in Jamaica at the same price tier, but they diverge meaningfully across several ratings. Sandals Royal Caribbean edges out Ochi on nearly every measurable dimension: beach (6.3 vs. 4.5), pool (7.1 vs. 6.5), atmosphere (7.7 vs. 7.1), food (7.9 vs. 7.4), cleanliness (9.1 vs. 8.7), service (9.1 vs. 8.6), and sleep quality (8.8 vs. 8.3). Ochi's strongest card is its location score (8.2 vs. 8.8 for Royal Caribbean), and it sits within the hills and lush greenery of Ocho Rios, offering a distinctly different landscape from Montego Bay. Royal Caribbean's beach advantage is significant — a 1.8-point gap — and it adds a lazy river to its amenity set. Ochi's lower beach score reflects a narrower, less impressive stretch. If you want the stronger Sandals execution overall — better beach, cleaner property, sharper service — Royal Caribbean is the clear choice. If the Ocho Rios location or its hillside tropical setting is a priority, Ochi holds its own.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples who specifically want the lush, hilly backdrop of Ocho Rios and don't mind a weaker beach in exchange for that distinct setting. Those prioritizing room quality (8.4) and strong overall value in a less urban, greener environment than Montego Bay will find Ochi a solid fit.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples who want the best all-around Sandals execution between these two: stronger beach, better food, superior service and cleanliness scores, a lazy river, and the convenience of Montego Bay's location near Sangster International Airport. Ideal for those where polish and amenity breadth matter most.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Jamaica's peak dry season, mid-December through mid-April, when rainfall is lowest and humidity most comfortable. Montego Bay at Royal Caribbean can see slightly more airport noise during peak travel periods. Ocho Rios at Ochi is more insulated from that. Shoulder season (May, November) offers lower rates at both with manageable weather risk.","activities":"Sandals Royal Caribbean offers diving, snorkelling, fishing, tennis, a lazy river, swim-up bar, spa, gym, evening entertainment, and a nightclub — a comprehensive slate for an active or relaxed couples trip. Ocho Rios near Ochi adds off-resort appeal: Dunn's River Falls, river tubing, and Blue Hole are all close by, giving guests strong excursion options if they want to explore beyond the property."},"sandals-royal-bahamian-vs-sandals-royal-caribbean":{"keyDifferences":"Sandals Royal Bahamian sits on Nassau's Cable Beach and scores notably higher on beach (7.8 vs 6.3) and pool (8.1 vs 7.1), making it the stronger choice if sand and swimming are priorities. Sandals Royal Caribbean in Montego Bay counters with a significantly broader amenity set — gym, diving, spa, lazy river, swim-up bar, snorkelling, fishing, tennis, nightclub, and evening entertainment — compared to Royal Bahamian's more limited beach-focused offering. Royal Caribbean also edges ahead on overall score (8.6 vs 8.2), value (8.3 vs 7.7), service (9.1 vs 8.6), and cleanliness (9.1 vs 8.9). Royal Bahamian leads on sleep quality (8.9 vs 8.8) and atmosphere feels more intimate and quiet. Both share identical location scores (8.8) and the same couples-only, premium pricing structure. The core trade-off is clear: Royal Bahamian delivers a calmer, beach-forward Nassau experience, while Royal Caribbean offers a more activity-rich Montego Bay resort with stronger service scores and better perceived value despite a weaker beach.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples who want a quieter, upscale Bahamian retreat where the beach and pool are the main draw. Those who prioritise sleep, cleanliness, and a more relaxed atmosphere over a packed activity schedule, and who are content with a simpler amenity offering at a Nassau address.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples who want maximum amenity variety — diving, spa, lazy river, nightclub, tennis, snorkelling — and are willing to accept a weaker beach in exchange for a fuller resort experience. Those who weight service quality and value highly will find Royal Caribbean's stronger scores in both categories rewarding.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak between December and April when weather is driest and most reliably sunny. Nassau and Montego Bay share similar hurricane exposure from June through November, with September being the riskiest month for both. Shoulder seasons in May and November offer lower rates with generally acceptable weather at either property.","activities":"Royal Bahamian guests are best served by Nassau's cable beach strip, nearby Atlantis day passes, and downtown Nassau's straw market and colonial architecture. Royal Caribbean guests can dive and snorkel directly from the resort, use the on-site tennis courts and spa, and access Montego Bay's Hip Strip, Dunn's River Falls excursions, and the broader roster of organised Jamaican cultural and adventure tours."},"sandals-barbados-vs-sandals-royal-caribbean":{"keyDifferences":"Sandals Barbados sits in the lively St. Lawrence Gap on Barbados's south coast, while Sandals Royal Caribbean occupies a beachfront stretch in Montego Bay, Jamaica. Both are couples-only, similarly priced, and score identically on food (7.9), atmosphere (7.7), and sleep quality (8.8), but meaningful gaps emerge elsewhere. Royal Caribbean edges Barbados on overall score (8.6 vs 8.4), service (9.1 vs 8.7), value (8.3 vs 7.8), and cleanliness (9.1 vs 9.0). Barbados counters with a notably better beach rating (7.0 vs 6.3) and a marginally higher pool score (7.4 vs 7.1). Both resorts score similarly on rooms (8.7 vs 8.6) and location (8.7 vs 8.8). Royal Caribbean's amenity list is more extensive, adding a lazy river, fishing, and nightclub to the standard Sandals toolkit. If beach quality matters most, Barbados has the clear edge; if service, value, and a broader activity roster drive the decision, Royal Caribbean pulls ahead.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples who prioritize a superior beach experience and are drawn to the cosmopolitan buzz of St. Lawrence Gap, Barbados's most social coastal strip. Those who value impeccably clean, comfortable rooms and don't need a full nightclub or lazy river to feel entertained.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples who want the best service scores, stronger perceived value, and a more comprehensive amenity set—lazy river, nightclub, fishing—in a classic Montego Bay setting. A good fit for those willing to trade a slightly weaker beach rating for a more well-rounded resort experience.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations share a broadly similar Caribbean dry season from December through April, when rainfall is lowest and crowds are highest. Barbados's south coast can see brisk Atlantic trade winds year-round, which some couples enjoy but windsensitive guests may not. Jamaica's Montego Bay is drier on the north coast and least rainy November through March. Both resorts command peak pricing over the Christmas and February school-holiday windows; shoulder months like May and November offer better value at both properties.","activities":"At Sandals Barbados, St. Lawrence Gap puts restaurants, bars, and local nightlife within walking distance, supplementing the resort's on-site diving, snorkelling, and pools. Sandals Royal Caribbean offers the same core watersports with the addition of a lazy river, fishing excursions, and a nightclub on property, while Montego Bay's Hip Strip, Dunn's River Falls, and ATV tours are accessible nearby. Both properties offer spa treatments, tennis, evening entertainment, and swim-up bars as standard."},"sandals-royal-barbados-vs-sandals-royal-caribbean":{"keyDifferences":"Sandals Royal Barbados and Sandals Royal Caribbean are both couples-only, premium-priced Sandals properties, but they differ meaningfully across several ratings. Royal Barbados scores higher on rooms (8.9 vs 8.6) and sleep quality (9 vs 8.8), suggesting quieter, more refined accommodation, while Royal Caribbean pulls ahead on overall score (8.6 vs 8.1), value (8.3 vs 7.5), service (9.1 vs 8.5), and cleanliness (9.1 vs 9.0). Neither property excels on beach — Royal Barbados rates 6.8 and Royal Caribbean a weaker 6.3 — so neither should be chosen primarily for shoreline. Royal Caribbean adds a lazy river, nightclub, diving, and fishing to its amenity roster, giving it a broader activity spread. Royal Barbados is positioned in Barbados's Oistins area with a location score of 8.7, while Royal Caribbean sits in Montego Bay at 8.8. For couples prioritising room quality and sleep, Barbados edges ahead; for those wanting better service scores, stronger value, and more on-site activities, Jamaica wins.","whoShouldChooseA":"Couples who prioritise beautifully appointed, quiet rooms and excellent sleep quality in a polished Barbados setting. Those willing to trade a slightly lower value score for a more intimate atmosphere and the character of an Oistins-area property will find Royal Barbados the better fit.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples who want the best service scores in the Sandals portfolio alongside stronger value for money, a broader activity lineup — including diving, fishing, a lazy river, and a nightclub — and the energy of a Montego Bay resort. Royal Caribbean suits couples who want to stay busy rather than simply unwind.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak in the December–April dry season when rainfall is lowest and humidity manageable. Barbados sits outside the main hurricane belt, making it a safer year-round bet, including shoulder months like May and November. Jamaica's Montego Bay is more exposed to Atlantic storm systems June through October, so Royal Caribbean is best avoided mid-hurricane season unless securing travel insurance and flexible booking terms.","activities":"Royal Caribbean's listed amenities cover diving, snorkelling, fishing, tennis, a lazy river, swim-up bar, spa, gym, buffet, evening entertainment, and a nightclub — enough to fill a week without leaving the property. Near both resorts, couples can explore local restaurants, rum distilleries, and markets. Barbados adds world-class surf at nearby Soup Bowl and historic Bridgetown, while Montego Bay offers Hip Strip dining, Dunn's River Falls day trips, and ATV excursions."},"beaches-barbados-vs-sandals-royal-caribbean":{"keyDifferences":"Beaches Barbados is a family all-inclusive in Barbados with a kids club catering to children under 4 and older, built around strong room, cleanliness, service, and sleep quality scores all at 9.0 or above, with a solid location rating of 8.1. Sandals Royal Caribbean is a couples-only adults all-inclusive in Montego Bay, Jamaica, priced at the premium end, with a notably broader amenity set including diving, snorkelling, spa, lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, fishing, tennis, gym, and evening entertainment. Sandals edges Beaches on food (7.9 vs 6.0) and value (8.3 vs 7.4), while Beaches leads on beach (7.4 vs 6.3) and pool (7.4 vs 7.1). Both score identically on cleanliness and service (9.1) and atmosphere is close (7.7 vs 7.5). The fundamental split is purpose: Beaches is a family resort where children are central to the design, while Sandals Royal Caribbean is a luxury couples retreat with a much deeper activity menu and a higher price tag to match.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children, including toddlers under 4, who want a clean, well-serviced Barbados all-inclusive with strong rooms and a genuine kids club. The high sleep quality and service scores suggest a resort that handles the logistics of family travel well.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples, specifically two adults, who want a premium Jamaican all-inclusive in Montego Bay with serious amenity depth: diving, snorkelling, spa, lazy river, nightclub, and fishing all included. Those who prioritize food quality and overall value at the luxury end will find the ratings justify the higher price.","whenToVisit":"Both Barbados and Jamaica enjoy their best weather from mid-December through April, when Caribbean rainfall and hurricane risk are lowest. Barbados sits south of the main hurricane belt, giving it a slight edge for year-round reliability. Jamaica's peak season aligns with Sandals' highest pricing, so shoulder months of May or November offer better value with generally acceptable weather at both destinations.","activities":"At Beaches Barbados, the focus is on beach and pool time with family-oriented programming through the kids clubs. At Sandals Royal Caribbean, guests can dive, snorkel, fish, play tennis, use the gym, float the lazy river, and access spa treatments, all within the all-inclusive rate. Both properties sit near enough to their respective island capitals, Bridgetown and Montego Bay, to support day trips for local dining, markets, and cultural sites."},"beaches-exuma-vs-sandals-royal-caribbean":{"keyDifferences":"Beaches Exuma is a family all-inclusive on Great Exuma in the Bahamas, a quieter, more remote destination celebrated for its extraordinary natural setting — its beach and location ratings of 9.0 and 8.9 reflect genuinely exceptional surroundings. Sandals Royal Caribbean is a couples-only premium all-inclusive in Montego Bay, Jamaica, with a far broader amenity set: gym, diving, spa, lazy river, nightclub, swim-up bar, tennis, fishing, and evening entertainment. Where Beaches Exuma scores very high on rooms (9.2), cleanliness (9.2), service (9.2), and sleep quality (9.0), its food rating of 6.4 is a notable weak point. Sandals Royal Caribbean counters with a stronger food score (7.9), better value rating (8.3 vs 7.4), and a beach score of only 6.3 — well below Exuma's 9.0. Exuma is a remote, nature-first family escape with outstanding physical surroundings; Sandals Royal Caribbean is a feature-rich couples resort in a busier Jamaican setting where the amenity breadth compensates for a more modest beach.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children who want an uncrowded, nature-immersed Bahamian escape with stunning beaches, excellent rooms, and attentive service, and who are willing to accept limited dining variety and fewer organized amenities in exchange for a genuinely remote, beautiful setting.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples who want a premium Jamaican all-inclusive with an extensive amenity lineup — diving, spa, lazy river, nightclub, tennis, and strong food — and who prioritize atmosphere, value, and resort facilities over beach quality or a secluded destination.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations peak December through April when rainfall is lowest and crowds are highest. The Bahamas hurricane season runs June through November, with September the riskiest month — Exuma's remoteness can complicate travel during disruptions. Jamaica shares a similar hurricane window, but Montego Bay's well-established infrastructure handles weather events more smoothly. Shoulder months of May and November offer meaningful price relief at both properties.","activities":"Beaches Exuma leans on its natural environment — the Exuma Cays, swimming pigs, and bonefishing are nearby draws, though the resort's own activity programming is limited. Sandals Royal Caribbean covers far more on-property ground: certified diving, snorkelling, fishing, tennis, a spa, lazy river, gym, and a nightclub keep guests occupied without leaving. Montego Bay also offers easy access to Dunn's River Falls, ATV excursions, and golf, giving Sandals guests strong off-property options too."},"beaches-runaway-bay-vs-sandals-royal-caribbean":{"keyDifferences":"Beaches Runaway Bay is a Jamaican family all-inclusive with a kids club for all ages including under-4s, posting strong scores in cleanliness (9.1), service (9.0), room quality (9.0), and sleep quality (8.9), but lagging notably in food (5.5) and pool (6.9). Sandals Royal Caribbean is a couples-only adults-only all-inclusive in Montego Bay rated at a premium price point, with a broader amenity set including diving, spa, lazy river, swim-up bar, nightclub, and fishing, and meaningfully stronger food ratings (7.9 vs 5.5) and location (8.8 vs 7.4). The food gap of 2.4 points is the single sharpest difference and a practical consideration for any guest. Sandals also edges ahead on atmosphere (7.7 vs 7.5) and beach (6.3 vs 7.2, though Beaches wins here). If you want a family-friendly Jamaican all-inclusive with excellent rooms and service at accessible pricing, choose Beaches Runaway Bay. If you want a couples-only Montego Bay all-inclusive with significantly better food, a richer amenity lineup, and a premium feel, choose Sandals Royal Caribbean.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of any age, including toddlers, who prioritize excellent rooms, high cleanliness, and attentive service in a Jamaican setting. Best suited to parents who want structured kids programming and are willing to accept more modest food and pool ratings in exchange for strong value.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples only seeking a premium Montego Bay adults-only experience with strong food ratings, a wide range of amenities including diving, spa, lazy river, and nightclub, and one of the better location scores in Jamaica. Ideal for those who want a polished, activity-rich romantic escape at a higher price point.","whenToVisit":"Both resorts benefit from Jamaica's dry season, mid-December through April, when rainfall is lowest and trade winds keep temperatures comfortable. Beaches Runaway Bay on the north coast and Sandals Royal Caribbean in Montego Bay share similar weather patterns. Avoid September and October, peak hurricane months. Shoulder season May through June offers lower rates with generally reliable weather at both properties.","activities":"Beaches Runaway Bay guests are largely limited to on-property kids club programming and beach and pool use. Sandals Royal Caribbean offers a substantially broader on-site activity menu including scuba diving, snorkelling, fishing, tennis, spa treatments, a lazy river, and evening entertainment with a nightclub. Both resorts allow access to nearby Montego Bay and Ocho Rios for off-property excursions including Dunn's River Falls, river tubing, and cultural tours."},"beaches-saint-vincent-vs-sandals-royal-caribbean":{"keyDifferences":"Beaches Saint Vincent is a family all-inclusive on the lesser-visited island of Saint Vincent, with a kids club for all ages including under-4s, and standout scores in room quality (9.2), cleanliness (9.3), service (9.3), and sleep quality (9.2). Its food rating (6.0) and beach score (7.2) are modest, and its amenity list is lean compared to most Beaches properties. Sandals Royal Caribbean is a couples-only adults all-inclusive in Montego Bay, Jamaica, loaded with amenities including diving, snorkelling, spa, lazy river, nightclub, swim-up bar, and tennis, with strong scores across food (7.9), location (8.8), rooms (8.6), and value (8.3). The beach score at Sandals Royal Caribbean (6.3) is actually lower than Beaches Saint Vincent (7.2), which is surprising given Montego Bay's reputation. Beaches Saint Vincent wins on room quality, cleanliness, and service by a meaningful margin, while Sandals Royal Caribbean wins on food, amenity breadth, and value. The fundamental split is family versus couples-only, making these resorts suited to entirely different travellers.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children, including infants and toddlers, who want an intimate, immaculately kept all-inclusive on an unspoiled Caribbean island. Those who prioritise exceptional rooms, service, and cleanliness over a wide amenity list or destination dining will feel well rewarded here.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and honeymooners who want a well-rounded adults-only Jamaican all-inclusive with strong food, a wide activity menu including diving and snorkelling, spa access, nightlife, and reliable value at a premium price point in the established Montego Bay resort corridor.","whenToVisit":"Saint Vincent sits south of the main Atlantic hurricane belt, giving it a relatively sheltered profile, with drier conditions from January through April. Montego Bay follows the standard Caribbean pattern with its driest, most settled weather from mid-December through April. Both destinations are best avoided during peak hurricane season, August through October, though Saint Vincent carries somewhat lower storm risk than Jamaica.","activities":"At Beaches Saint Vincent, guests are largely dependent on resort amenities and guided excursions to explore Saint Vincent's volcanic interior, waterfalls, and botanical gardens, one of the oldest in the Western Hemisphere. Sandals Royal Caribbean guests can dive, snorkel, fish, and use the lazy river and swim-up bar on property, and access Montego Bay's shopping, nightlife, and excursions including Dunn's River Falls and river tubing within easy reach."},"breathless-montego-bay-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Breathless Montego Bay is an adults-only Jamaican all-inclusive on the Montego Bay strip with a nightclub, evening entertainment, tennis, swim-up bar, and a beach, catering to a lively social crowd. Zoëtry Marigot Bay is a family-friendly St. Lucia boutique all-inclusive nestled in the dramatic Marigot Bay, with fishing, babysitting, a spa, and an intimate atmosphere that prioritizes tranquility over activity. The beach gap is stark: Breathless scores 5.5 versus Zoëtry's 2.5, meaning neither excels but Breathless is meaningfully better for sand. Zoëtry pulls ahead on service (9.1 vs 8.7), cleanliness (9.2 vs 8.9), sleep quality (9.2 vs 8.3), atmosphere (8.6 vs 7.4), and food (8.6 vs 7.5), reflecting its quieter, more refined setting. Breathless counters with nightlife, tennis, and a more energetic social scene. If you want an adults-only Jamaican party-leaning all-inclusive with entertainment and a beach, choose Breathless. If you want a serene, high-service boutique St. Lucia experience in a stunning bay setting with superior food and sleep quality, choose Zoëtry.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples or groups who want a lively, social all-inclusive in Montego Bay with a nightclub, evening entertainment, swim-up bar, and tennis. Best suited to those who prioritize atmosphere and activity over culinary refinement or absolute quiet.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples or small families seeking a serene, boutique St. Lucia retreat with exceptional service, outstanding food, and some of the highest sleep quality scores in the region. Guests who value atmosphere and cleanliness over nightlife or a wide beach.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations share a broadly similar Caribbean dry season from December through April. Jamaica's Montego Bay sees its peak crowds around Christmas and spring break; St. Lucia's Marigot Bay is especially stunning in the dry months when the lush hills are vivid. Both destinations can experience hurricane-season humidity and rain from July through October, though St. Lucia sits slightly south of the main hurricane belt.","activities":"At Breathless Montego Bay, guests can use the beach, play tennis, enjoy evening entertainment and the nightclub, and access Montego Bay's nearby Hip Strip, shopping, and excursions to Dunn's River Falls or Rose Hall. At Zoëtry Marigot Bay, guests can fish directly from the resort, explore the iconic Marigot Bay by water, visit the Pitons, go hiking, and take boat trips to Castries or Soufrière for volcano and rainforest excursions."},"secrets-wild-orchid-montego-bay-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Wild Orchid Montego Bay is a large adults-only Jamaican all-inclusive on a busy Montego Bay strip with a casino, nightclub, lazy river, diving, tennis, and evening entertainment at a premium price point. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a small, family-friendly boutique all-inclusive tucked into the lush hillsides above Marigot Bay, offering exceptional service and food but a beach rating of just 2.5 versus Secrets' 6.8. Both share the same overall score of 8.6, but the differences are stark: Secrets wins on beach, pool, and entertainment breadth, while Zoëtry leads on food (8.6 vs. 7.9), cleanliness (9.2 vs. 9.0), service (9.1 vs. 8.9), and sleep quality (9.2 vs. 8.8). Secrets suits guests who want a lively, amenity-heavy adult escape; Zoëtry suits those who prioritize intimate atmosphere, outstanding dining, and the dramatic natural setting of St. Lucia's Marigot Bay over a traditional beach experience.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults who want a lively, amenity-packed Jamaican all-inclusive with a casino, nightclub, lazy river, diving, and evening entertainment in Montego Bay. Well-suited to couples and groups who want a buzzy social atmosphere alongside solid beach access and strong service.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families or couples who prioritize exceptional food, impeccable service, and a serene boutique atmosphere over beach quality. Ideal for those drawn to St. Lucia's dramatic hillside scenery and the intimate character of Marigot Bay, and who won't miss a traditional resort beach.","whenToVisit":"Both islands peak December through April when rainfall is low and trade winds keep temperatures comfortable. Jamaica's Montego Bay and St. Lucia share a similar wet season from June through November. Zoëtry's hillside setting means it can feel especially lush and green in the shoulder months, while Secrets benefits from Montego Bay's reliable beach weather in the dry season.","activities":"At Secrets Wild Orchid, guests can dive, play tennis, use the lazy river and swim-up bar, gamble at the casino, and catch nightly entertainment. Nearby Montego Bay offers duty-free shopping, the Hip Strip, and excursions to Dunn's River Falls. At Zoëtry Marigot Bay, guests can fish, explore the bay by water taxi, and day-trip to the Piton peaks, Sulphur Springs, and St. Lucia's rainforest interior."},"breathless-cancun-soul-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Breathless Cancun Soul Resort & Spa is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive in Puerto Morelos with a beach rated 7.8, nightclub, evening entertainment, and swim-up bar — a lively, social property built around atmosphere and a strong room score of 9.1. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a family-friendly boutique all-inclusive on a marina bay in St. Lucia with exceptional food (8.6 vs. 7.6), service (9.1 vs. 8.8), and sleep quality (9.2 vs. 8.5), but a beach score of just 2.5, reflecting its bay setting rather than a traditional sandy beach. Breathless wins on beach access, nightlife, and entertainment; Zoëtry wins on dining, tranquility, and service refinement. The atmosphere gap — Zoëtry 8.6 vs. Breathless 7.5 — signals a quieter, more intimate experience despite Zoëtry's family classification. If you want a lively adults-only Cancun all-inclusive with beach access, a nightclub, and energetic entertainment, choose Breathless. If you want a serene, food-forward St. Lucia boutique all-inclusive on a scenic bay with polished service, choose Zoëtry Marigot Bay.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults and couples who want a social, energetic Mexican all-inclusive with strong beach access, a nightclub, swim-up bar, and evening entertainment in a well-connected Puerto Morelos location without sacrificing room quality or cleanliness.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families or couples seeking a quiet, refined St. Lucia boutique experience where exceptional food, attentive service, and a stunning marina bay setting matter more than a traditional beach — ideal for those who prioritize atmosphere and gastronomy over sand.","whenToVisit":"Cancun's Puerto Morelos is best from December through April, avoiding hurricane season peaks from August to October. St. Lucia's dry season runs January through April, though the island sees year-round tropical conditions with brief showers even outside peak hurricane months of August to October. Both destinations command premium pricing over the December to April high season.","activities":"Breathless Cancun guests have direct Caribbean beach access, a gym, spa, nightclub, and evening entertainment on-site, with Puerto Morelos's coral reef reserve and cenotes nearby for snorkelling and diving excursions. Zoëtry Marigot Bay offers fishing, a spa, and gym on a scenic marina, with St. Lucia's Piton Mountains, volcanic mud baths, rainforest hikes, and sailing excursions all accessible from the bay."},"dreams-playa-esmeralda-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Playa Esmeralda is a large Dominican Republic family all-inclusive in El Cedro with a kids club, teen club, babysitting, gym, spa, and buffet with no-reservation restaurants, earning strong room (9.2), cleanliness (9.3), service (9.2), and location (9.0) scores on a legitimate beach rated 8.3. Zoëtry Marigot Bay is a boutique St. Lucia all-inclusive tucked into the dramatic Marigot Bay, with a swim-up bar, fishing, spa, gym, and babysitting, posting excellent food (8.6), atmosphere (8.6), and room (8.8) scores, but a beach rating of just 2.5 that reflects the bay's near-absence of a sandy shore. The 4.4-point food gap favors Zoëtry considerably, while Dreams holds a clear edge for families who need proper beach access. Dreams is the better-value, beach-forward family resort; Zoëtry trades sand for scenery and culinary quality in a more intimate, design-conscious setting. If you want a genuine Caribbean beach with full kids programming at a large Dominican resort, choose Dreams. If you want exceptional food and stunning bay views in a boutique St. Lucia setting and can live without a real beach, choose Zoëtry.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children or teenagers who need a real beach, a dedicated kids club, and a teen program in a large Dominican Republic all-inclusive with strong room quality and service at a price point that rewards the extras.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples or small families with older children who prioritize exceptional food (8.6), intimate boutique atmosphere, and the cinematic scenery of Marigot Bay over a beach, and who are comfortable with a maximum of three guests per room.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations sit in the Caribbean hurricane belt. The Dominican Republic's peak dry season runs December through April, with El Cedro's eastern location adding some year-round rain. St. Lucia's dry season peaks January through April; the bay's lush hillsides stay green year-round. Both resorts command higher rates over Christmas and New Year. Shoulder months of May and November offer better pricing at each property.","activities":"At Dreams Playa Esmeralda, guests access watersports along an 8.3-rated beach, plus spa treatments, gym sessions, and supervised kids and teen programming. Zoëtry Marigot Bay offers fishing excursions directly from the bay, a swim-up bar, spa, and easy access to Marigot Bay's sailing scene and nearby Soufrière for volcano hikes, sulphur springs, and the iconic Piton peaks."},"secrets-st-james-montego-bay-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets St. James Montego Bay is an adults-only Jamaican all-inclusive on Montego Bay's coastline with a beach, heated pool, casino, nightclub, tennis, diving, evening entertainment, and swim-up bar — a full-amenity resort built around activity and social energy. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a family-friendly boutique all-inclusive tucked into St. Lucia's dramatic Marigot Bay, with a spa, fishing, babysitting, and an intimate atmosphere that prioritizes calm over programming. The beach gap is stark: Secrets rates 6.8 versus Zoëtry's 2.5, reflecting Zoëtry's marina-bay setting where beach access is minimal. Food tells the opposite story — Zoëtry scores 8.6 against Secrets' 7.9. Service and sleep quality also favor Zoëtry at 9.1 and 9.2 versus 8.9 and 8.8. Secrets wins on sheer amenity breadth — casino, nightclub, diving, tennis — while Zoëtry wins on refinement and tranquility in a spectacular St. Lucian bay setting. Both sit at $$$$ pricing with near-identical overall scores of 8.5 and 8.6.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults-only couples or groups who want a lively, amenity-rich Jamaican all-inclusive with a beach, casino, nightclub, diving, and evening entertainment in Montego Bay. Best for those who want social atmosphere and activity variety over boutique refinement.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples or small families drawn to boutique intimacy, exceptional food, and the extraordinary scenery of Marigot Bay. Ideal for guests who prioritize outstanding service, peaceful sleep, and St. Lucia's natural beauty over beach access or a broad activity program.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations share a similar Caribbean dry season from December through April, making that window the most reliable for either resort. Jamaica's Montego Bay and St. Lucia's Marigot Bay both see heavier rainfall from June through November. Shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates with generally reasonable weather at both properties.","activities":"Secrets guests can dive, play tennis, use the casino, and explore Montego Bay's Hip Strip, duty-free shopping, and nearby Green Grotto Caves. Zoëtry guests can fish in Marigot Bay, arrange sailing and watersports through local operators, visit the Pitons UNESCO site, hike the Soufrière volcanic landscape, and explore St. Lucia's lush rainforest interior — all within easy reach of the bay."},"dreams-sands-cancun-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Sands Cancun and Zoëtry Marigot Bay share a $$$$ price tier and family positioning, but their ratings tell very different stories. Dreams Sands leads on beach (6.5 vs 2.5) and pool (6.0 vs 7.4), with a lazy river and kids club for under-4s making it a genuine family beach resort on the Cancun Hotel Zone. Zoëtry Marigot Bay, tucked into a lush St. Lucia inlet, scores dramatically higher on food (8.6 vs 6.9), atmosphere (8.6 vs 6.7), room quality (8.8 vs 7.8), cleanliness (9.2 vs 8.5), service (9.1 vs 8.7), and sleep quality (9.2 vs 8.1). Zoëtry's beach rating of 2.5 signals this is a marina-side property, not a sand destination. Dreams Sands is the better pick for families who want a proper beach and pool setup in Cancun; Zoëtry is the stronger resort by nearly every quality metric, but guests must accept that swimming happens in a pool or bay rather than on a traditional beach.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with toddlers and young children who want a genuine Caribbean beach holiday in Cancun, with a lazy river, kids club for under-4s, no-reservation dining, and solid service ratings at a price point that delivers clear beach and pool value.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with older children or couples who prioritize exceptional food, service, room quality, and atmosphere over a beach, and who want the dramatic rainforest-meets-marina setting of Marigot Bay with babysitting, a spa, and some of the highest cleanliness and sleep scores in the Caribbean.","whenToVisit":"Cancun's peak season runs December through April, when dry weather and calm seas make Dreams Sands most appealing; hurricane season (June–November) brings risk but lower rates. St. Lucia's dry season is January through April, with lush green scenery year-round making Zoëtry's rainforest setting particularly striking in the wetter months, though brief tropical showers are common from June through November.","activities":"Dreams Sands guests have Cancun's Hotel Zone on their doorstep — jet skiing, parasailing, Isla Mujeres day trips, and Chichen Itza excursions are easy to arrange. Zoëtry Marigot Bay offers fishing, spa treatments, and swimming in the iconic bay, with Piton hikes, Soufrière volcano tours, mud baths, and catamaran sails around St. Lucia all accessible from the marina."},"secrets-mirabel-cancun-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Mirabel Cancún is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on the Cancún hotel strip, earning a strong beach rating of 7.3 and a location score of 9.0, with snorkelling, evening entertainment, and a swim-up bar rounding out a conventional but well-executed resort experience. Zoëtry Marigot Bay sits in a lush St. Lucia inlet, family-friendly with babysitting and a family cap of three per room, but its beach score of just 2.5 signals that guests are here for the dramatic bay setting rather than a sandy stretch. Secrets edges Mirabel on beach and location, while Zoëtry leads on food (8.6 vs 8.2) and atmosphere (8.6 vs 8.0), reflecting its more intimate, wellness-oriented character. Secrets delivers a livelier, more amenity-dense Cancún adults-only experience; Zoëtry trades the beach for rainforest scenery, fishing, and a quieter pace. If you want a polished adults-only Cancún all-inclusive with snorkelling, evening entertainment, and a genuine beach, choose Secrets Mirabel. If you want a serene, food-forward St. Lucia boutique experience in a scenic bay setting, choose Zoëtry Marigot Bay.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adult couples and solo travellers who want a polished, lively Cancún all-inclusive with a real beach, snorkelling, evening entertainment, and strong room quality at a price point that delivers clear value. The 9.0 location score signals easy access to Cancún's broader dining and nightlife beyond the resort.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with young children, or couples seeking a quiet, atmosphere-rich retreat in St. Lucia's Marigot Bay who prioritise exceptional food, rainforest scenery, and personalised service over beach access. The 8.6 food and atmosphere scores reflect a genuinely distinctive, unhurried experience that rewards guests who value setting over amenities.","whenToVisit":"Cancún's dry season runs December through April, with peak clarity for snorkelling and reliable sunshine. St. Lucia's dry season also peaks January through April, though its lush landscape means some rainfall year-round. Both destinations command higher prices over Christmas and New Year; February and March offer the best balance of weather and value at either property.","activities":"At Secrets Mirabel, guests snorkel directly off the resort, use the swim-up bar, and access Cancún's Zona Hotelera for water parks, deep-sea fishing, and Mayan ruins at Chichén Itzá within day-trip distance. At Zoëtry Marigot Bay, guests fish the bay, explore St. Lucia's Piton mountains, visit sulphur springs, take catamaran excursions, and sail into Soufrière for one of the Caribbean's most dramatic shoreline approaches."},"dreams-sapphire-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Sapphire Resort & Spa is a large Mexican family all-inclusive in Puerto Morelos with a kids club, teen club, infant care, diving, snorkelling, yoga, tennis, nightclub, swim-up bar, and evening entertainment on a Caribbean-facing beach. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a boutique Saint Lucian family all-inclusive set in the dramatic Marigot Bay, with a swim-up bar, spa, fishing, and babysitting, but a much thinner activity roster and a beach rating of just 2.5 versus Dreams Sapphire's 5. Zoëtry scores meaningfully higher on food (8.6 vs 7.2), atmosphere (8.6 vs 6.9), cleanliness (9.2 vs 8.8), sleep quality (9.2 vs 8.5), and location (8.8 vs 8.3), reflecting a quieter, more intimate property. Dreams Sapphire counters with a vastly broader amenity set for families with children of all ages. If you want a full-service Mexican family all-inclusive with structured kids programming, watersports, and nightly entertainment, choose Dreams Sapphire. If you want a refined, tranquil Saint Lucian boutique experience with outstanding food and atmosphere in a scenic bay, choose Zoëtry Marigot Bay.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages, including infants, who want a large Mexican all-inclusive with dedicated kids and teen clubs, babysitting, diving, snorkelling, tennis, and a lively evening entertainment and nightclub program on the Riviera Maya.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with older children or couples seeking a quiet, intimate Saint Lucian all-inclusive where outstanding food (8.6), exceptional sleep quality (9.2), and the striking scenery of Marigot Bay matter more than a broad activity menu or a proper beach.","whenToVisit":"Puerto Morelos is driest and calmest from December through April, with peak crowds around the holidays and spring break; May through November brings humidity and hurricane risk. Saint Lucia's dry season also runs December through April, with calmer seas ideal for the bay setting; June through November is wetter and coincides with the Atlantic hurricane season, though Saint Lucia sits at the southern edge of the hurricane belt.","activities":"Dreams Sapphire guests can dive, snorkel, fish, play tennis, and take yoga classes on-site, with the Mesoamerican Reef and Puerto Morelos village a short trip away. Zoëtry Marigot Bay guests can fish and explore the bay by water, with Saint Lucia's rainforest hikes, the Piton peaks, Sulphur Springs, and sailing excursions out of Castries or Rodney Bay accessible nearby."},"sunscape-dorado-pacifico-ixtapa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Sunscape Dorado Pacifico Ixtapa and Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia share the same overall rating (8.6) and value score (8.3), but diverge sharply on almost every other dimension. Sunscape is a Mexican Pacific family beach resort in Ixtapa with a beach rating of 6.8 versus Zoëtry's 2.5, making it the clear winner for traditional sand-and-surf holidays. Zoëtry counters with dramatically superior food (8.6 vs. 6.4), service (9.1 vs. 8.6), cleanliness (9.2 vs. 8.6), sleep quality (9.2 vs. 8.0), and room quality (8.8 vs. 8.2), reflecting its boutique, upscale St. Lucia positioning at a higher price tier. Zoëtry's atmosphere rating of 8.6 versus Sunscape's 6.3 signals a meaningful experiential gap. Sunscape is a larger, more conventional Mexican family resort where the beach and location drive satisfaction. Zoëtry is a refined, intimate St. Lucia property set on Marigot Bay where food, service, and atmosphere are the core draws, not the beach.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a straightforward Mexican Pacific all-inclusive with direct beach access, a reliable location score of 8.8, and solid overall value at a lower price point than boutique Caribbean alternatives. Best for those prioritizing beach time over dining or atmosphere.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with older children or couples willing to pay premium rates for exceptional food (8.6), service (9.1), and cleanliness (9.2) in an intimate St. Lucia bay setting. Ideal for guests who prioritize a refined, tranquil atmosphere over beach quality.","whenToVisit":"Sunscape Ixtapa is best visited November through April when Mexico's Pacific coast is dry and sunny, avoiding the June–October hurricane and rainy season. Zoëtry Marigot Bay benefits from St. Lucia's drier season of December through May, though the island sees less hurricane exposure than northern Caribbean destinations, making shoulder months like November and June reasonable options.","activities":"At Sunscape Ixtapa, guests can use the resort beach, explore Ixtapa's marina and shops, take day trips to nearby Zihuatanejo, or try local sportfishing. Zoëtry Marigot Bay offers fishing, a spa, swim-up bar, and babysitting on property, with the iconic Marigot Bay itself ideal for sailing excursions, plus easy access to Soufrière, the Piton mountains, and St. Lucia's volcanic mud baths nearby."},"secrets-tulum-resort-and-beach-club-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Tulum is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on the Riviera Maya with a strong room score (8.9), excellent sleep quality (9.1), and a standout atmosphere rating (8.5), but its beach score is a notable weak point at 5.5 and food sits at a modest 7.9. Zoëtry Marigot Bay is a family-friendly St. Lucia all-inclusive tucked into a dramatic Caribbean bay, scoring significantly higher on food (8.6 vs 7.9), service (9.1 vs 8.8), location (8.8 vs 7.8), and value (8.3 vs 7.9), though its beach score is even lower at 2.5, reflecting its bay rather than beach-fronted setting. Secrets Tulum leans into atmosphere and room quality for couples seeking a polished adults-only escape in Mexico, while Zoëtry Marigot Bay delivers a more intimate, service-led experience in a visually spectacular St. Lucia inlet with a gym, spa, fishing, and babysitting. If you want an adults-only Mexican retreat with exceptional rooms and atmosphere, choose Secrets Tulum. If you want superior food, service, and a breathtaking bay setting in St. Lucia at better value, choose Zoëtry Marigot Bay.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults-only couples or solo travelers who prioritize beautifully appointed rooms, a high-energy atmosphere, and a well-established Riviera Maya all-inclusive experience, and who are not dependent on a standout beach for their holiday.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples or small families who value exceptional food, attentive service, and a strikingly scenic bay location in St. Lucia over a conventional beach setup, and who appreciate a more intimate, wellness-oriented all-inclusive atmosphere.","whenToVisit":"Secrets Tulum is best visited November through April, when Yucatán humidity drops and sargassum seaweed is least likely to affect the coast. Zoëtry Marigot Bay suits travel from December through May, St. Lucia's dry season, when rainfall is minimal and the bay's lush hillside scenery is most vivid without the September–November hurricane risk.","activities":"At Secrets Tulum, guests have access to the resort's pools, spa, and no-reservation dining, with Tulum's archaeological ruins, cenotes, and Sian Ka'an Biosphere Reserve nearby. At Zoëtry Marigot Bay, guests can fish, use the swim-up bar, spa, and gym on-site, while St. Lucia's Piton mountains, sulfur springs, rainforest hikes, and sailing excursions out of Marigot Bay itself are all within easy reach."},"zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia-vs-zoetry-montego-bay-jamaica":{"keyDifferences":"Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia and Zoëtry Montego Bay Jamaica share a brand and a luxury price point, but differ meaningfully in guest profile, setting, and ratings. Marigot Bay accepts families with children (max 3 per room) and scores higher across nearly every category: overall 8.6 vs. 8.2, food 8.6 vs. 8.1, atmosphere 8.6 vs. 8.0, location 8.8 vs. 8.1, and value 8.3 vs. 7.9. Marigot Bay's beach score is notably low at 2.5 — the property sits on a marina bay rather than a true beach — while Montego Bay scores a modest but better 4.0 on beach. Pool scores also favor Marigot Bay at 7.4 vs. 6.7. Both score closely on rooms (8.8 vs. 8.7) and sleep quality (9.2 vs. 8.9). Marigot Bay offers babysitting, fishing, a buffet, swim-up bar, spa, and gym. Montego Bay is adults-only, making the choice straightforward for families. For those without children, Montego Bay's Jamaican setting competes, but Marigot Bay's stronger ratings across the board give it a consistent edge.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples seeking a serene, high-rated luxury all-inclusive tucked into St. Lucia's scenic Marigot Bay. Ideal if you prioritize exceptional service, cleanliness, and atmosphere over a beach, and want babysitting and fishing alongside a spa and swim-up bar.","whoShouldChooseB":"Adults-only couples or solo travelers who want a quieter, boutique Jamaican all-inclusive experience near Montego Bay without children present. Best suited to those who value a peaceful atmosphere and solid room quality over top-tier beach or pool amenities.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations enjoy best conditions from mid-December through April, when rainfall and hurricane risk are lowest. St. Lucia's Marigot Bay can be lush and green year-round, with its sheltered bay offering calm waters even outside peak season. Montego Bay follows Jamaica's standard dry season pattern; avoid the late August to October hurricane peak for both.","activities":"At Marigot Bay, guests can explore one of the Caribbean's most photographed natural harbors, take fishing excursions, visit the Marigot Bay marina village, or venture to nearby Soufrière for volcano and rainforest tours. Montego Bay guests have access to Dunn's River Falls day trips, Negril beaches, and the Hip Strip's dining and nightlife scene, with snorkeling and catamaran excursions readily available offshore."},"sunscape-dominicus-la-romana-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Sunscape Dominicus La Romana is a family-focused Dominican Republic all-inclusive on a strong beach (8.0) with waterparks for both younger and older kids, a teens club, and kids club, making it a conventional but functional beach-holiday option. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a boutique, wellness-inflected St. Lucia all-inclusive tucked into Marigot Bay with virtually no beach (2.5) but exceptional scores across food (8.6 vs. 6.2), atmosphere (8.6 vs. 6.2), cleanliness (9.2 vs. 8.5), service (9.1 vs. 8.3), room quality (8.8 vs. 8.0), and sleep quality (9.2 vs. 8.1). Sunscape wins on beach and kids infrastructure; Zoëtry wins on almost everything else. Pool scores also favor Sunscape slightly (6.2 vs. 7.4 reversed — Zoëtry leads there too). Sunscape suits families who prioritize sand and waterparks; Zoëtry suits families or couples who want refinement, exceptional service, and a dramatic bay setting over beach access. Note Zoëtry limits rooms to three guests maximum, so larger families should factor that in.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children of all ages who put a real beach and waterpark infrastructure first. Sunscape's kids club, teen club, and two waterparks make it purpose-built for keeping children entertained across age groups, and its strong beach rating (8.0) and location score (8.3) deliver the classic Dominican beach-holiday formula.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples or small families of up to three who prioritize exceptional food, impeccable service, and a tranquil boutique atmosphere over beach access. Zoëtry's wellness amenities, spa, and stunning Marigot Bay setting suit guests who want a refined, intimate St. Lucia experience rather than a conventional all-inclusive beach holiday.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations share a broadly similar Caribbean dry season from December through April, when rainfall and hurricane risk are lowest. The Dominican Republic's La Romana area is drier and more predictable year-round than St. Lucia, which sits in a wetter, greener part of the eastern Caribbean. St. Lucia's lush scenery peaks in the wet season (June–November) but brings higher rain probability; book Zoëtry in the dry season for the most reliable conditions.","activities":"At Sunscape Dominicus, guests focus on beach time, waterpark use across two separate parks, and kids and teen club programming, with La Romana's Altos de Chavón cultural village and Casa de Campo golf nearby. At Zoëtry Marigot Bay, guests can fish, use the spa and gym, swim from the pool or dock, and explore St. Lucia's Piton peaks, Sulphur Springs, rainforest hikes, sailing excursions, and the restaurants and bars of Marigot Bay village just outside the resort."},"dreams-bahia-mita-surf-and-spa-resort-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Bahia Mita and Zoëtry Marigot Bay share the same overall rating of 8.6 and price tier, but diverge sharply in what they deliver. Dreams Bahia Mita is a full-family Mexican Pacific resort in Punta de Mita with a kids club, babysitting, evening entertainment, and no-reservation dining, sitting on an actual beach (rated 4.8, modest but present) with strong room scores (9.0) and cleanliness (9.2). Zoëtry Marigot Bay is a boutique St. Lucian property nestled in a dramatic marina bay where beach access is essentially nonexistent (rated 2.5), but food quality is markedly superior (8.6 vs. 7.3), atmosphere is noticeably higher (8.6 vs. 7.4), and sleep quality edges ahead (9.2 vs. 8.8). Zoëtry caps rooms at three guests and skews intimate rather than activity-dense, with a swim-up bar and fishing but no kids club or evening entertainment. Dreams is the broader family operation; Zoëtry suits those who prioritize cuisine, atmosphere, and St. Lucian scenery over beach access or structured programming.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young children who want a Pacific Mexico all-inclusive with a kids club, babysitting, evening entertainment, and open-seating restaurants. The strong room scores, cleanliness ratings, and Punta de Mita location make it an easy, well-rounded choice for families seeking convenience and consistent service.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples or small families with older children who prioritize exceptional food (8.6), a striking marina-bay atmosphere, and boutique intimacy over beach access. Guests drawn to St. Lucia's lush scenery, fishing excursions, and a quieter, more culinary-focused all-inclusive experience will feel at home here.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Bahia Mita benefits from Mexico's dry season, roughly November through April, when Pacific swell and rainfall are minimal. Zoëtry Marigot Bay sits in St. Lucia's drier corridor from December through May, avoiding the heavier Caribbean rainfall of summer and early autumn. Both properties see peak pricing over the Christmas and New Year period, so shoulder months like November or late April offer better value at either resort.","activities":"Dreams Bahia Mita guests can surf the Punta de Mita break, explore the Riviera Nayarit coastline, take boat trips to the Marietas Islands, and use the resort spa and gym. Zoëtry Marigot Bay guests can fish the St. Lucian waters, hike to the Pitons, tour Castries, use the swim-up bar and spa, and explore Marigot Bay's sheltered marina by water taxi or kayak."},"dreams-los-cabos-suites-golf-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Los Cabos and Zoëtry Marigot Bay share the same overall rating (8.6) and value score (8.3), but diverge meaningfully across several categories. Zoëtry leads in food (8.6 vs 7.5, a full point gap), service (9.1 vs 8.7), cleanliness (9.2 vs 8.9), atmosphere (8.6 vs 7.2), and sleep quality (9.2 vs 8.6), reflecting its boutique, wellness-oriented character in a lush St. Lucian bay. Dreams scores higher on room ratings (8.7 vs 8.8, essentially tied) and location (8.4 vs 8.8, slight Zoëtry edge). Critically, neither resort has a strong beach: Dreams scores a weak 3.3, Zoëtry an even lower 2.5, so neither destination suits guests prioritizing a classic Caribbean beach experience. Dreams is a larger Mexican family resort near San Jose del Cabo with a kids club and no-reservation dining, while Zoëtry is a more intimate, high-service St. Lucian property with a spa, swim-up bar, babysitting, and notably superior food and atmosphere scores in a dramatic rainforest-meets-bay setting.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with very young children who want a larger Mexican resort near Los Cabos, value no-reservation flexible dining, and appreciate strong room quality and cleanliness without needing a serious beach. The Baja Pacific coastline is rugged rather than swimmable, so guests should come for the scenery and resort amenities, not sand.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families or couples seeking a boutique, high-service St. Lucian all-inclusive where exceptional food, atmosphere, and sleep quality matter most. With a gym, spa, fishing, and swim-up bar set against Marigot Bay's iconic scenery, it suits guests drawn to a refined, intimate experience rather than a lively, activity-heavy resort.","whenToVisit":"Los Cabos is driest and most reliably sunny from November through May, avoiding hurricane season and summer heat. St. Lucia's dry season runs January through April, when Marigot Bay's lush hillsides are at their greenest without heavy rainfall. Both destinations see inflated pricing over Christmas and New Year; shoulder months like November or early December offer better rates at comparable conditions.","activities":"At Dreams Los Cabos, guests can arrange whale watching from January to March, sport fishing charters out of San Jose del Cabo marina, ATV tours into the desert, and day trips to the famous El Arco arch at Land's End. At Zoëtry Marigot Bay, on-site fishing, snorkelling, and spa treatments anchor the experience, with Piton hikes, zip-lining through the rainforest, and catamaran cruises to Soufrière accessible nearby."},"dreams-natura-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Natura Resort & Spa is a family all-inclusive on Mexico's Caribbean coast near Puerto Morelos, with a beach, kids club for under-4s, and no-reservation dining in a well-rated room and cleanliness package scoring 8.8 and 9.0 respectively. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a boutique family all-inclusive tucked into a dramatic St. Lucian bay, with a spa, swim-up bar, fishing, babysitting, and gym, limited to three guests per room. The most telling gap is in food: Zoëtry scores a full 1.3 points higher at 8.6 versus Dreams Natura's 7.3, and service follows the same pattern at 9.1 versus 8.7. Beach quality sharply separates them in the opposite direction: Dreams Natura scores 4.5 while Zoëtry scores just 2.5, making neither a strong beach destination but Dreams Natura the less disappointing of the two. Atmosphere at Zoëtry is notably stronger at 8.6 versus Dreams Natura's 6.9, reflecting the intimate bay setting. Dreams Natura is the better choice for young families wanting beach access and kids programming; Zoëtry suits those prioritising food, service, and atmosphere over beach quality.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with very young children who want a Mexican Caribbean all-inclusive with a dedicated under-4s kids club, beach access, and no-reservation casual dining in a clean, well-maintained resort near Puerto Morelos at a predictable price point.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with older children or couples who prioritise exceptional food, attentive service rated 9.1, and a distinctive boutique atmosphere in a dramatic St. Lucian bay setting, and who won't miss a strong beach.","whenToVisit":"Puerto Morelos is best visited November through April to avoid Atlantic hurricane season and peak summer heat. St. Lucia's dry season runs January through April, with the wettest months from June through November. Both destinations carry some hurricane or tropical storm risk in late summer and fall, making the winter and early spring months the safest and most comfortable window for either resort.","activities":"Dreams Natura guests can explore Puerto Morelos's nearby coral reef, one of the most accessible reef systems on the Mexican Caribbean, along with cenote diving, Mayan ruins at Tulum and Cobá, and jungle zip-lining. Zoëtry Marigot Bay guests can arrange fishing excursions directly through the resort, take water taxis into Castries, hike to the Piton peaks, visit the volcanic sulphur springs at Soufrière, and explore St. Lucia's lush rainforest interior."},"secrets-st-lucia-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Both resorts sit at the same overall rating of 8.6 and share Saint Lucia as their setting, but they diverge sharply on beach access and guest profile. Secrets St. Lucia is an adults-only resort with a beach score of 6.8, while Zoëtry Marigot Bay sits in the sheltered marina bay with a striking beach score of just 2.5, indicating it is not a beach resort in any conventional sense. Zoëtry compensates with a higher food rating of 8.6 versus Secrets' 8.0, a better room score of 8.8 versus 8.6, and a stronger atmosphere rating of 8.6 versus 7.8. Secrets edges ahead on service at 9.2 versus 9.1 and offers the convenience of no restaurant reservations required. Zoëtry is a family-permitting property set in the lush, dramatic Marigot Bay, making it a scenic inland-water experience rather than a beachfront holiday. If you are prioritizing a beach, Secrets is the clearer choice. If you want refined dining, atmospheric jungle-bay surroundings, and a spa-led retreat, Zoëtry wins despite its negligible beach offering.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults-only couples and solo travelers who want polished service, strong sleep quality, reliable beachfront access, and no-reservation dining in a well-rated Saint Lucia resort. Best suited to those who value a classic Caribbean beach experience with a refined, crowd-free adults atmosphere.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples or small families seeking a boutique, atmosphere-rich retreat on the dramatic Marigot Bay who have no expectation of a traditional beach holiday. Guests drawn to scenic marina surroundings, superior dining, a spa, and a quiet, design-led escape will find Zoëtry the more rewarding choice.","whenToVisit":"Saint Lucia's dry season runs from January through April, offering the clearest skies and calmest seas for both properties. Zoëtry's sheltered bay position means it is less exposed to Atlantic swells year-round, while Secrets benefits most from dry-season conditions for beach use. The shoulder months of May and December offer competitive pricing with still-reasonable weather at both resorts.","activities":"Secrets guests can enjoy the beach, pool, and on-site dining without reservations. Zoëtry offers fishing, a swim-up bar, gym, babysitting, and spa facilities within its Marigot Bay setting. Both properties are positioned near the lush interior of Saint Lucia, giving access to Piton hikes, zip-lining, waterfall tours, whale watching, and the historic capital Castries, all reachable by boat or short drive from either resort."},"dreams-tulum-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Tulum is a large family all-inclusive on Mexico's Caribbean coast with a kids club for under-4s, a beach, and casual dining that requires no reservations, scoring a solid overall 8.2 but showing clear weaknesses in food (7.0) and beach quality (6.3). Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a boutique family all-inclusive nestled in St. Lucia's iconic Marigot Bay, with a gym, spa, swim-up bar, babysitting, and fishing, scoring a superior overall 8.6 with standout marks for food (8.6), cleanliness (9.2), service (9.1), and sleep quality (9.2). The beach gap is stark: Dreams Tulum scores 6.3 while Zoëtry scores just 2.5, reflecting Marigot Bay's marina-style setting rather than a traditional beach. Dreams Tulum wins on beach access and kids club programming for toddlers; Zoëtry wins decisively on food, service, atmosphere, and overall refinement at a comparable price point. If you want a Mexican Caribbean beach all-inclusive with a kids club and laid-back dining, choose Dreams Tulum. If you want a boutique St. Lucian all-inclusive with exceptional food, service, and atmosphere in a stunning bay setting, choose Zoëtry Marigot Bay.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with very young children who prioritize direct beach access and a structured kids club in a casual Mexican Caribbean setting, and who can accept more modest food and pool ratings in exchange for a reliable Tulum location at a fair price.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with older children or couples who value exceptional food, immaculate cleanliness, and attentive service over beach access, and who want a boutique, atmosphere-rich St. Lucian retreat tucked inside one of the Caribbean's most photogenic bays.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Tulum is best visited December through April to avoid Mexico's hurricane season and summer heat. Zoëtry Marigot Bay benefits from St. Lucia's drier season, January through April, when rainfall is lowest and the lush bay scenery is at its most vivid. Both resorts sit in the Caribbean basin, so avoiding the September–October peak hurricane window applies to either destination.","activities":"At Dreams Tulum, guests can explore nearby Mayan ruins at Tulum Archaeological Zone, snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef, or visit Sian Ka'an Biosphere Reserve. At Zoëtry Marigot Bay, guests can charter boats from the marina, go fishing, hike the Piton mountains, tour banana plantations, or take a sailing trip along St. Lucia's dramatic volcanic coastline. Both resorts offer watersports and spa treatments on-site."},"sunscape-coco-punta-cana-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Sunscape Coco Punta Cana is a family-oriented Dominican Republic all-inclusive on a beach in Punta Cana, rated 8.2 overall, with a kids club, teen club, and a beach-forward layout at a mid-range price point. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a premium boutique all-inclusive tucked into St. Lucia's dramatic Marigot Bay, rated 8.6 overall, with a spa, swim-up bar, babysitting, and standout scores in cleanliness (9.2), sleep quality (9.2), service (9.1), and rooms (8.8). The most striking gap is the beach: Sunscape rates 6.8 versus Zoëtry's 2.5, meaning guests at the latter are coming for the lush bay setting, not a sandy stretch. Sunscape's food rates just 6.2 against Zoëtry's 8.6, a significant difference. Sunscape suits families who want a conventional beach holiday in the Dominican Republic at a lower price; Zoëtry suits those willing to pay more for exceptional service, refined food, and an intimate rainforest-bay atmosphere in St. Lucia.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with children and teenagers who want a straightforward Dominican Republic beach all-inclusive with dedicated kids and teen programming at a mid-range price point. If an active beach, a familiar Punta Cana setting, and structured kids activities are the priority, Sunscape Coco delivers solid value.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples or small families with young children who want a boutique, high-service St. Lucia experience over a traditional beach holiday. Zoëtry's exceptional cleanliness, room quality, and food scores make it ideal for guests who prioritise atmosphere, intimacy, and refinement over a conventional sandy shoreline.","whenToVisit":"Both destinations enjoy dry, sunny conditions from December through April, making that the peak window for either resort. Punta Cana's shoulder months of May and November offer lower rates with manageable weather. St. Lucia's dry season runs January to April; the lush green landscape that defines Marigot Bay is at its most dramatic after the wetter months of June through October, though brief showers remain possible year-round.","activities":"At Sunscape Coco, the beach and pool are the core draws alongside the kids and teen clubs. Near Punta Cana, guests can access golf courses, deep-sea fishing, dune buggy excursions, and zip-lining. At Zoëtry Marigot Bay, the spa, fishing, and swim-up bar anchor the property, and St. Lucia's broader offer includes sailing to the Pitons, whale watching, volcano tours, rainforest hikes, and some of the Caribbean's best diving at sites like Anse Chastanet."},"zoetry-curacao-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Both properties carry the Zoëtry boutique all-inclusive brand at the $$$$ price tier, but they diverge sharply in guest profile, setting, and performance. Zoëtry Curaçao is adults-only near Willemstad with a beach rating of just 3.3, while Zoëtry Marigot Bay sits in one of the Caribbean's most dramatic natural harbors in Saint Lucia, though its beach scores an even lower 2.5. The St. Lucia property outperforms on nearly every rated dimension: overall 8.6 vs 7.6, food 8.6 vs 8.1, service 9.1 vs 8.2, cleanliness 9.2 vs 8.8, value 8.3 vs 7.4, and atmosphere 8.6 vs 8.0. Zoëtry Curaçao holds its own in room quality at 8.8, matching St. Lucia exactly, and its Willemstad location offers a culturally rich urban backdrop that Marigot Bay cannot replicate. Marigot Bay accepts families with children up to three per room, while Curaçao is strictly adults-only. If you want a refined adults-only Caribbean retreat near a UNESCO-listed colonial city, choose Curaçao. If you want higher-rated service, food, and atmosphere in a stunning Saint Lucian bay setting with family access, choose Marigot Bay.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults-only couples or solo travelers who want a quiet, design-conscious Zoëtry retreat near Willemstad's colorful Dutch colonial architecture and vibrant island culture, and who prioritize exceptional room quality and sleep comfort over beach access or the broadest amenity set.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and small families who want the highest-performing Zoëtry experience overall, with outstanding service, cleanliness, and food ratings in the spectacular natural setting of Marigot Bay, and who are happy trading a conventional beach for world-class Saint Lucian scenery and amenities including a spa, swim-up bar, and babysitting.","whenToVisit":"Curaçao sits outside the hurricane belt and enjoys consistent sunshine and low rainfall year-round, making any month a reliable choice. Saint Lucia's dry season runs January through April, offering the most settled weather for Marigot Bay. Both islands see peak pricing over the December–January holidays; shoulder months of May and November offer better value at both properties.","activities":"Curaçao guests have easy access to Willemstad's historic Punda district, vibrant coral reef diving, snorkeling at Tugboat Beach, and island jeep tours. Marigot Bay guests can arrange fishing excursions directly through the resort, explore the Piton Mitan rainforest, take boat trips to Soufrière and the volcanic Sulphur Springs, or arrange catamaran sails along Saint Lucia's lush western coastline."},"dreams-puerto-morelos-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Puerto Morelos is a large family all-inclusive on Mexico's Riviera Maya with waterparks for both young children and older kids, a beach, and no-reservation dining, rated 7.8 overall with solid room (8.5) and cleanliness (8.6) scores but weaker beach (5.0) and pool (6.7) ratings. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a boutique family all-inclusive in a dramatic St. Lucian bay setting, rated 8.6 overall with standout scores in service (9.1), cleanliness (9.2), sleep quality (9.2), location (8.8), and food (8.6), but a near-absent beach score of 2.5. Dreams edges Zoëtry on family water infrastructure with its dual waterparks, while Zoëtry leads on nearly every experiential metric by meaningful margins, particularly food (8.6 vs. 7.0) and atmosphere (8.6 vs. 6.9). The tradeoff is scale versus refinement: Dreams delivers a busy, amenity-rich Mexican beach resort experience; Zoëtry delivers a quieter, higher-quality boutique stay in a spectacular Caribbean bay where swimming is from the marina rather than a surf beach.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with young and older children who want a feature-packed Mexican all-inclusive with dual waterparks, a beach, and casual no-reservation dining in a well-established Riviera Maya setting. Best for families who prioritize activity infrastructure and volume of offerings over boutique polish.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with older children or couples who prioritize exceptional service, food, and atmosphere over beach access. Ideal for guests drawn to St. Lucia's volcanic scenery, a tranquil marina-bay setting, and a boutique experience where quality across every touchpoint consistently outperforms the typical all-inclusive.","whenToVisit":"Puerto Morelos is best from December through April when Caribbean winds keep humidity manageable and rainfall is low. St. Lucia's dry season also runs December through May, with the most settled weather in the early months of the year. Both destinations see elevated pricing over the Christmas and New Year period. Hurricane season affects both from June through November, though St. Lucia sits outside the primary hurricane belt.","activities":"At Dreams Puerto Morelos, guests can use the waterparks, beach, and access nearby Puerto Morelos village and Mesoamerican reef snorkeling. Zoëtry Marigot Bay offers fishing, spa treatments, and is well-positioned for St. Lucia excursions including Piton hikes, waterfall tours, mud baths at Sulphur Springs, and sailing trips along the island's spectacular west coast."},"dreams-playa-bonita-panama-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Playa Bonita Panama is a family all-inclusive near Panama City, positioned as a city-adjacent beach resort with a kids club for under-4s, casual dining without reservations, and solid cleanliness and service scores. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a boutique adults-oriented family all-inclusive — maximum three guests per room — nestled in the dramatic Marigot Bay with a spa, swim-up bar, gym, fishing, and babysitting. The rating gaps are significant: Zoëtry outscores Dreams across nearly every category, with overall 8.6 vs. 7.4, food 8.6 vs. 6.7, atmosphere 8.6 vs. 6.5, service 9.1 vs. 8.1, and cleanliness 9.2 vs. 8. Neither property excels on beach — Zoëtry scores a 2.5 and Dreams a 4 — but Zoëtry compensates with its stunning bay setting and location score of 8.8. Dreams offers better access to Panama City's urban attractions and suits younger families, while Zoëtry delivers a quieter, more refined St. Lucian experience at a measurably higher quality level across food, rooms, and atmosphere.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with very young children who want a Panama City-adjacent all-inclusive with no-reservation dining, a toddler-focused kids club, and easy access to urban Panama for day trips. Guests who prioritize location convenience over atmosphere and food quality will find Dreams Playa Bonita a practical base.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples and small families with older children who want a boutique, high-quality St. Lucian all-inclusive in the scenic Marigot Bay setting, with outstanding food, service, and cleanliness scores. Guests seeking a tranquil, refined atmosphere with a spa and swim-up bar rather than a lively beach-strip resort.","whenToVisit":"Panama's dry season runs December through April, making those months the best window for Dreams Playa Bonita. St. Lucia's dry season similarly peaks January through April, when Zoëtry Marigot Bay offers the most reliable sunshine. Both destinations sit outside the primary hurricane belt, though St. Lucia can see rain year-round; January to March represents the sweet spot for either resort.","activities":"Dreams Playa Bonita guests can take day trips into Panama City, visit the Panama Canal, and explore Casco Viejo. Zoëtry Marigot Bay guests can go fishing directly through the resort, kayak the protected bay, hike to Gros Piton, take a catamaran to Soufrière, or visit the iconic drive-in volcano. Zoëtry's on-site spa adds a wellness dimension that Dreams does not match."},"sunscape-puerto-vallarta-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Sunscape Puerto Vallarta is a mid-to-upper price family all-inclusive on Mexico's Pacific coast with a broad amenity set and solid scores for location (8.3), service (8.3), and cleanliness (8.2), but notably weak food (6.2) and beach (5.3) ratings. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a premium boutique family all-inclusive tucked into a rainforest-framed bay in St. Lucia, with standout scores across food (8.6), atmosphere (8.6), rooms (8.8), cleanliness (9.2), service (9.1), and sleep quality (9.2), though its beach score (2.5) is strikingly low given its marina-bay setting. The gap in food quality is significant at 2.4 points, and Zoëtry leads on nearly every experiential metric. Sunscape offers a more conventional Pacific Mexico resort experience at a lower price, while Zoëtry delivers a refined, intimate Caribbean atmosphere at a premium. If you want a well-located Puerto Vallarta family all-inclusive at a competitive price with reliable service, go to Sunscape. If you want a boutique St. Lucia resort with exceptional food, service, and atmosphere in a dramatic natural setting, go to Zoëtry Marigot Bay.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families or couples who want a well-located Puerto Vallarta all-inclusive at a mid-range price point, value clean, well-serviced surroundings, and are less focused on dining quality or beach experience.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with older children or couples who want a premium, intimate St. Lucia all-inclusive with exceptional food, immaculate rooms, and a lush rainforest-bay atmosphere, and who prioritize service and ambiance over a traditional beach experience.","whenToVisit":"Puerto Vallarta's dry season runs November through April, making those months ideal for Sunscape. St. Lucia's drier, calmer season also falls between December and April, aligning well for Zoëtry Marigot Bay. Both destinations see higher rainfall from July through October, with St. Lucia sitting in the Atlantic hurricane belt, so late summer travel carries more weather risk for the St. Lucia option.","activities":"At Sunscape Puerto Vallarta, guests can explore Puerto Vallarta's Malecón boardwalk, Old Town art galleries, whale watching from December to March, and zip-lining excursions in the Sierra Madre. At Zoëtry Marigot Bay, guests can go fishing, use the swim-up bar and spa, or venture out to St. Lucia's Piton peaks, sulphur springs, and sailing trips along the island's dramatic volcanic coastline."},"sunscape-sabor-cozumel-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Sunscape Sabor Cozumel is a mid-market Mexican family all-inclusive on Cozumel island with direct beach access, rated 7.6 overall, where the main draw is its location score of 8.0 and strong service at 8.2, though food (6.1) and beach (5.8) ratings are notably weak. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a premium boutique family resort in Saint Lucia rated 8.6 overall, commanding a four-dollar price point and outperforming Sunscape across nearly every category: food is 2.5 points higher at 8.6, rooms score 8.8 versus 7.2, cleanliness reaches 9.2, and service hits 9.1. The one area where Sunscape wins is beach access — Zoëtry's beach rating is a striking 2.5, reflecting Marigot Bay's marina-cove setting rather than a conventional sandy stretch. Sunscape suits budget-conscious families wanting an island base for Cozumel diving and reef snorkelling; Zoëtry suits guests who prioritise exceptional food, immaculate rooms, and a dramatic rainforest-bay atmosphere and can absorb the premium price.","whoShouldChooseA":"Budget-conscious families or divers who want a straightforward Mexican island all-inclusive on Cozumel, using the resort primarily as a comfortable base for world-class reef diving and snorkelling rather than expecting standout food or a premium beach experience.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with older children or couples who want a refined, boutique Saint Lucian all-inclusive where exceptional food (8.6), spotless rooms (8.8 cleanliness), and a dramatic Marigot Bay setting matter more than a traditional sandy beach, and who are comfortable paying a significant premium for it.","whenToVisit":"Cozumel's dry season runs December through April, avoiding Atlantic hurricane risk and offering the clearest water for diving. St. Lucia's dry season also peaks December through May, though the island receives rain year-round due to its mountainous terrain. Both destinations see elevated prices and demand over the Christmas and New Year period. Shoulder months like November or early May offer better value at both properties.","activities":"Cozumel is one of the world's premier diving and snorkelling destinations, with the Mesoamerican Reef minutes offshore; Sunscape guests can also explore the island's town centre and Mayan ruins nearby. At Zoëtry Marigot Bay, guests have access to fishing, a spa, and a swim-up bar within the property, while Saint Lucia beyond the gates offers the Pitons, rainforest hikes, sulphur springs, and sailing charters from Castries."},"dreams-cozumel-cape-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Cozumel Cape Resort & Spa is a family all-inclusive on Mexico's Cozumel island, rated 7.3 overall, with a kids club for under-4s, no-reservation dining, and solid scores for location (8.3), room (8.2), and cleanliness (8.5), though food (6.8) and beach (5.3) are notably weak. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a boutique St. Lucia all-inclusive rated 8.6 overall, with exceptional scores across service (9.1), cleanliness (9.2), sleep quality (9.2), and food (8.6), though its beach rating of 2.5 is the lowest possible differentiator — Marigot Bay is a sheltered marina inlet, not a swim beach. Dreams Cozumel leads only in beach potential relative to Zoëtry, yet still scores just 5.3 there. Zoëtry outperforms Dreams across every other rated category, often by significant margins — atmosphere (8.6 vs 6.9), value (8.3 vs 7.5), room (8.8 vs 8.2). Both are $$$$, making Zoëtry the stronger option for quality-focused travelers willing to forgo a traditional beach setting.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with toddlers who want a structured Mexican island all-inclusive with a dedicated under-4 kids club, casual no-reservation dining, and easy access to Cozumel's world-class diving and snorkeling reefs, accepting that food quality and the beach itself will be unremarkable.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples or small families (maximum three per room) who prioritize exceptional food, impeccable service, and a serene St. Lucia marina atmosphere over a traditional beach holiday — and who would rather have a swim-up bar, spa, and near-perfect cleanliness scores than a sandy shoreline.","whenToVisit":"Cozumel's dry season runs December through April, with peak diving visibility in summer despite higher humidity. St. Lucia's dry season similarly peaks January through April, avoiding the Atlantic hurricane season that affects both destinations from June through November. Both resorts offer better value and availability in the shoulder months of May and November, though St. Lucia carries slightly higher storm risk in that window.","activities":"Dreams Cozumel guests can access some of the Caribbean's best diving and snorkeling directly off Cozumel's reefs, plus watersports and Mayan archaeological sites nearby. Zoëtry Marigot Bay guests can fish, use the spa and gym, and explore St. Lucia's dramatic volcanic landscape, pitons, sulphur springs, and rainforest zip-lining — Marigot Bay itself is a picturesque marina hub with sailing and boat charter options."},"dreams-acapulco-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Acapulco is a family-oriented Mexican Pacific all-inclusive in Acapulco with a kids club for under-4s and no-reservation dining, sitting at a mid-market price point with modest ratings across food (6.5), beach (6.0), and pool (6.2). Zoëtry Marigot Bay is a premium St. Lucia all-inclusive nestled in a dramatic Caribbean bay, rated significantly higher across nearly every category: food (8.6 vs 6.5), atmosphere (8.6 vs 6.3), service (9.1 vs 7.7), cleanliness (9.2 vs 7.9), and sleep quality (9.2 vs 7.9). The beach gap is notable in the opposite direction — Dreams scores a low 6.0 while Zoëtry scores an even lower 2.5, meaning neither property is a classic beach destination, but Zoëtry compensates with its stunning bay setting, spa, swim-up bar, and exceptional room quality (8.8). Dreams is more accessible and family-volume oriented; Zoëtry is a quieter, more refined luxury escape at a higher price with a maximum of three guests per room.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with very young children who want a no-fuss Mexican Pacific all-inclusive with a kids club for under-4s, casual dining without reservations, and a more budget-accessible price point in Acapulco.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples or small families seeking a high-end, intimate St. Lucia retreat in a spectacular bay setting, where exceptional service (9.1), pristine cleanliness (9.2), and a spa-led atmosphere matter more than a traditional beach.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Acapulco is best visited November through April when Pacific Mexico is dry and sunny; hurricane season brings humidity and rain from June onward. Zoëtry Marigot Bay benefits from St. Lucia's dry season, December through April, when trade winds keep the lush hillside setting comfortable. Both destinations are warmer and wetter from June through October.","activities":"Dreams Acapulco guests can explore Acapulco's famous cliff divers at La Quebrada and the city's waterfront promenade nearby. Zoëtry Marigot Bay offers fishing, a swim-up bar, and spa on property, with St. Lucia's Piton peaks, rainforest hikes, sulphur springs, and sailing excursions all accessible from the bay. Zoëtry's activity offering is more nature-driven and scenically rewarding."},"secrets-aura-cozumel-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Secrets Aura Cozumel is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on the island of Cozumel, rated overall 7.4, with strong location (8.3) and service (8.3) scores but a notably weak beach rating (5.5) and middling food (7.3) and pool (6.9) scores. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a family-friendly boutique all-inclusive nestled in St. Lucia's dramatic Marigot Bay, rated overall 8.6, with exceptional cleanliness (9.2), sleep quality (9.2), service (9.1), and room scores (8.8), though its beach rating is even lower at 2.5. Secrets Aura is the livelier, adults-only island escape with Cozumel's world-class diving and snorkelling on its doorstep, while Zoëtry Marigot Bay wins on virtually every quality metric — food, atmosphere, rooms, cleanliness, and service — in a rainforest-bay setting that trades beach for sheer boutique refinement. The 1.2-point overall gap and Zoëtry's near-perfect cleanliness and sleep scores reflect two meaningfully different tiers of experience despite the same price level.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults-only couples or solo travellers who want a base in Cozumel primarily to dive or snorkel the Mesoamerican Reef, value a no-reservation dining policy for flexibility, and are willing to trade resort polish for one of the Caribbean's best underwater destinations on their doorstep.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families or couples — including those with young children given the babysitting service — who prioritise immaculate rooms, outstanding food, and exceptional service over beach access, and want a boutique St. Lucia experience inside the postcard scenery of Marigot Bay.","whenToVisit":"Cozumel's dry season runs December through April, with calmest seas and peak diving visibility; hurricane season peaks September to October. St. Lucia's dry season similarly runs January through April, with the island's lush green landscape best appreciated just after the wet season in November and December. Both destinations are most in demand — and most expensive — over the Christmas and New Year holiday window.","activities":"Secrets Aura Cozumel sits steps from some of the world's top dive and snorkel sites along the Mesoamerican Barrier Reef, with glass-bottom boat tours, sport fishing, and the town of San Miguel a short ride away. Zoëtry Marigot Bay offers spa treatments, swimming in the bay, sport fishing, and easy access to St. Lucia's hiking trails, the Piton peaks, sulphur springs, and sailing excursions from one of the Eastern Caribbean's most photogenic natural harbours."},"sunscape-curacao-resort-spa-and-casino-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Sunscape Curacao is a family all-inclusive on Curaçao near Willemstad with a casino, spa, and beach access, scoring a modest 7.3 overall with notably weak food (6.2), pool (6.0), and atmosphere (6.2) ratings. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a boutique adults-leaning all-inclusive (max 3 guests per room) tucked into St. Lucia's dramatic Marigot Bay, scoring 8.6 overall with exceptional service (9.1), cleanliness (9.2), rooms (8.8), and food (8.6) — but an almost unusable beach rating of 2.5. Sunscape's strongest suit is location proximity to Willemstad (8.1) and cleanliness (8.0), while Zoëtry dominates on nearly every quality metric. The critical trade-off is beach versus refinement: Sunscape gives you actual beach access, while Zoëtry sits in a stunning bay setting where swimming is limited. If you want a family Caribbean all-inclusive with a casino and genuine beach in Curaçao at a mid-tier quality level, go to Sunscape. If you want a boutique, high-quality St. Lucia experience with outstanding food, rooms, and service in a scenic bay setting and can forgo a real beach, go to Zoëtry.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families who want a conventional Caribbean all-inclusive with beach access, a casino, and proximity to Willemstad's colourful city sights, and who prioritise having a proper beach over top-tier food or atmosphere.","whoShouldChooseB":"Couples or small families with older children who prioritise exceptional food, immaculate rooms, and personalised service in one of the Caribbean's most photogenic bay settings, and won't miss a traditional beach.","whenToVisit":"Curaçao sits outside the hurricane belt and is reliably dry year-round, making Sunscape a strong choice from December through April when other Caribbean islands see more rain. Zoëtry Marigot Bay is best visited during St. Lucia's dry season, January through April, when the bay's lush hillsides are vivid and rainfall is minimal; the island's wetter months run June through November.","activities":"Sunscape guests can explore Willemstad's UNESCO-listed Dutch colonial architecture, dive Curaçao's renowned reef walls, and try the on-site casino. Zoëtry guests can fish, use the swim-up bar, spa, and gym, or venture out to hike the Piton peaks, tour a cocoa estate, or take a sailing trip along St. Lucia's spectacular west coast."},"dreams-curacao-resort-spa-and-casino-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Curaçao and Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia share a $$$ price tier and family positioning, but their ratings tell starkly different stories. Zoëtry outscores Dreams across nearly every category: overall 8.6 vs 6.4, food 8.6 vs 7.0, atmosphere 8.6 vs 6.8, service 9.1 vs 7.3, and cleanliness 9.2 vs 7.8. The one area where Dreams holds an edge is beach, where its 5.3 still beats Zoëtry's exceptionally low 2.5, reflecting Marigot Bay's sheltered marina setting rather than a traditional swim beach. Dreams is a larger, livelier Curaçao resort near Willemstad with a casino, kids club for under-4s, and solid location score of 7.9. Zoëtry is a boutique St. Lucia property tucked into the dramatic scenery of Marigot Bay, with top-tier scores for sleep quality (9.2), rooms (8.8), and value (8.3) that suggest a genuinely refined experience. Dreams suits families wanting a conventional beach-focused Caribbean all-inclusive; Zoëtry suits those prioritizing atmosphere, service, and setting over sand.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with very young children who want a conventional Caribbean all-inclusive near the culture and colour of Willemstad, with a casino for adults, a kids club for under-4s, and a real beach on a laid-back Dutch island that doesn't demand much planning.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with older children or couples who want a boutique St. Lucia all-inclusive with exceptional service (9.1), immaculate rooms (8.8), and the cinematic scenery of Marigot Bay, and who won't miss a traditional beach in exchange for that atmosphere.","whenToVisit":"Curaçao sits outside the hurricane belt, making Dreams a reliable year-round destination with dry, sunny weather peaking December through April. St. Lucia's Marigot Bay is most reliably sunny from January through April; the June–November hurricane season brings higher humidity and rain risk, though Zoëtry's sheltered bay location offers some natural protection.","activities":"Dreams guests can explore Willemstad's UNESCO-listed colonial waterfront, dive Curaçao's renowned reefs, and use the on-site casino. Zoëtry guests have access to the spa, swim-up bar, fishing, and the lush natural scenery of Marigot Bay, with the Piton mountains, rainforest hikes, and sulphur springs of southern St. Lucia all within reach."},"dreams-grand-island-cancun-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Dreams Grand Island Cancun is a large family all-inclusive on Mexico's Costa Mujeres with a kids club for under-4s, no-reservation dining, and strong scores for cleanliness (9.0), service (9.1), and sleep quality (9.0), though its beach rating is modest at 6.1 and food scores only 7.2. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a boutique family all-inclusive tucked into St. Lucia's dramatic Marigot Bay, with a notably higher food rating (8.6 vs 7.2), better atmosphere (8.6 vs 6.9), superior room score (8.8 vs 8.3), and an overall rating of 8.6. The beach at Zoëtry scores a very low 2.5, making it essentially a pool-and-scenery destination rather than a beach resort. Dreams Grand Island wins on location accessibility (8.5) with easy Cancun airport transfers, while Zoëtry commands a premium experience in a lush, intimate Caribbean setting. Both share strong service and cleanliness, but Zoëtry consistently outperforms across food, atmosphere, and rooms at a similar price tier. Choose Dreams for a classic Cancun family beach holiday; choose Zoëtry for boutique St. Lucian scenery and superior dining.","whoShouldChooseA":"Families with very young children who want a large, well-run Cancun all-inclusive with a kids club for under-4s, no-reservation dining, easy airport access, and reliable service and cleanliness on a recognizable Mexican resort strip.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families with older children or couples seeking a boutique St. Lucian all-inclusive in the scenic Marigot Bay setting, where exceptional food, atmospheric surroundings, and high-quality rooms matter more than beach access.","whenToVisit":"Dreams Grand Island Cancun is best visited November through April, avoiding Atlantic hurricane season and peak summer heat. Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is also best from December through April during St. Lucia's dry season. Both resorts sit in the Caribbean basin, sharing similar seasonal rhythms, though St. Lucia's lush landscape means some rainfall year-round regardless of season.","activities":"At Dreams Grand Island Cancun, guests enjoy Cancun's water sports, snorkelling, and nearby Isla Mujeres day trips. At Zoëtry Marigot Bay, guests can fish, use the spa, and explore St. Lucia's rainforest, Piton hikes, and sailing excursions from the bay. Both resorts offer pool access and on-site dining, but Zoëtry's dramatic natural surroundings give it a distinct edge for land-based adventure."},"breathless-puerto-vallarta-resort-and-spa-vs-zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia":{"keyDifferences":"Breathless Puerto Vallarta is an adults-only Mexican all-inclusive on the Pacific coast with a strong location score (8.7) and exceptional room (9.1), cleanliness (9.3), and service (9.2) ratings, but a notably weak beach score (6.5) and modest pool rating (7.0). Zoëtry Marigot Bay St. Lucia is a family-friendly boutique all-inclusive nestled in a rainforest-framed bay in St. Lucia, earning higher marks for food (8.6 vs 7.7), atmosphere (8.6 vs 7.5), sleep quality (9.2 vs 8.5), and room quality (8.8 vs 9.1 narrowly), though its beach score is an even lower 2.5, reflecting its marina-bay setting rather than a traditional beach. Both sit at the same price level, but Breathless skews toward a livelier, social adults-only vibe in a well-connected urban resort corridor, while Zoëtry leans into intimate, nature-immersed seclusion. If you want an energetic adults-only Pacific Mexico resort with outstanding service and rooms, choose Breathless. If you want a quiet, boutique St. Lucia retreat in a dramatic bay setting with superior dining and atmosphere, choose Zoëtry.","whoShouldChooseA":"Adults and couples who want a lively, social all-inclusive in Puerto Vallarta with standout service, immaculate rooms, and easy access to one of Mexico's most vibrant resort towns, and who are not prioritizing a premium beach.","whoShouldChooseB":"Families or couples seeking an intimate, upscale boutique retreat in a stunning St. Lucia bay setting, who value exceptional food, a serene atmosphere, and rainforest surroundings over a traditional beach experience.","whenToVisit":"Puerto Vallarta's dry season runs November through April, making those months ideal for Breathless with reliably sunny skies and calm Pacific waters. St. Lucia's best weather also falls between December and April, when rainfall is lowest and humidity eases. Both destinations see higher rates and more visitors over the Christmas–New Year period. Visiting either resort in late January or February offers good weather with slightly thinner crowds.","activities":"Breathless guests can explore Puerto Vallarta's Malecón boardwalk, Old Town galleries, whale-watching tours (December–March), and Banderas Bay water sports. Zoëtry Marigot Bay offers fishing excursions, spa treatments, and a swim-up bar within its sheltered bay, plus easy access to St. Lucia's landmark Piton hikes, sulphur springs, rainforest zip-lining, and catamaran day sails along the island's scenic west coast."}}
